<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Names     04-09 0881</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Names,0915</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Names in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY14</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KULA, Hawaii (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cher may not win the Best Actress award at
Monday night's Academy Awards, but she already has been rated as
having the best public image among the five nominees.
   Cher was given a 9.9 on a 10-point image scale by Daniel
Eastman, a former Hollywood skin care and makeup expert.
   ``For nine years I have rated the nominees on style,
personality, character, even the way they walk and talk in
public,'' Eastman said. ``A good self and public image is your most
valuable asset, whether you're a waiter, banker, housewife, or
shooting for `Best Actress.'''
   Eastman rated Meryl Streep at 9.7; Glenn Close, 9.5; Sally
Kirkland, 9.2; and Holly Hunter, 9.0.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CONCORD, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The only woman to enter a Jim and Tammy
Bakker lookalike contest walked away with the three top prizes,
including an air-conditioned doghouse.
   Linda Brewer, 43, of High Point won the contest Friday at the
Charlotte Motor Speedway near the former PTL leader's old stomping
grounds, said public relations director Tom Cotter.
   Besides the doghouse _ a replica of the one built for the
Bakkers' pooch _ Brewer also won a trip to Los Vegas and a
gold-plated faucet.
   Although Brewer won by default, she probably would have given
all challengers a good run for the money. Not only did she resemble
Tammy Bakker, she spent two hours Friday morning putting on thick
eyelashes and mascara.
   Brewer, a beauty salon owner, also stuffed sweat socks in her
bra and brought along an onion in a vain effort to force out some
tears.
   ``My mistake was I bought a sweet onion,'' she said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Comedian Robin Williams labeled the
Grande Ole Opry House ``the Sistine Chapel built by Black and
Decker'' and took a jab at the state's portly governor during a
benefit performance for the American Cancer Society.
   Williams, making his first visit to Tennessee, joined Opry star
Minnie Pearl and musicians James Taylor and Amy Grant for the show
Thursday night.
   Williams, the frenetic comedian whose performance in ``Good
Morning, Vietnam'' is nominated for an Oscar, went into the
audience to offer Gov. Ned McWherter some vanilla wafers _ the
governor's favorite snack _ as a peace offering.
   Williams joked that the inlaid section of the Opry stage taken
from the floor of the original Opry, Ryman Auditorium, was a
country music Twilight Zone.
   Stepping onto the inlay, he parodied country lyrics, singing,
``Don't care about atomic emissions, C'mon darlin', let's go
nuclear fission.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>HAARLEM, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Irish playwright Samuel Beckett has
threatened to sue a Dutch actors troupe if it persists in a plan to
stage his play ``Waiting for Godot'' with an all-female cast, the
play's producer said.
   Beckett made the threat two weeks ago in a telegram to the
Theater Barn troupe in this western Dutch city, where the
production of the 1952 play is scheduled to open Thursday, producer
Ina Otten said Friday.
   Beckett gave no reasons for his disapproval in the telegram, Ms.
Otten said. The 82-year old playwright could not immediately be
reached for comment at his French home.
   ``We're putting the play on just the way Beckett says it should
be done, except we're using women,'' Ms. Otten told the Associated
Press. She maintained the play would go ahead as scheduled despite
Beckett's threat.
   ``Wating For Godot,'' which calls for an all-male cast of four,
is an absurdist classic widely regarded as the central metaphors
for the philosophy of existentialism.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>RANCHO MIRAGE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former first lady Betty Ford, still
recovering from heart bypass surgery last year, marked her 70th
birthday with a small party, her secretary said.
   ``Her husband is giving a party for her this evening with a few
friends and family,'' Ann Cullen said Friday.
   Mrs. Ford underwent bypass surgery in November, but returned to
the hospital in December because of complications. She was released
from Eisenhower Medical Center on Jan. 3.
   ``She is feeling very well, taking things a little slowly but
pretty much back to normal,'' Ms. Cullen said.
   Ms. Cullen said Mrs. Ford planned to spend Friday ``sitting at
her desk, working on the day-to-day operation of the Betty Ford
Center,'' a drug and alcohol dependency clinic she founded in 1982.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fawn Hall, who made her television debut
testifying about former boss Oliver North before a Senate
committee, will be co-host of a network special about fashionable
people.
   Miss Hall was chosen ``because she is very spontaneous and has a
presence that is indicative she can handle this kind of assignment
with zest and energy,'' Gary Pudney, an ABC television executive,
said Friday.
   ``M-W Men and Women,'' based upon M and W magazines, will air
the first week in June. Pudney said it is to combine
``Entertainment Tonight,'' ``60 Minutes'' and ``Lifestyles of the
Rich and Famous.''
   The other co-hosts are Ron Reagan, the president's son; actress
Jane Seymour; and Danny Sullivan, the cab-driving Indianapolis 500
winner.
   Miss Hall already has taped her segment for the hourlong show _
an interview with a British heiress who gave it all up to live with
her husband, a Masai warrior, outside of Nairobi, Kenya, in East
Africa.
</TEXT>
