<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Cordovez     04-09 0634</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cordovez,0656</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.N. Mediator: A Latin Mix of Pep and Perseverance</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Saturday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By HANNS NEUERBOURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When others had given up hope that U.N.-sponsored
talks would produce a peace settlement for Afghanistan, Diego
Cordovez wouldn't call it quits.
   ``It has happened that everybody has given up, except myself,''
said Cordovez, an undersecretary-general of the United Nations who
mediated the indirect peace talks between Afghanistan and Pakistan.
   ``Not to give up is my duty,'' said the 52-year-old Ecuadoran
lawyer.
   Cordovez said in an interview that the task of mediating the
talks ``requires tremendous physical and mental strength. You
cannot do it unless you're convinced you will succeed.''
   Success seems within reach with all main elements complete in a
package of agreements designed to end the war. The accord is to be
signed next week.
   Cordovez, the son of Ecuadorean politician Luis Cordovez, has
had a string of other trouble-shooting assignments since he joined
the U.N. system as a 27-year-old law graduate of the University of
Chile.
   In 1965, he was in the Dominican Republic, then in the throes of
a civil war, and he went to Bangladesh shortly after it gained
independence after the 1971 Indo-Pakistan War.
   He was the highest-ranking U.N. official to accompany a special
independent mission to Tehran that failed to resolve the U.S.
hostage crisis in February 1980, and he helped settle a dispute
between Malta and Libya over offshore prospecting rights.
   While the Afghanistan talks were under way, he also was involved
in U.N. efforts to end the Iran-Iraq war and was sent to Grenada
after the 1983 U.S. invasion.
   But none of his assignments has posed more of a challenge than
the Geneva talks.
   Cordovez is credited with avoiding an early collapse of the
Afghan negotiations over the issue of face-to-face talks. Pakistan,
which considers Kabul a Soviet puppet, refused direct talks
although it still has a diplomatic mission in the Afghan capital.
   Pakistan represents the Moslem guerrillas fighting the Communist
government in Kabul, which has been backed by an estimated 115,000
Soviet troops. The Afghan and Pakistani negotiators have not spoken
to each other since the talks were launched six years ago.
   Initially, the delegations took turns meeting with Cordovez.
When the Afghans threatened to leave unless they got more
recognition from the Pakistanis, the U.N. diplomat devised the
``proximity'' formula under which both delegations sit in separate
rooms in the Geneva U.N. office, with Cordovez shuttling between
them.
   ``The satisfaction of getting the adversaries to compromise is
fantastic,'' he said. ``The more difficult the problem, the more I
enjoy it.''
   Although known for taking a tough stance, Cordovez also has a
sense of humor. He says he has been ``cracking jokes all the time''
during his meetings with the two sides.
   ``A sense of humor is absolutely essential in these
negotiations,'' he said. ``A joke can immediately defuse a
situation.''
   Recently, he was seen limping down a corridor. There was no
accident, a bystander was assured. Cordovez was just illustrating
that the talks were ``limping on.''
   Journalists grabbed their pens when he opened a rare news
conference by saying he had an important announcement.
   ``My name is not spelled with an accent over the `o' and if a
newspaper keeps misspelling it, I will cease buying it.''
   Much of his negotiating strength derives from his ability to
leave his work behind on weekends.
   ``People are forbidden to call me at home and I never call my
assistants,'' said Cordovez, who is married with one son.
   He enjoys an occasional Cuban cigar _ sometimes from Fidel
Castro _ good wine and a good meal.
   Cordovez has termed his assignment ``the most exacting and
rewarding in my life.'' But he adds, ``You cannot do such a thing
twice.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
