<1ST_LINE>r a AM-NationalGuard     04-09 0455</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-National Guard,0466</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Hears Arguments In Dispute Over National Guard Training</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER B. DALY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge heard arguments for more than an
hour Friday in a suit by the state of Massachusetts challenging the
authority of federal officials to direct the training of the
National Guard in peacetime.
   U.S. District Court Judge Robert Keeton took the case under
advisement but indicated that he expected to rule promptly.
   Massachusetts Gov. Michael S. Dukakis, a Democratic presidential
candidate who opposes the Reagan administration's policies in
Central America, is resisting Washington's orders sending 13
guardsmen to Panama and Honduras late next month.
   Douglas Wilkins, an assistant state attorney general, argued
that the framers of the U.S. Constitution envisioned ``the
militia'' as a citizens' army, allowing the ``genius of the
people'' to exert a democratic influence over the perils posed by a
large standing army.
   He said that in spite of the National Guard's dual federal-state
status Congress did not have the power to set aside the states'
traditional role in training the militia.
   ``The original militia, at least in these parts, was the
minutemen of Lexington and Concord,'' Wilkins said.
   Massachusetts is asking the federal court to overturn a 1986 act
of Congress known as the Montgomery Amendment that says governors
may not withhold their consent for training assignments outside the
United States because of objections to the location, purpose or
schedule of the training.
   Justice Department lawyer Vincent Garvey argued that Congress,
acting in 1933 under the ``army clause'' of the Constitution,
created the National Guard of the United States. When members of
the militia are serving in their federal status, they are part of
that ``federal entity'' and answerable to Congress and the
president.
   From the bench, Keeton asked several questions about the
``militia clause,'' which clause gives Congress power over
organizing, arming and disciplining the militia, ``reserving to the
states respectively ... the authority of training the militia
according to the discipline prescribed by Congress.''
   If the states are to retain their authority over training, he
asked, how can federal officers order a training mission over a
governor's objection?
   Last year, a federal court in Minnesota rejected a suit brought
by Gov. Rudy Perpich seeking to block his state's National Guard
troops from a similar assignment. That case, which Massachusetts
joined as a ``friend of the court,'' is on appeal.
   In late January, after receiving direct orders from Washington,
Dukakis filed a fresh suit in Boston. Dukakis has said that if he
is faced with a lawful order, he will comply when the 13 members of
the 65th Public Affairs Detachment are scheduled to leave for two
weeks in Panama and Honduras on May 28.
</TEXT>
