<FILEID>AP-NR-04-09-88 0301EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Reagan Bjt   04-09 0594</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Reagan, Bjt,600</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Return Shows Tax Reform Worked To The Reagans' Advantage</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERENCE HUNT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP White House Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTA BARBARA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan has turned out a
winner in the tax-reform law he championed, making more money and
paying less tax last year than he did in 1986.
   The White House on Friday released copies of federal tax return
filed by Reagan and his wife, Nancy. It showed their tax liability
for 1987 was $86,638, or 25.1 percent of their $345,359 gross
income.
   In 1986, their tax bill had been $92,460 on a total income of
$336,640, or 27.5 percent.
   In other words, they made $8,719 more in 1987 than in 1986 but
paid $5,822 less in federal taxes.
   ``Basically, I would conclude that tax reform didn't have too
much of an impact'' on the Reagans, said White House spokesman
Marlin Fitzwater.
   ``It had some effect but not very much,'' Fitzwater added.
   He said he was not aware of any factors other than tax reform
that would have allowed Reagan to pay less tax on more income.
   The sweeping tax reform law, applied for the first time to 1987
returns, eliminated many deductions and lowered tax rates. For the
richest Americans, such as the Reagans, the maximum rate dropped to
38.5 percent last year, down from 50 percent in 1986.
   Reagan had waged an intensive campaign for tax reform, making
speech after speech around the country to prod Congress into
enacting the changes.
   The Reagans' returns provided a glimpse into their private life.
   For example, Mrs. Reagan sold three drawings by Japanese artist
Fojita that she inherited from her mother, the late Edith Luckett
Davis. They sold for $33,000, and were reported as a $31,350
capital gain after deduction of a sales charge.
   The Reagans reduced their reportable charitable contributions,
from $30,487 in 1986 to $25,407 in 1987. The tax return showed
$14,095 were given in cash contributions that were not identified.
Fitzwater said $214 of that amount were donated by Mrs. Reagan to
the Community Foundation of Greater Washington from residuals for
appearing on the television shows, ``Different Strokes'' and ``One
to Grow On.''
   Besides the unidentified cash contributions, Reagan also gave
$11,312 to his alma mater, Eureka College in Illinois. Of that
amount, $1,312 was a fee for appearing on the 25th anniversary of
Johnny Carson's ``Tonight'' show.
   Fitzwater said the contribution total did not include
non-deductible outlays Reagan had made for organ transplant cases
brought to his attention.
   Reagan is still drawing royalties from the autobiography he
wrote years ago, earning $281 last year on ``Where's the Rest of
Me.''
   The Reagans signed their tax returns last Wednesday, well ahead
of the April 15 filing deadline, while vacationing at their
mountaintop ranch. Their returns will be audited by the Internal
Revenue Service, as they are every year, Fitzwater said.
   Indeed, among the $77,792 in deductions claimed by the Reagans
are $32,200 in legal fees, including $7,600 for handling a tax
audit in 1986.
   The Reagans actually are owed a refund for last year since they
prepaid $97,392 in estimated tax payments and withholding. However,
they asked that the $10,754 they are owed be applied to their 1988
tax bill.
   In wages, the Reagans earned $201,526, most of it from his
$200,000 salary. Other major sources of income included $54,178 in
interest and $46,208 in capital gains.
   The blind trust Reagan established when he became president to
keep an arms length from his investments yielded $44,766 of the
interest income he reported. It also provided $319 in dividends.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880409-0012 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-09-88 0239EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Shultz Bjt   04-09 0594</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Shultz, Bjt,590</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shultz On Mideast: ``We'll Keep At It''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Back home after logging 16,000 miles in a
failed effort to get Arabs and Israelis to agree to negotiations,
Secretary of State George P. Shultz says he won't be deterred from
trying again.
   Their reluctance to sign on to a two-stage U.S. proposal for
negotiations, means one deadline has passed and another almost
certainly will go by the boards.
   The first was Shultz's call for a reply by mid-March. Israel and
Jordan, the two key parties, did not turn him down. But they also
did not agree to the talks.
   The second deadline was mid-April, the target date for an
international peace conference. That obviously will not happen,
Shultz said Friday at his last stop in Amman, Jordan.
   Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir simply rejected a
conference in which he feared the Soviet Union might try to impose
terms on Israel.
   Jordan's King Hussein, on the other hand, refuses to sit down
and deal directly with Israel unless the United States, the Soviets
and the three other permanent members of the United Nations
Security Council, China, Britain and France, play an active role.
   China, like the Soviets, has no formal relations with Israel and
invariably backs Arab positions.
   But despite the deadlines passing, Shultz is sticking to his
``time line'' for the negotiations. His plan calls for an
international conference, to please Hussein, but one without much
power, to satisfy Shamir.
   It would be followed in about two weeks by the opening of
negotiations to provide self-rule, but not statehood, to the 1.5
million Palestinian Arabs on the West Bank and in Gaza.
   Then, seven months later, full-scale negotiations would begin on
an overall settlement. To attend, Israel must agree to trade
territory for peace. Jordan, on the other hand, would not be
guaranteed Israel will relinquish all the territories captured in
the Six-Day war of 1967.
   Shultz told the Arabs a total withdrawal was just not ``in the
cards.''
   He also opposed creation of a Palestinian state and stood firm
against participation by the PLO in the talks.
   Shultz has all but acknowledged that even if he can get
negotiations going, he cannot expect an agreement in the little
more than nine months he has left as secretary of state.
   But he refuses to give up, despite the long odds against success.
   ``Who's afraid to struggle against odds?,'' he said Friday in
Amman. ``You have to be willing to do it. What am I saving myself
for anyway?
   ``I've got a few more months to go here and I want to try to
leave something constructive for the region and for my successors.
So I am going to put my back into it, why not?''
   Shultz has made three trips to the region in six months,
measuring the progress in inches.
   In 10 days, he is due to go to Moscow to plan the next
superpower summit meeting. He will have another session with
Foreign Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze in mid-May, and then attend
the summit itself with President Reagan at the end of the month.
   The new nuclear weapons reduction treaty Reagan and General
Secretary Mikhail S. Gorbachev plan to sign is far from ready,
however.
   And there are lots of problems on Shultz's desk, including the
turmoil in Panama and completing an agreement with the Soviet Union
to withdraw the Red Army from Afghanistan.
   But he plans to go back to the Middle East.
   ``I will find the time,'' Shultz said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
