<1ST_LINE>r a AM-TrumpTaxes     04-09 0271</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Trump Taxes,0279</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Trump Gets Tax Break on Mar-A-Lago Estate</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge ruled Friday that real
estate tycoon Donald Trump was entitled to an $86,000 tax break on
Mar-A-Lago after he challenged the county's assessment on the
118-room mansion.
   Circuit Judge Richard Burk ruled Friday that Trump was
responsible for taxes on the 17-acre estate's $7 million purchase
price, rather than an $11.5 million assessment made by the Palm
Beach County Property Appraiser's Office.
   Mar-a-Lago was built in 1926 by cereal heiress Marjorie
Merriweather Post. Trump's purchase in 1985 was the first time the
estate had been sold.
   Robb Maass, Trump's attorney, said Burk's decision was ``a very
proper way of looking at the market value.''
   Gaylord Wood, a Fort Lauderdale attorney who represented Palm
Beach County Property Appraiser Rebecca Walker, said the decision
would be appealed.
   ``Donald Trump has demonstrated once again that there is no one
better in this country at buying things for less than what they are
worth,'' Ms. Wood said.
   Trump challenged the assessment in a 1987 lawsuit after the
county said he owed $208,000 in taxes. Trump contended that the
bill should only be $122,000, including a 4 percent discount for
early payment.
   In a prepared statement, Trump said historic properties such as
Mar-a-Lago are often overassessed, so the ruling constituted a
victory for property owners who have preserved rather than razed
buildings.
   In his ruling, Burk wrote that Trump's $7 million purchase price
established Mar-a-Lago's market value because the estate has no
equal.
   ``Surely in this case, one sale does in fact make a market,''
Burk wrote.
</TEXT>
