<1ST_LINE>r p PM-LouisianaCongress     04-09 0452</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Louisiana Congress,0465</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Heated Campaign Resumes For Seat Vacated By Governor</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN McGILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Democratic candidate for a north
Louisiana congressional seat has returned to the campaign trail
after losing an eye in a car accident, and his Republican opponent
may be as happy as anyone to see him back.
   Foster Campbell, a state senator who suffered other severe
injuries in the accident, faces former congressional aide Jim
McCrery in the April 16 election to fill the seat left vacant when
Buddy Roemer became governor on March 14.
   The winner in the 4th District race will serve only the
remainder of the unexpired term in Congress and must run for
re-election in the fall when all Louisiana congressional seats are
on the ballot.
   Each candidate claims to be the ideological heir of Roemer, a
conservative Democrat who often sided with the Republican
president. They were locked in a close battle before Campbell's
March 13 accident en route to Baton Rouge.
   Campbell's car plunged into a 13-inch-deep hole where workers
had been replacing a section of concrete on Interstate 49. His
right eye was ruptured. His nose, left cheekbone and upper jaw were
broken.
   McCrery scaled back his campaign while Campbell was
recuperating, and Campbell's wife appeared in his place. She proved
to be a personable stand-in for her husband, and McCrery found it
difficult to campaign against her face-to-face.
   ``She doesn't address any issues,'' McCrery complained in an
interview. ``I'm the only one at risk in those situations.''
   Campbell resumed campaigning Thursday night at a fundraiser in
Shreveport. And he said the painful accident had helped his
campaign, citing polls indicating he held a slight advantage over
McCrery.
   ``I think a lot of people view me now as a person who won't
quit,'' he said. With Campbell back in the race, both candidates
resumed the tough campaign tactics they had used before the
accident.
   Campbell immediately accused his opponent of representing ``the
lobbyists and special interests.''
   ``I've been lobbying for good things, not voting for bad
things,'' said McCrery, the former regional manager for government
affairs with Georgia Pacific Corp.
   Then he called Campbell a crony of former Gov. Edwin Edwards,
the once-popular governor who lost a re-election bid to Roemer as
the state's economy declined and rumors of corruption circulated
about the state capital.
   Responded Campbell: ``I voted with Edwin Edwards when he was
right and when he was wrong I voted against him.''
   Campbell noted that McCrery only recently switched from the
Democratic party to the GOP and has never held elective office.
   ``I think Mr. McCrery is a strict opportunist,'' Campbell said.
``We'll see what the voters think about that.''
</TEXT>
