<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Cuomo-California     04-09 0299</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cuomo-California,0306</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Draft-Cuomo Group Loses Suit for Place on California Ballot</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUG WILLIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge refused Friday to place Mario
Cuomo's name on California's June 7 presidential primary ballot,
but Cuomo backers said they would appeal the ruling next week.
   The Draft Cuomo for President Committee filed suit Monday
against Secretary of State March Fong Eu after she ruled that the
New York governor had to be actively seeking the Democratic
nomination to qualify under California law for a place on the
ballot.
   Eu also rejected the estimated 17,000 signatures the committee
had submitted on Cuomo's behalf because they did not meet the
minimum of 500 signatures required from each of California's 45
congressional districts for a candidate to get on the presidential
ballot by petition.
   Paul DeMarco, attorney for the Cuomo committee, argued in
Superior Court Friday that Cuomo's active support of the effort was
not required under a portion of state law that directs Eu to place
on the ballot the names of persons ``generally advocated for the
nomination.''
   But Superior Court Judge Cecily Bond ruled that the section
applied only to people actively seeking the presidential nomination.
   She also rejected DeMarco's argument that the requirement of 500
signatures per congressional district was burdensome, noting that
statewide initiatives routinely qualify for the ballot by petitions
of up to 1 million signatures.
   Eu's attorney, Richard Nishite, said Saturday was the final day
to add or delete anything from the June 7 ballot.
   As certified by Eu, California's Democratic ballot includes the
names of Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis, Sen. Albert Gore, the
Rev. Jesse Jackson, Lyndon LaRouche and Sen. Paul Simon. The names
of Vice President George Bush, Sen. Bob Dole and Pat Robertson will
appear on the Republican ballot.
</TEXT>
