<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Zaccaro     04-09 0480</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Zaccaro,0497</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ferraro's Son Claims He Was Victim of Entrapment</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANICA KIRKA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RUTLAND, Vt. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   John Zaccaro Jr. was a well-organized drug
dealer who was known as ``the Pharmacist,'' a prosecutor said in
the cocaine trial of the son of former vice presidential candidate
Geraldine Ferraro.
   In opening arguments Friday, a defense lawyer for Zaccaro, now
24, conceded that his client had sold cocaine, but said he was
tricked into making the sale by an attractive female agent. The
trial was to continue today.
   Undercover agent Laura Manning, a state police officer,
testified that she went to Zaccaro's apartment during the
Middlebury College Winter Carnival, with instructions to buy a
quarter gram of cocaine.
   Manning testified that Zaccaro was not home when she first went
to his off-campus apartment on Feb. 20, 1986, but he answered the
door when she returned an hour later and said she was looking for
John.
   When asked what she said to Zaccaro, Manning responded, ``I
said, `A couple of people told me that you could sell me some
coke.'''
   ``And what did he say?'' asked Addison County State's Attorney
John Quinn.
   ``Sure,'' Manning quoted Zaccaro as responding. She added, ``He
pulled a tray from under the couch.''
   The tray, Manning said, contained about 15 packets of cocaine in
a plastic bag, with the packets marked by weight.
   Charles Tetzlaff, Zaccaro's lawyer, accused police of entrapment.
   ``The defense will not dispute the allegation that he sold a
regulated drug,'' Tetzlaff said. ``This is a case of improper and
overzealous police conduct.''
   Tetzlaff said ``an attractive female police officer'' who had
never before acted on an undercover assignment entrapped Zaccaro
into making the sale. He said it was Manning _ not Zaccaro _ who
brought up the subject of drugs and a purchase.
   Tetzlaff questioned Manning in detail about what she wore to
Zaccaro's apartment, and whether her jeans were tight and her
jacket open.
   Manning said she was told to dress like a college student. She
said she wore an open jean jacket, a yellow V-neck sweater and
jeans, which were not tight.
   Quinn, the prosecutor, conceded in his opening arguments that
Manning was inexperienced, but he asked jurors to remember the
Middlebury Police Department is a low-budget, small-town operation.
   It was difficult even for police to ``to scrap together $30' for
the drug purchase, he said.
   The prosecutor painted a picture of Zaccaro as a well-organized
drug dealer.
   ``When he takes a packet off the tray, he opens it up, being the
good merchant that he is ... looks at it, wraps it up'' and gives
it to Manning, Quinn said.
   Police began investigating Zaccaro after receiving a note
containing Zaccaro's name, address, car registration and the words:
``The Pharmacist,'' Quinn said. Zaccaro earned the nickname on
campus because of his reputation as a drug dealer, authorities say.
</TEXT>
