<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Iran-Contra 520   04-09 0520</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Iran-Contra, 520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prosecution Fights Defense Claims On Use Of Congressional
Testimony</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Independent Counsel in the Iran-Contra
criminal case is fighting claims that congressional testimony by
three of the defendants is being improperly used against them.
   A court filing made Friday by Lawrence E. Walsh's office denies
a defense charge prosecutors illegally relied on the congressional
testimony given by former national security adviser John M.
Poindexter, Lt. Col. Oliver L. North and arms dealer Albert Hakim.
   ``Defendants' involvement in the activities underlying the
indictment had been fully identified prior to any of their
immunized testimony,'' Walsh's office said in a brief filed by
Herbert J. Stern, a former federal judge hired to handle the
congressional immunity issue.
   ``The government represents that the overwhelming majority of
its case-in-chief will consist of witnesses known to it and
documents obtained or requested by it before any of the defendants
gave immunized testimony,'' the prosecution brief said.
   Walsh's office opposed a defense motion to dismiss the 23-count
indictment on the grounds that prosecutors impermissibly based
their case on the three defendants' congressional testimony, which
was given under grants of limited immunity from prosecution.
   It also urged U.S. District Judge Gerhard A. Gesell to deny the
defense request for a hearing on the congressional immunity issue.
   The defense claims that forcing Poindexter, North and Hakim to
stand trial on charges of conspiring to illegally divert proceeds
of the U.S.-Iran arms sales to the Nicaraguan rebels would violate
their Fifth Amendment protection against self-incrimination because
they were compelled to testify before Congress.
   A fourth defendant, retired Air Force Maj. Gen. Richard V.
Secord, testified at last year's congressional hearings without
such an immunity grant.
   Under the law, Walsh is prohibited from using the congressional
testimony of North, Poindexter and Hakim as evidence against him.
He must also prove that he built his case independently of that
immunized testimony.
   But the prosecution brief argued that any statements North,
Poindexter or Hakim made voluntarily before Congress could be used
as evidence against them in the criminal proceeding.
   ``The immunity statute, like the Fifth Amendment, protects only
compelled disclosures,'' the prosecutor's brief said. ``In
contrast, the privilege does not protect voluntary answers or the
`spontaneous outpouring of testimony.'''
   Without identifying any voluntary statements, the prosecution
offered to forgo introducing such testimony as evidence if Gesell
denies the defense request for what Stern called a ``massive
multi-month'' hearing.
   ``The defendant's request for discovery is testimony to their
intent to use pre-trial proceedings to delay their trial by jury
and obtain unparalleled discovery in a criminal case,'' Stern said.
   Defense lawyers asked to question prosecutors and grand jurors
about whether they learned of the congressional testimony of North,
Poindexter and Hakim. They also want to examine documents to
determine if Walsh relied on the congressional testimony for leads.
   Stern said the prosecution should be allowed to submit for
Gesell's review ``sufficient evidence _ documents and witness
interviews all collected or requested before the immunized
testimony _ to demonstate that it is not unfair to place the
defendants on trial.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
