<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BoyPilot     04-09 0332</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Boy Pilot,0341</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Youngest Pilot On His Way Home</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By OWEN CANFIELD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As the Cessna 210 rolled to a stop at Wiley
Post Airport, the reporters clustered around the pilot's door,
waiting for a word with the daring young aviator at the controls.
   The interviews would have to wait, however. ``I have to go to
the bathroom, first,'' said the 9-year-old pilot, Tony Aliengena.
   Tony, of Orange County, Calif., made his claim for the record
books April 2 when he landed in the Boston area after a
cross-country flight.
   He became the youngest pilot to fly across the continental
United States unaided, beating a 10-year-old's previous
achievement, according to the National Aeronautics Association.
   The youngster made a stop on his way home Friday in Oklahoma
City to refuel and stretch his legs a bit before heading to
Phoenix. ``It was pretty good, a good flight the whole way,'' Tony
said, his braces gleaming.
   Standing about 4-foot-8, Tony uses a car seat to reach the
pedals on the floor of the white and brown plane, which belongs to
his father. Tony is traveling with his flight instructor, a
newspaper reporter and an observer.
   ``He's experienced quite a bit in this week and a half,''
instructor Ed Ferrett said. ``I don't touch anything.''
   The one time he did put his hand on the controls, Ferrett said,
was during a storm near Chattanooga, Tenn., on their way east. ``We
went back and restarted the leg so we could say he flew the whole
way by himself,'' Ferrett said.
   Tony, a third-grader, got his start in aviation through his
father, who used to let the child sit in his lap during takeoffs.
Several months ago he heard about the 10-year-old who set the
record, and told his dad he'd like to try to beat it.
   ``The first time I asked him, he said no,'' Tony said. ``Then I
asked him about a month later and he said OK.''
</TEXT>
