<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Honda     04-09 0249</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Honda,0255</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>One Millionth Car Rolls Off Assembly Line; Hondas Arrive in Japan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MARYSVILLE, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The first shipment of Honda cars made in
the United States rolled onto Japanese soil while the Ohio factory
that produced the exports turned out its one-millionth automobile.
   A shipload of 540 Accords made at Honda of America
Manufacturing's plant in this central Ohio city arrived in Tokyo on
Friday. The cars left Portland, Ore., bound for Japan last month.
   The voyage aboard the U.S.-flagged ship Green Bay was
interrupted when its ballast tank and fuel tank cracked during a
storm in the northern Pacific Ocean on the third day at sea. It
returned to Portland and left again on March 17.
   In Tokyo, Honda spokesman Bret Anderson said the company does
not build the American-made coupe.
   Production was halted for a few minutes shortly after 9 a.m.
Friday on Honda's No. 2 assembly line as a Civic four-door sedan
was driven off the assembly line at the plant which has been
building cars since November 1982.
   Al Kinzer, who became Honda of America's first employee when he
was hired as manager of administration in 1978, drove the car off
the assembly line.
   ``We owe our ability to produce 1 million cars in such a short
period of time to the teamwork and efforts of our (employees),''
said Kinzer, vice president and plant manager of Honda's engine
plant in Anna, Ohio. ``They have proven that Honda quality knows no
geographical boundaries.''
</TEXT>
