<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Turner-Wildlife     04-09 0331</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Turner-Wildlife,0339</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Florida Charges Ted Turner With Wildlife Violations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL KACZOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Florida officials have filed
misdemeanor charges against broadcasting executive Ted Turner, who
they say illegally brought two cougars and three black bears into
the state and released them.
   If convicted, Turner faces a maximum penalty of $500 and 60 days
in jail on each of the three counts of violating Florida wildlife
laws, a spokesman for the Game and Fresh Water Fish Commission said
Friday.
   One of the western cougars was killed March 9 after being struck
by a car near Capps, about 15 miles east of Tallahassee, said Henry
Cabbage, public information supervisor for the commission.
   An investigation led two game officers to Turner's Avalon
Plantation near Capps, the commission said. Turner staffers told
the officers that he had ordered the animals brought from his
plantation in South Carolina and released into the wild at Avalon,
Cabbage said.
   Assistant State Attorney Jim Hintz said he filed two counts of
importing non-native wild animals, one each for the bears and
cougars, and one count of possessing such animals. The charges were
filed March 30 in Monticello.
   A secretary at Turner Broadcasting System headquarters in
Atlanta said he was traveling and unavailable for comment Friday.
She said he received a notice in the mail Wednesday asking him to
come to Florida, but said it didn't state why.
   Hintz said Turner wouldn't be arrested, but would be served with
a summons asking him to appear or be represented by counsel at a
May 4 arraignment.
   Turner applied for a permit last year to move the bears from
South Carolina and release them on his Florida property, but it was
denied, Cabbage said. No permit had been sought for the cougars.
   Game officials will try to capture the other cougar, but the
bears will be allowed to roam free because it would be impossible
to distinguish Turner's bears from native black bears, Cabbage said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
