<1ST_LINE>r p PM-PoliticalRdp Bjt   04-09 0615</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Political Rdp, Bjt,630</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis, Gore Sound Anti-Drug Theme; Jackson Courts Jewish Vote</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NANCY BENAC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Presidential contenders Michael Dukakis and Albert Gore Jr. both
are sounding anti-drug themes as they battle for Democratic support
in New York, while Jesse Jackson tries to make peace with the
state's Jewish voters.
   But while Jackson said Friday his campaign would ``continue to
heal relationships'' with the Jewish community, aides said he won't
have time to meet with Jewish leaders concerned that he is
anti-Israel.
   In the Republican race, meanwhile, Vice President George Bush
hit the campaign trail Friday for the first time since Bob Dole
quit the race and Pat Robertson switched his campaign into low gear.
   On a visit to Fort Worth, Texas, Bush said he was delighted with
the slim competition he faces for Republican delegates and
``wouldn't trade'' places with the three Democrats scrambling for
their party's nomination.
   Nevertheless, he said he wasn't banking on Democratic infighting
to pave his way to the Oval Office.
   ``I wish I thought the Democrats would have a unity problem but
I don't think they will,'' Bush said. ``I'm not counting on the
blood on the floor that exists at this moment to carry over and
cause the Democrats to hemorrhage to death.''
   Back in New York, Jackson campaign aide Gerald Austin said his
boss would not accept a request to meet with the Jewish Community
Relations Council because ``we've already answered all these
questions. I don't see why we have to go to a meeting to answer all
the questions again.''
   The questions revolve around Jackson's use of the phrase
``Hymietown'' during his 1984 campaign, his past association with
Nation of Islam leader Louis Farrakhan, who has called Judaism a
``gutter religion,'' and his closeness to the Palestinian cause.
   Jackson himself had plenty of conciliatory words for Jewish
voters as he campaigned across New York and Long Island in advance
of the state's April 19 primary.
   Visiting the posh Sardi's restaurant in Manhattan, Jackson
recalled the days when ``it was commonplace to see signs that said
`blacks and Jews and dogs are not welcome.'''
   ``Our commitment is to end any vestiges of racism, of
anti-Semitism, or sexism,'' he said. ``We've sent a message no one
can miss.''
   Dukakis and Gore, meanwhile, both had harsh words for the
effectiveness of the Reagan administration's anti-drug efforts, and
pledged to do better if elected.
   Speaking at a senior citizens center on Long Island, Dukakis
promised he'd ``wage a real war, not a phony war, on drugs.''
   ``In Latin America, the gravest threat to our security comes not
from the Sandinistas, but from drugs,'' the Massachusetts governor
said earlier in a speech at St. John's University.
   Gore was advancing a similar theme.
   ``The administration declared a war against drugs and drugs
won,'' the Tennessee senator told an audience on Long Island.
``They've got to say yes to funding for drug programs.''
   The 255 Democratic delegates at stake in New York's primary make
the state a crucial battleground for Dukakis, Jackson and Gore.
None thus far are close to the 2,082 delegates needed to gain the
Democratic nomination.
   Dukakis holds a slight lead, with 745.05 delegates, compared
with Jackson's 708.55, and Gore's 395.8. Illinois Sen. Paul Simon,
with 171.5 delegates, remains on the candidates' roster, but has
suspended all campaign activities.
   New York Gov. Mario Cuomo, whose endorsement has been courted
unsuccessfully by the Democratic candidates, revealed he'd already
voted by absentee ballot for one of the contenders, but refused to
say which one.
   Cuomo said he was discussing making campaign appearances for all
three active Democratic candidates, as time permits.
   ``I'll go anywhere with them,'' he said.
</TEXT>
