<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ChicagoProbe     04-09 0308</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Chicago Probe,0316</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prosecutor Says Davis Sentence Should Serve as Warning</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES LITKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The 8{-year prison term given a former alderman
convicted of extortion and racketeering, should warning others that
corruption by public officials will be punished severely, a federal
prosecutor says.
   ``Today was his turn to pay,'' Assistant U.S. Attorney Michael
Shepard said after former alderman Wallace Davis, 36, was sentenced
Friday. ``It should serve as a lesson to people in his position.''
   A federal jury found Davis guilty Oct. 12 of racketeering,
extortion, attempted extortion and lying to an FBI agent during the
government's Operation Incubator probe of City Hall corruption.
   Shepard said Davis had amassed an ``amazing record of corruption
for someone just starting out in public office,'' extorting money
from small businesses in his impoverished ward and accepting bribes
from an FBI informant seeking lucrative city contracts.
   Shepard told U.S. District Judge Ann Williams on Friday that one
of Davis' schemes involved putting his niece on the city payroll
and then demanding that she kick back part of her salary.
   Davis, clenching and unclenching his hands behind his back,
stood silently before Ms. Williams.
   Defense attorney Paul Bradley said he would appeal Davis'
sentence.
   Davis' conviction came three months after he was acquitted of
charges that he had beaten and pistol-whipped a former secretary
over her cooperation with federal investigators in the Operation
Incubator probe.
   Davis narrowly lost a re-election bid in April 1987 in a
campaign he ran from his cell. He was indicted in December 1986 on
the federal corruption charges and in February on state charges in
the pistol-whipping case.
   Shepard and Assistant U.S. Attorney Howard Pearl said Davis
accepted $5,000 from informant Michael Raymond, representing a New
York company trying to land a multimillion dollar city contract to
collect unpaid parking tickets.
</TEXT>
