<2ND_LINE>PM-Washington in Brief,570</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Plastic Bottles To Carry Codes To Promote Recycling</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The plastics industry is hoping to encourage
recycling of the bottles it makes by marking containers with code
numbers that designate the kind of plastic used.
   The Council on Plastics and Packaging in the Environment said
Friday that bottles soon will carry a single-digit number inside a
triangle to help guide recyclers.
   The council called a news conference to present its view that
trash disposal should make room for recycling, incineration,
landfilling and composting.
   The voluntary identification system devised by the Society of
the Plastics Industry calls for number codes on all plastic bottles
of 16 ounces or larger, and other containers of 8 ounces or more.
Almost all recycling markets are designed to handle one kind of
plastic at a time, though various efforts are under way to develop
techniques to separate mixed plastics.
</TEXT>
