<HEAD>Capitol ``Slammer'' Gets Official Who Had It Installed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The official who recommended the installation
of barricades to protect the Capitol from terrorists was himself
injured when his government car struck one of the so-called
``slammers.''
   Officer Dan Nichols of the Capitol police force said Capitol
architect George White, who is responsible for the Capitol's
buildings and grounds, was treated Friday by Capitol physicians,
along with a driver who also received minor injuries.
   Nichols said White's car struck the mechancial barrier at the
south entrance to the Capitol Plaza as the slammer was being
lowered to allow entry.
   ``Preliminarily, it looks like driver error,'' said Nichols,
adding that the investigation was continuing.
   White, a passenger in the back seat, disagreed with that
assessment. He said he thought the barrier had been lowered and
then rose unexpectedly, either because of a mechanical malfunction
or a barrier-keeper pushing the wrong button.
