<HEAD>New Law Allows Federal Employees To Donate Leave to Bosses</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTA BARBARA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new law allows federal employees
to donate annual leave time to superiors who need prolonged, unpaid
absences from work for medical or family emergencies.
   There is a statutory ban on gifts from federal workers to their
superiors, which could have prevented some officials from
benefiting from leave-transfer programs. President Reagan on Friday
signed legislation to allow such transfers.
   It was also announced Friday that Reagan signed into law an
18-month extension of the deadline for filing civil actions
alleging age discrimination for certain claims filed with the Equal
Employment Opportunity Commission.
   The bill was passed in response to the failure of the EEOC to
act in a timely manner on about 1,200 complaints that were properly
filed.
