<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>3-Cent Stamp Sales Swamp Some Post Offices</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Postal Service is working to refill
depleted inventories of 3-cent stamps at some post offices.
   The stamps are in high demand because they make up the
difference between the old rate of 22 cents for a first-class
letter and the new price of 25 cents.
   ``The stamps are out there, but some offices have a lot more
than others,'' spokeswoman Tanya Perkins said Friday.
   More than 1 billion 3-cent stamps were sent to local post
offices in preparation for the rate change last Sunday, Perkins
said. Another 600 million of the 3-cent stamps are in warehouses,
being used to replenish stocks where needed, she said.
   ``We had asked local offices to predict how many they would
need, and some had a lot more demand than expected. We've been
filling orders all week,'' Perkins said.
