<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Namibia     04-09 0484</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Namibia,0503</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>South Africa Tightens Powers Over Neighboring Territory</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   WINDHOEK, South-West Africa (AP) _ President P.W. Botha decreed
broadened powers for his chief representative in this
Pretoria-ruled territory, insisting the rights of whites and other
minorities must be protected.
   The official, Administrator-General Louis Pienaar, will be
empowered to take action against ``subversive'' media, arrange for
regional or racially based elections and refer certain major court
rulings to South Africa's appellate court.
   Cabinet ministers complained that the new powers, announced by
Botha Friday during a visit to Windhoek, amounted to greater South
African intervention in the affairs of this territory alsk known as
Namibia.
   Botha, after a three-hour meeting with the territory's
multi-racial Cabinet, also indicated he might accept proposals to
eliminate most racially segregated political structures.
   Finance Minister Dirk Mudge, a white moderate, said he hoped
Pienaar would consult with the Cabinet rather than acting
singlehandedly to perpetuate a whites-only political structure.
   Also Friday, Archbishop Desmond Tutu flew with other Anglican
bishops to the territory's northern region of Ovambo.
   Tutu, an outspoken critic of Botha and South Africa's system of
apartheid, spoke to 1,500 exuberent worshippers at a war-damaged
mission center near the Angolan border.
   In Windhoek, more than 100 supporters of the South-West African
People's Organization staged an anti-Botha demonstration outside a
downtown hotel, holding up placards with slogans such as ``Stop
Sucking Our Blood'' and ``Take Your Puppet Government to Pretoria.''
   SWAPO, which has been waging a guerrilla war against South
African rule for 22 years, claims overwhelming support in Ovambo,
home of 55 percent of Namibia's people.
   Niko Bessinger, an official of SWAPO's legal political wing,
said Botha was manipulating the territorial Cabinet as part of a
``divide and rule'' strategy aimed at avoiding one-man, one-vote
national elections.
   Pienaar said it was virtually certain the interim government
Botha installed in 1985 would be allowed to repeal a controversial
1980 proclamation that establishes 11 ethnically based second-tier
governments in Namibia.
   Blacks, who make up 88 percent of Namibia's 1.3 million people,
complain the system provides disproportionate benefits for the
white and mixed-race communities, each of which makes up 6 percent
of the population.
   Pienaar said the 1980 proclamation would be repealed only when
provisions were adopted to ensure that the cultural and linguistic
rights of minorities were protected.
   The interim government favors total repeal of apartheid-style
laws, but a white and mixed-race party supports retention of
racially segregated structures.
   Botha reiterated that South Africa will not agree to the U.N.
call for Namibian independence until all Cuban troops withdraw from
neighboring, Marxist-ruled Angola.
   Namibia is the main staging point for South African troops who
are fighting in Angola in support of rebels.
   Apartheid establishes a racially segregated society in which the
26 million blacks have no vote in national affairs. The 5 million
whites control the economy and maintain separate districts, schools
and health services.
</TEXT>
