<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Nicaragua     04-09 0547</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nicaragua,0569</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Military Talks Suspended, Sandinistas Call Contras Intransigent</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RODOLFO GARCIA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Negotiators suspended talks on setting
up Contra rebel cease-fire zones, with the Sandinistas calling the
rebels intransigent for demanding they be allowed to receive
military supplies inside the zones.
   Military leaders of the two sides met six times in the southern
border town of Sapoa to negotiate precise locations, sizes, and
rules governing conduct inside the zones.
   A preliminary peace agreement signed March 23 by Sandinista and
Contra leaders calls for the U.S.-supported rebel fighters to
gather inside the zones by April 15.
   But the Contra military delegation abruptly abandoned Friday's
meeting and immediately left in vehicles for the Costa Rican border
without comment.
   Maj. Gen. Joaquin Cuadra, head of the Sandinista delegation,
termed Friday's talks ``very serious'' and said rebel negotiators
had been intransigent in demanding they be allowed to maintain
military supplies inside their zones.
   The Sapoa peace accord permits humanitarian assistance to the
rebels, to be administered by a neutral international organization.
   Cuadra said the technical talks would be resumed alongside
high-level negotiations between the Sandinistas and the Nicaraguan
Resistance, the Contra umbrella group, next Friday in Managua.
   They will try to negotiate a permanent end to the war, which has
killed more than 40,000. A 60-day cease-fire went into effect April
1.
   Cuadra said the rebel technical delegation ``didn't have
sufficient authority'' to respond to a 25-point government proposal
outlining Contra activity inside the zones. The proposal addressed
food assistance to the rebels and verification procedures.
   Cuadra said the government proposal was based on the Sapoa
accords and the Central American peace plan signed by the region's
five presidents Aug. 7.
   The Contra team had proposed its own 34-point plan on Thursday.
   Among other conditions, it demanded the rebels be allowed to
receive military assistance, recover military supplies and maintain
a munitions stock, and have access to air delivery of necessary
supplies.
   Cuadra dismissed the rebel proposal as seeking ``to violate the
sovereign rights of the Nicaraguan republic.''
   On Thursday, the two sides had agreed on defining the location
of seven Contra zones.
   Cuadra said he hoped negotiators could resolve outstanding
differences at the April 15 meeting.
   President Daniel Ortega was quoted in newspapers Friday as
saying the Contras signed the preliminary accord because they had
been defeated militarily after nearly seven years of war and
``never held an inch of territory.''
   The Sandinista newspaper Barricada said the president explained
that the Contras would move into the zones, lay down their weapons
and return to civilian life.
   But the Contras say they will never put down their weapons until
Nicaragua is ``on an irreversible road to democracy.''
   In Copenhagen, Denmark, on Friday, a Sandinista official,
Commandant Victor Tirado, told a news conference that the
Sandinista government is dissatisfied with the way the truce is
taking shape.
   ``We cannot be satisfied with developments the past few days,''
he said. ``The Contras took part in setting the dates for the
cease-fire, and then they start breaking the accord themselves.''
   Tirado is one of the nine commanders of the ruling Sandinista
National Liberation Front.
   Tirado was in Denmark for a conference on Central America
organized by the Danish Social Democratic Party and the trade union
congress.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880409-0034 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-09-88 0602EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Demjanjuk-Citizenship     04-09 0389</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Demjanjuk-Citizenship,0400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Demjanjuk Files Suit Seeking to Restore Citizenship</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEPHANIE NANO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   John Demjanjuk, a retired auto worker awaiting
a verdict in Israel on charges that he committed war crimes as a
Nazi death camp guard during World War II, has filed a lawsuit to
regain his U.S. citizenship.
   Demjanjuk, who lost his citizenship in 1981, alleges in the suit
filed Friday in U.S. District Court that the Justice Department's
Office of Special Investigations withheld evidence that would have
helped prove his innocence.
   A federal judge ruled that Demjanjuk lied to conceal from U.S.
authorities his alleged past as the brutal guard Ivan the Terrible
at the Treblinka death camp in Nazi-occupied Poland.
   Demjanjuk, 68, was extradited in 1986 to Israel. He had lived in
the Cleveland suburb of Seven Hills.
   ``We've acquired documents through unknown sources that really
lay out, plain and clear, what OSI's intentions were from the
beginning _ that they did not believe Mr. Demjanjuk was in fact
Ivan the Terrible and they went ahead and prosecuted him and
suppressed the evidence that would help him prove his case,'' said
Ed Nishnic, Demjanjuk's son-in-law.
   Justice Department spokesman John Russell said Demjanjuk has
been unsuccessful in a number of appeals in the case ``and we will
respond in court to the present suit.''
   The Ukrainian-born Demjanjuk says he's a victim of mistaken
identity and was never at the Treblinka camp. Demjanjuk has
admitted lying on his immigration papers, but says he did so
because he feared execution if he returned to the Soviet Union
after the war.
   Demjanjuk says he served in the Soviet Army, was captured by the
Germans in 1941 and remained in prisoner-of-war camps until 1943.
He claims he was not at Treblinka, as alleged, in 1942 and 1943.
   The Israeli judges are expected to render a verdict April 18.
   The case to recover his citizenship is based on material
obtained through the Freedom Of Information Act and Justice
Department documents sent anonymously to the family.
   According to Demjanjuk's suit, government investigators
interviewed 71 people but only disclosed the existence of 31
interviews to defense attorneys and released only 11 statements.
   The suit also alleges that the government failed to reveal that
most of the people interviewed failed to identify Demjanjuk or
their identification was flawed.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
