<FILEID>AP-NR-04-09-88 0616EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Israel-Settlers     04-09 0730</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel-Settlers,0754</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Many Fear Girl's Death May Signal Start Of Bloodier Conflict</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MASHA HAMILTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ELON MOREH, Occupied West Bank (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Israeli girl's death in
a clash with Arabs was a watershed in four months of violence,
radicalizing Jewish settlers. Many fear it presages a more savage
conflict in the occupied lands.
   The killing of Tirza Porat on Wednesday shocked the nation, but
the general feeling had been that it was only a matter of time
before a Jew living in these disputed hills would die because of
the Arab rebellion.
   Ironically, Israeli media reported Friday that it was likely the
girl was slain by a bullet fired from the rifle of a Jewish settler
guarding her, and not by a rock flung by an Arab as the army
previously reported.
   The reports said the guard may have inadvertantly fired on Tirza.
   Still, many settlers blamed their government _ accusing it of
creating an atmosphere of leniency toward Arabs that made the
confrontation possible.
   One of the sorest points to the 850,000 Arabs in the West Bank,
which they call ``occupied Palestine,'' is the presence of 65,000
Jewish settlers in the land Israel calls by the biblical names
Judea and Samaria.
   The Israelis have ruled the West Bank and Gaza Strip since
capturing them from Jordan and Egypt in the 1967 Middle East war.
   ``Israel is a castrated giant, afraid to deport Arabs, afraid to
really punish rioters,'' said Eliakim Haetzni, a lawyer and leader
in the Kiryat Arba settlement.
   ``We've reached the point where the last Arab urchin in the last
alley in the last refugee camp is no longer afraid of our
government or our army, so of course they attack Jewish children,''
he told The Associated Press.
   Benny Katzover, head of the settlement council, said: ``If our
leaders don't take steps to stop the Arabs now, they will not be
able to stop Jews from taking things in their own hands.''
   Palestinians fear that. ``Now settlers will retaliate against
Palestinians everywhere,'' said Mubarak Awad, an Arab-American who
advocates non-violent resistance.
   ``Soon the army will have to make a decision about who is
running the show. If it is the settlers, that means there will be
more killings on both sides.''
   Jewish settlers enraged by Tirza's death raided Arab villages
under cover of night, beating Palestinians and smashing windows of
Arab-owned homes and cars near the settlements of Kiryat Arba and
Elon Moreh, where the girl lived.
   Tirza, 15, and other teen-agers from Elon Moreh were on a
Passover holiday hike, accompanied by two adult guards. They
encountered stone-throwing Palestinians and were led to Beita,
where the fatal clash occurred.
   Two Arabs also were killed and 141 have died since violence
began in the occupied territories Dec. 8, according to U.N.
figures. One Israeli soldier was stabbed to death but Tirza is the
first Israeli citizen killed.
   Settlers carried guns at her funeral on a West Bank hillside at
midday Thursday. Some shouted ``Revenge! Revenge!'' despite
admonitions from a rabbi, who said over a loudspeaker that such
disruptions were out of place.
   The death of the teen-ager appalled Israelis. Many demanded that
the Arabs of Beita be punished, but others said the were dragging
the country deeper into its war with the Palestinians.
   ``This will mean the start of a cycle of bloodshed that will be
difficult to end,'' the left-wing daily Hadashot declared.
   ``If you cannot enforce a stronger policy, Mr. prime minister,
our next meeting will again be in a cemetery,'' Hanan Porat, a
settler leader who is not related to Tirza, told Yitzhak Shamir at
the girl's funeral.
   Some Israelis asked why Jewish children were hiking in the West
Bank hills at a time of such trouble.
   One hiker, her head bandaged, explained from her hospital bed:
``We have to show them that we are the owners of the country.''
   Her party made one mistake, she said: ``It wasn't good that we
had only two guns.'' She spoke on television and was not identified
by name.
   Requests for gun permits have increased by 50 percent since
December, mostly from Israelis in the occupied territories and
Jerusalem, the daily Al Hamishmar reported.
   According to Moshe Weiss of the Interior Ministry, about 200,000
Israelis own private weapons. Both parents and the older children
in many West Bank homes are getting permits.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
