<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Philippines-Priest 1stLd-Writethru   04-09 0392</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Philippines-Priest, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0480,0401</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Militiaman Kills American Priest</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 4 grafs to UPDATE with Ramos ordering an
investigation; picks up 4th pvs, `It said ...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A tribal militiaman gunned down a
70-year-old Roman Catholic priest from Chicago in the southern
Philippines after accusing the clergyman of harboring criminals,
the military reported today.
   Defense Secretary Fidel Ramos today ordered an investigation in
the killing of the Rev. Carl Schmitz, including the possibility
that religious differences may have played a role. He did not
elaborate.
   In Chicago, a church official said he was told the priest was
slain because he had refused to employ the killer's wife.
   A military report said the Schmitz died Thursday from multiple
gunshot wounds from a .30-caliber Garand rifle during the attack
inside his convent in Koronadal, a provincial capital 620 miles
south of Manila.
   It said Schmitz was slain by Saguin Munday, 29, a teacher and
head of the local government militia, after a heated argument over
the priest's willingness to give sanctuary to wanted tribal
criminals.
   Munday, a B'laan tribesman, surrendered to police authorities
after the slaying.
   Schmitz did missonary work in Japan before being assigned to the
Philippines in 1974. He was the head of the Notre Dame of Marbel
Colleges, a missionary school for the minority B'laan tribe.
   Manila newspapers gave differing accounts on Schmitz's killing.
   The Philippine Inquirer said Schmitz had punched Munday during
the confrontation, prompting the militiaman to shoot the priest.
The Manila Bulletin, quoting a military report, said the priest
allegedly turned down the wife of Munday who was applying for a
teaching job in the school.
   In another account, the Daily Globe said Munday barged into the
Convent of the Passion and without saying a word gunned down the
priest.
   Today's edition of the Chicago Tribune quoted Rev. Sebastian
MacDonald, provincial superior of the Passionist Community, as
saying priests in Manila told him Schmitz was killed by the husband
of a woman who had been refused a teaching job at the missionary
school.
   ``We are going to petition the Filipino government to set up an
investigative committee to explore the facts and clear his name of
any smear,'' MacDonald was quoted as saying.
   Schmitz also served a missionary in China in the late 1940s but
was expelled during the communist takeover.
</TEXT>
