<DOCNO> AP880409-0044 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-09-88 0657EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SriLanka     04-09 0402</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sri Lanka,0416</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>14 Sinhalese Villagers Massacred</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEXTER CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Separatist Tamil rebels stopped 14
Sinhalese villagers on a road in northern Sri Lanka and massacred
them, military officials said today.
   Also, a senior police official said detectives had arrested a
Sinhalese man believed responsible for an attempt to assassinate
President Junius R. Jayewardene in Parliament last August.
   The rebel slayings took place Friday evening, when villagers on
bicycles and in a truck were stopped near the town of Anuradhapura,
about 100 miles northeast of Colombo, said the officials, who spoke
on condition of anonymity.
   They did not elaborate on the slayings.
   The latest killings raised to at least 147 the number of
villagers slain in northern Sri Lanka since March 2. Most of the
victims have been members of the island's majority Sinhalese
community.
   But at least 22 members of the minority Tamil community were
killed in a revenge attack blamed on Sinhalese March 11, and 17
Moslems died in a raid blamed on Tamil separatists March 31.
   Frank Silva, director of the national Criminal Investigation
Department, said the ``the main suspect in the Parliament grenade
attack'' was arrested Friday at the village of Naula, 68 miles
northeast of Colombo.
   He was identified as Ajith Kumara, 28.
   One lawmaker and a clerk were killed and several people were
injured Aug. 18, when two hand grenades were thrown into a
conference room where Jayewardene was presiding over a meeting of
Cabinet ministers and Parliament members.
   The attack occurred shortly after India and Sri Lanka signed a
peace accord July 29 aimed at ending the Tamil minority's
4-year-old guerrilla war for an independent homeland in the north
and east of the island.
   The accord was opposed by many in the majority Sinhalese
community, who felt it made too many concessions to the Tamils. The
largest of the Tamil rebel groups, the Liberation Tigers of Tamil
Eelam, also has rejected the pact.
   India now has more than 50,000 troops on the island to try to
contain the Tigers' rebellion.
   Tamils, who are mostly Hindus, make up about 18 percent of Sri
Lanka's 16 million population. They claim they are discriminated
against by the Sinhalese, who control the government and military.
   India has become involved because it has an estimated 60 million
ethnic Tamils in its southern states who are sympathetic to the Sri
Lankan Tamils.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880409-0045 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-09-88 0713EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>d a PM-ParentsShot     04-09 0187</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Parents Shot,0189</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Teen-ager Charged In Shooting of Parents</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CLAYTON, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 17-year-old accused of shooting her
parents in bed as part of a plot with her younger brother has been
arrested in Indiana, authorities said.
   Tammy Norris of St. Louis was stopped Friday evening about 40
miles southeast of Indianapolis, police said. She was held on
$100,000 bond in the Decatur County Jail.
   Her parents were not seriously wounded in the shooting early
Friday. Her father, Charles Norris, was shot once with a
.22-caliber rifle as he lay in bed. The bullet went through his
shoulder, then grazed the ear and cheek of Ellen Norris, police
said.
   The teen-ager apparently was angry with her parents because they
had disciplined her brother for failing to clean up the basement,
said Sgt. Ted Zinselmeier of St. Louis County's crimes against
persons unit.
   Miss Norris was charged Friday with two counts of first-degree
assault, two counts of armed criminal action and one count of
automobile theft in warrants issued by the St. Louis County Circuit
Court. Her 16-year-old brother was taken into custody by juvenile
authorities.
</TEXT>
