<1ST_LINE>r a PM-StudentProtest 1stLd-Writethru a0473 04-09 0646</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Student Protest, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0473,0663</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>91 Protesters Arrested At Penn State</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 13 grafs to UPDATE with arrests. Picks up 7th graf
pvs, `This fall ....' Millar in 15th graf is cq.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID S. MARTIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STATE COLLEGE, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police this morning arrested 91
protesters staging a sit-in at a Penn State building, ending a
15-hour impasse over a canceled meeting with university officials
on minority issues.
   ``I think it's a terrible message to send to the students, when
the president of this university would rather send state troopers
to meet with them than come himself,'' said Seth Williams, who is
president of the student government.
   Williams, one of more than 150 students who occupied the
university's Telecommunications Building overnight, said he was
cited for defiant trespass.
   David Stormer, director of university safety, said most students
were charged with summary trespass, while some faced disorderly
conduct charges.
   ``It was a very peaceful demonstration,'' he said.
   More than 75 police officers from university, State College and
state police took part in the arrests.
   The university had obtained an injunction Friday in Centre
County Court, ordering the students to leave the building.
   Students were arrested individually, issued yellow citation
slips and released, receiving cheers and hugs from their friends
outside a police cordon around the building.
   Stormer said about 130 people were in the building just before
the arrests, but many left rather than face criminal charges.
   The students, most of them black, began the protest Friday after
a meeting between student leaders and school administrators failed
to agree on ground rules for another session to discuss minority
issues.
   The university canceled a similar meeting Friday after officials
said they couldn't reach student leaders who had demanded the
meeting to end an earlier sit-in outside the office of Penn State
President Bryce Jordan.
   ``We're going to do it, folks. Ain't no stopping us now,'' said
Darryl King, a senior from Philadelphia and past president of the
Black Caucus, a student organization.
   Robert Blair, a spokesman for the Black Caucus, said minority
students should have a voice in programs at the university that
affect them and criticized Penn State for failing to meet a
court-mandated goal for black enrollment.
   This fall, Penn State failed to reach a 5 percent black
enrollment, which the university agreed to under court order. Penn
State has a 3.6 percent black enrollment, which equals 2,424 black
students.
   Late Friday night, Craig Millar, assistant vice president for
student services, told the protesters that they would be violating
Penn State's code of conduct if they remained and could be subject
to dismissal from the university.
   He also said they could face criminal charges of disorderly
conduct, harassment and trespassing. ``Your point has been made and
we are please asking you to leave,'' Millar said.
   Outside the building half a dozen students slept in sleeping
bags, while others huddled under blankets in the 37-degree chill.
   King said they would occupy the building until they're arrested
or their demand is met for a meeting with Jordan and other
university officials. ``Right now we will be in this place until
whatever happens,'' he said.
   Jordan had agreed Tuesday to convene the canceled meeting to end
an earlier sit-in outside his office by nine black students and a
local pastor.
   Carol A. Cartwright, chairman of the Equal Opportunity Planning
Committee, said the university had offered to set up a meeting
Friday night outside the building to plan a forum next week on
minority issues. The offer was rejected.
   ``We need to make it clear we have made very serious offers,''
Cartwright said. ``We are willing to have a dialogue, but we're not
willing to let students occupy buildings and get this accomplished
this way.''
   Student leaders said they didn't trust the university to keep
its word once they left the building.
</TEXT>
