<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Panama     04-09 0454</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Panama,0467</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Impact Of New U.S. Economic Sanctions Studied</HEAD>
<HEAD>With US-Panama, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOSEPH B. FRAZIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An American businessman described new
U.S. sanctions against Panama as futile and said they gave Gen.
Manuel Antonio Noriega the opportunity to shut down American firms
there.
   ``The U.S. has very little to say in this situation as far as
preventing U.S. companies from deciding whether or not to pay taxes
in Panama. If you don't pay, your right to operate here can be
taken away,'' said the manager of a U.S. franchise in Panama,
speaking on condition of anonymity.
   President Reagan ordered the new sanctions, which prohibit all
payments by American citizens and organizations in the United
States and Panama to the Noriega government. The ban specifically
includes branches and subsidiaries of American companies.
   The sanctions come after Texaco, Eastern Airlines and other U.S.
firms paid more than $5 million in taxes and fees to the Noriega
government for doing business in Panama.
   The United States previously had stopped paying monthly toll
fees to the Panama Canal Commission and had frozen government
deposits in American banks.
   Noriega, head of Panama's 15,000-member Defense Forces and the
power behind the civilian government, is under indictment in the
United States on drug trafficking charges. The United States has
called upon the general to step down.
   Don Halman, manager of the General Mills operation in Panama,
said he believed the sanctions would not apply to his company.
   While the local General Mills operation is partly
American-owned, he said, ``It is a Panamanian corporation with
Panamanian shareholders. I would not think that it could apply to
us.''
   The U.S. Embassy said tax payments by U.S. firms should be
directed to an escrow account set up by the Federal Reserve Bank in
New York for deposed President Eric Arturo Delvalle. Noriega forced
Delvalle from office after Delvalle tried to fire the general on
Feb. 25.
   The United States recognizes Delvalle as Panama's legitimate
president.
   There are 190 members of the U.S. Chamber of Commerce in Panama,
but many are franchises of American firms and operate as Panamanian
corporations.
   All businesses in Panama, including U.S. firms, must pay social
security taxes, workers' compensation, value-added and other taxes,
according to a U.S. businessman who has been in the country more
than 15 years.
   ``If you do business in a country you have to obey the laws of
that country,'' said the businessman, who added that the sanctions
gave Noriega an excuse to seize U.S. businesses.
   The shortage of dollars, Panama's official currency, has kept
banks closed since March 3 and prevented the government from paying
130,000 public employees and 15,000 troops for more than a month.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
