<1ST_LINE>r i PM-China-Congress 1stLd-Writethru a0443 04-09 0719</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-China-Congress, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0443,0736</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Li Peng Elected Premier, Government Reorganization Approved</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after 14th graf pvs, ``Zhao has ... to UPDATE
with military commission members chosen. Picks up 15th graf pvs,
``Ren Jianxin ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KATHY WILHELM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China's legislature today approved Li Peng as
premier and endorsed a reorganization plan that intends to make the
government a leaner, more efficient instrument for promoting
economic development.
   Li, a Moscow-educated technocrat, has been acting premier for
five months.
   One National People's Congress delegate voted against the
reorganization of state ministries and top-level commissions, which
was approved by a show of hands of the 2,877 delegates attending in
the Great Hall of the People. One delegate abstained.
   A key component of the reorganization, the merger of China's
railway and communications ministries and national airline, was
abruptly dropped. Officials said only that delegates had objected
to it.
   The delegates then voted by ballot for premier, vice chairmen of
the state Central Military Commission and top judicial posts.
   In announcing the results, the state-run Xinhua News Agency did
not say if any delegates voted against Li.
   Senior leader Deng Xiaoping, who is a delegate, did not attend
and there was no official explanation for his absence. Deng, 84,
had appeared in good health at Friday's congress session.
   Ninety-two ordinary delegates said to have other business were
also absent.
   Foreign reporters were allowed to watch from a balcony, as they
were for the first time Friday when the congress elected Gen. Yang
Shangkun president and former Vice Premier Wan Li to head the
congress Standing Committee.
   Li, 59, was appointed acting premier by the previous congress'
Standing Committee in November, when Zhao Ziyang gave up the post
to become Communist Party chief.
   Since then, the former vice premier and minister of education
and power industry has felt his way slowly in his new job. Although
he supports China's program of modernization, Li's public
statements indicate he favors moving cautiously in introducing
market-style economic reforms, in contrast to Zhao's emphasis on
the need for speedy action.
   In his speech to the congress when its session opened March 25,
Li strongly endorsed the reform goals of Deng and Zhao, but warned
against rushing ``headlong into mass action'' or being ``too
impatient for quick results.''
   In other voting, Zhao was elected vice chairman of the state
Central Military Commission under Deng as chairman. Yang Shangkun
stayed on as permanent vice chairman.
   Zhao has no military experience, and the post is seen as an
opportunity for him to gain the connections and support in the
military he will need if he is to succeed Deng as China's top
leader.
   Six members of the military commission also were elected,
including Qin Jiwei, head of the Beijing Military Command who is
expected to be named defense minister.
   Ren Jianxin, vice president of the Supreme People's Court, was
promoted to president, replacing Zheng Tianxiang.
   Liu Fuzhi, 71, a former minister of justice and minister of
public security, was elected the nation's top prosecutor.
   The government reorganization approved Saturday calls for
splitting several existing ministries and combining others,
reducing the total number from 45 to 41. Among the major changes,
the current planning and economic commissions will be merged into a
powerful body directing China's economic and social development
strategies.
   The ministries of coal, petroleum and nuclear industry will be
merged into a single Energy Ministry, while the Ministry of Labor
and Personnel will be split in half.
   The cancellation of plans to merge the railways and Civil
Aviation Administration of China, the national flag carrier, came
as a suprise not only because of its abruptness but because the
Railways Ministry was regarded as a prime target of reform.
   The train system, China's main means of long-distance travel,
has failed to expand as quickly as demand, and has been criticized
for chronic mismanagement and sloppy operating procedures. Four
fatal train accidents this year, claiming a total of 168 lives,
created a clamor for improved safety measures.
   The congress is expected next week to approve ministerial
appointments and vote on several key laws, including one that would
guarantee business people more freedom from government interference.
   It also is expected to approve a constitutional amendment
legitimizing China's small but growing private sector.
</TEXT>
