<1ST_LINE>r a PM-MissingNewlyweds     04-09 0437</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Missing Newlyweds,0450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Find More Traces of Missing Couple in Downtown Chicago</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By F.N. D'ALESSIO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police have found further traces of two missing
Wheaton College newlyweds but still are unable to determine if
their week-long absence has been the result of foul play.
   Scott Swanson, 23, and Carolyn MacLean, 22, have not been seen
since the couple left the Flint, Mich., home of Ms. MacLean's
grandmother April 2 on their way to the Swanson family home in the
west Chicago suburb of Elgin.
   Sgt. Raymond Caplis of the Chicago Police Youth Headquarters
confirmed late Friday that identification belonging to one of the
missing students had been found in a downtown alley, near the spot
where Ms. MacLean's car was found.
   ``The cards were found in the alley behind Orchestra Hall _
apparently beneath a Dumpster,'' Caplis said.
   Caplis declined to describe the identification, but WBBM-TV
reported that it included several credit cards and a student
identification card.
   Another youth headquarters officer, Detective Paul Stubblefield,
said earlier Friday that neither of the two missing students had
withdrawn any money from their bank accounts since leaving Flint.
   There was speculation initially that the couple, who married
secretly March 26, might have taken off on a delayed honeymoon. But
that speculation was tempered by fear because Ms. MacLean's red BMW
was found last Saturday with its engine running, and police said
there was evidence its glove compartment had been tampered with.
   A pack of cigarettes and a lighter found in the car indicated
the car may have been stolen because friends said neither Swanson
nor Ms. MacLean smoked.
   While police in Illinois, Michigan and Indiana searched for
possible clues, friends, family members and fellow students spread
fliers with the missing couple's pictures to restaurants and gas
stations along Interstate 94 between Flint and Chicago.
   Police have been investigating a report that the two were seen
at a Stevensville, Mich., restaurant off Interstate 94 last
Saturday shortly after leaving Flint.
   John Bradburn of Elgin, a friend of the Swanson family who
helped coordinate the volunteer effort, described the couple as
``good students and good Christians.''
   ``It's been real hard for everyone, especially the families,''
Bradburn said. ``You're up, you're down, you get encouraged with
one report, and then that doesn't work out.''
   Bradburn said Swanson was a senior majoring in psychology.
   School officials said Swanson was active as an ROTC cadet, and
Ms. MacLean, a New Jersey native, worked part time as a model.
   Fellow students at Wheaton College, a religious school west of
Chicago, held round-the-clock prayer services for their missing
schoolmates.
</TEXT>
