<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Jordan-Bomb     04-09 0223</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jordan-Bomb,0230</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bomb Explodes, Injuring Two</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AMMAN, Jordan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A small bomb exploded beneath a stairway at
the capital's main motor vehicles office today, injuring two people
and shattering windows, police said.
   A police spokesman, Col. Ibrahim Harb, said a package containing
about two pounds of dynamite exploded under a stairway near the
building entrance at 11:30 a.m. (4:30 a.m. EDT).
   The blast injured a policeman and a civilian, although ``not
badly,'' he said. The explosion shattered windows, cracked walls
and damaged a door, he said.
   ``We know it was meant to harm people because it exploded ...
when public use of this entrance is usually the heaviest,'' Harb
said.
   ``Fortunately there weren't many people today because people can
get their licenses now from police stations,'' he said, referring
to a recent change of policy.
   He said police were still trying to determine who planted the
bomb, but the official Jordan News Agency hinted at a political
motive.
   ``It comes at a time when his majesty, King Hussein, is
discussing the national Arab stand for defending the nation and
Palestine and Arab lands,'' said an unidentified official quoted by
the agency.
   He was referring to discussions on starting Middle East peace
talks. U.S. Secretary of State George P. Shultz traveled to Jordan
this week to meet with Hussein about the talks.
