<DOCNO> AP880409-0053 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-09-88 0913EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Boeing-BritishAirways     04-09 0541</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Boeing-British Airways,0553</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>British Airways Criticizes Boeing On Quality Control Problems</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   British Airways has criticized Boeing Co. for
faulty workmanship and poor quality control in the construction of
commercial aircraft _ the second complaint revealed this week by an
international Boeing customer.
   The Seattle Times today reported that British Airways, in a
letter written in February, complained in particular about Boeing's
plant in Everett, 30 miles north of Seattle, where the company
makes 747 jumbo jets and twin-engine 767 widebodies.
   The newspaper quoted the letter as saying at least one mistake
compromised the integrity of a 747 and that Boeing workers ``seem
oblivious that they are building aircraft where any mistake not
properly corrected or hidden represents a direct compromise with
safety.''
   The Times obtained a copy of the letter Friday. It was written
by D.K. Craig, British Airways' chief engineer for technical and
quality services, to Phil Condit, executive vice president of
Boeing Commercial Airplanes.
   Boeing officials Friday said they were aware of the situation.
However, company spokesman David Jimenez said they declined to
discuss it ``until later.''
   Japan Air Lines complained to Boeing chairman Frank Shrontz in a
letter leaked Tuesday to the Japanese press. JAL's complaints
ranged from incorrect assembly of fire-extinguisher piping in 767s
to engine-temperature sensors being installed in reverse order in a
747. The letter demanded that Boeing make greater efforts to
achieve better quality control.
   A Japan Air Lines spokesman was quoted in a Wall Street Journal
story this week as saying the defects were not ``critical problems
for safety.''
   Craig's letter cites problems spotted by airline inspectors at
the Boeing plant ranging from missing fasteners to wrong or missing
parts, the newspaper reported.
   One missing part caused the floor of a jet to bow so much that a
main deck cargo power drive unit wouldn't work, the newspaper said.
   ``My quality inspectors can only properly inspect a very small
proportion of each aircraft,'' Craig wrote. ``They should never
ever come across ... missing fasteners, missing parts, cracks .. .
fasteners fitted the wrong way round. Yet we find instances of some
of these on every aircraft.''
   British Airways placed Boeing's largest-ever order potentially
worth $4.1 billion in August 1986 when it ordered 16 747-400s and
placed options for 12 more. It also has 11 767s on order and flies
Boeing 737s and 757s.
   Like other customers, British Airways maintains a staff of
inspectors at Boeing factories.
   Craig Martin, Boeing Commercial Airplanes spokesman, said after
the JAL letter was made public that an investigation was under way
to determine how the mistakes occurred and said he believed they
were ``one-time occurrences.''
   But the British Airways official wrote the situation
``underscores our fears that the underlying reason for the Boeing
Co.'s poor quality record is that the production work force are in
general, inadequately trained, possess a low level of basic working
skills, and of paramount concern, seem oblivious that they are
building aircraft where any mistake not properly corrected or
hidden represents a direct compromise with safety.''
   Boeing, the world's biggest maker of commercial aircraft and one
of the United States' biggest exporters, is in the third year of a
major effort to improve products, increase productivity and cut
costs.
</TEXT>
