<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BoyDefender     04-09 0270</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Boy Defender,0277</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Boy Drives Off Intruder In Defending Little Sister</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BIRMINGHAM, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 10-year-old boy drove out an intruder
by pounding him with a board after the man broke into the boy's
house and grabbed his little sister around the neck.
   Burglary officer H.R. Barnett said that in nearly 17 years as a
police officer he had ``never seen such a degree of bravery in a
little boy'' as that of Michael King.
   ``He chased off a 36-year-old man by hitting him about the head
and back with a stick,'' Barnett said.
   Keith Strode was arrested soon after the incident and was held
in the Jefferson County Jail on a charge of violating his parole,
police said.
   Michael's mother, Wanda King, said her husband was at work when
a man crashed through her bedroom window shortly after midnight
Wednesday morning and seized her 7-year-old daughter, Latasha, a
police report said.
   Mrs. King and Michael fled the house but once outside, Mrs. King
saw the intruder had her daughter around the neck, the report said.
Michael rushed back into the house and drove off the man with a bed
rail slat, it said.
   Shortly after, police said they found Strode a few blocks away
and took him to the King home, where Michael said, ``That's him.
That's the man who was in the house.''
   Strode was taken to Cooper Green Hospital for treatment of cuts,
police said.
   Mrs. King said the children still are frightened about sleeping
at night.
   ``I don't know what made (Michael) do it. It must have been the
Lord guiding him,'' she said.
