<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Sikhs     04-09 0287</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sikhs,0300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Fear Sikhs Have U.S. Missiles</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AMRITSAR, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Punjab police said today they fear that
Sikh extremists have acquired one or two U.S.-made Stinger missiles
and have hidden them inside the Golden Temple, Sikhism's holiest
shrine.
   Police halted trucks carrying rice, milk and other basic
supplies to the temple to search for the missiles.
   The missiles would represent a major upgrading in the arsenal of
Sikh extremists, who have been waging a guerrilla war since 1982
for an independent homeland in Punjab state. In the past, the Sikhs
have largely relied on knives, swords, pistols and automatic rifles.
   A senior police official, speaking on condition of anonymity,
said today that ``initial intelligence reports suggest the
militants inside the temple may have Stinger missiles with them.''
   Authorities were unsure where the weapons would have come from,
but one police official said they were ``obviously from Pakistan.''
   The United States has supplied the shoulder-launched Stinger
missiles via Pakistan to Afghan guerrillas fighting the
Soviet-backed Afghanistan government.
   India has accused neighboring Pakistan of allowing Sikh
militants to train and arm on its territory.
   The militants are also believed to use the temple for military
purposes. Police say about 400 people are in the temple complex,
some pilgrims and some militants.
   A June 1984 government raid to drive radicals from the shrine
left more than 1,200 people dead, mostly Sikhs. Soon afterward,
Sikh bodyguards killed Prime Minister Indira Gandhi. Militants are
believed to have rearmed the temple since then.
   Sikhs, whose religion was formed about 500 years ago as an
alternative to Hinduism and Islam, claim they suffer discrimination
from India's majority Hindus.
   They are the religious minority in India but form the majority
in Punjab.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
