<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Mecham     04-09 0199</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mecham,0205</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Grants Delay in Mecham Criminal Trial</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge has granted a defense lawyer's
motion to delay the criminal trial of ex-Gov. Evan Mecham and his
brother, Willard, for a month.
   Maricopa County Superior Judge Michael Ryan announced his
decision Friday after Michael Scott, a lawyer for Evan Mecham, said
he had a scheduling conflict with an unrelated child-abuse case set
for trial April 19.
   Ryan agreed to postpone the Mechams' trial to May 19 from April
21 despite the objections of assistant attorneys general Barnett
Lotstein and Michael Cudahy.
   The new trial date is two days after a recall gubernatorial
election scheduled for May 17.
   The Arizona Supreme Court is expected to decide next week
whether the election will proceed despite Mecham's ouster from
office after his conviction Monday by the Arizona Senate on two
impeachment charges.
   The governorship is held by Rose Mofford, formerly Secretary of
State, who assumed the job after Mecham was impeached Feb. 5.
   Evan Mecham, 63, and Willard Mecham, 67, were indicted by a
state grand jury Jan. 8 on charges of violating state laws by
concealing a $350,000 loan to Evan Mecham's 1986 gubernatorial
campaign.
</TEXT>
