<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Vietnam-US 1stLd-Writethru a0459 04-09 0511</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Vietnam-US, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0459,0523</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Senator Predicts Closer U.S.-Vietnamese Ties</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS last week to this week in graf 10 bgng ``Pressler,
who...'' and inserts 1 graf after 10th with background on transfer
of remains. Picks up 12th pvs, `Pressler said...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DENIS D. GRAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An American senator returning from
Vietnam predicted today that the United States and Vietnam would
establish special offices in each other's capitals as early as this
year.
   Sen. Larry Pressler, R-S.D., a Vietnam War veteran, said such
special interest sections would help expedite the accounting for
Americans missing in action during the war, the plight of
Amerasians and other problems between the former enemies.
   Pressler told a news conference that despite opposition to such
sections from the U.S. State Department, there would be
``overwhelming support'' in the U.S. Congress and implementation
within the next two years.
   Last month, Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., a former prisoner of war
in Vietnam, introduced legislation to set up the special interest
sections, which are usually housed in a third country's consular
offices.
   Pressler said he would seek an amendment to include a U.S.
``special technical office'' in Ho Chi Minh City.
   Ho Chi Minh City, formerly called Saigon, is the major exit
point for thousands of Vietnamese departing for the United States
and other countries under the U.N.-sponsored Orderly Departure
Program.
   These include the children of Vietnamese and American couples,
or Amerasians, during the war.
   Pressler also predicted full diplomatic relations would be
established within five to 10 years.
   ``I think we are on the verge of some substantial changes in our
relations with Vietnam. Our policy on Vietnam will change,'' he
said. ``We have so many common bonds.''
   Pressler, who served as an Army second lieutenant in Vietnam 21
years ago, met with Foreign Minister Nguyen Co Thach and other
Vietnamese officials this week. On Wednesday, he took part in a
ceremony at Hanoi in which the remains of 27 people believed to be
missing Americans were repatriated.
   It was the largest such transfer of remains since the last
American forces withdrew from South Vietnam on March 29, 1973.
   
   Pressler said that given severe food shortages in Vietnam, he
explored the idea of sending some food aid to that country by
private American organizations. But he said such aid should not be
tied to the accounting for 1,767 Americans MIAs in Vietnam.
   Pressler said he agreed with the State Department's policy on
tying the U.S. trade embargo with Vietnam's accounting for the MIAs
and the withdrwal of its troops from Cambodia, which Hanoi invaded
in late 1978.
   But he said he could not understand the Department's opposition
to the interest section offices.
   ``Whether we like it or not, our country is going to have a
great interest in Vietnam,'' Pressler said, citing the large
numbers of U.S. war veterans, Vietnamese who have settled in the
United States and other factors that bind the two countries.
   U.S. troops supported South Vietnam, which was defeated by
communist North Vietnam in 1975.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
