<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Shultz-Afghanistan     04-09 0195</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Shultz-Afghanistan,170</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shultz May Attend Signing of Soviet-Afghan Accords, Official Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz may go to
Geneva on Thursday to attend the signing of accords calling for the
withdrawal of Soviet forces from Afghanistan after an occupation of
more than eight years, an administration official said today.
   But the signing expected Thursday depends on a formal response
by Moscow to a U.S. proposal for a symetrical continuation of U.S.
and Soviet aid to warring factions. The offical, who spoke on
condition of anonymity, said the Soviets have not yet affirmed the
compromise and a decision on Shultz attending the signing depended
on that affirmation.
   Foreign Minister Eduard Shevardnadze would sign the accords for
the Soviet Union, which would withdraw its troops by the end of the
year. The United States has provided shoulder-fired Stinger
missiles and other arms to guerrillas at war with the Marxist
government in Kabul, which is backed by the Soviet army.
   Shultz proposed ending all U.S. and Soviet aid to the two sides,
but was turned down by the Soviets and offered the compromise,
calling for symetrical levels of aid, in its place.
</TEXT>
