<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Israel 2ndLd-Writethru a0485 04-09 0779</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0485,0799</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Military Source Says Israeli Girl May Have Been Killed By Guard's
Gun</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 11 grafs with military source saying bullet may
have killed girl, UPDATES with new clashes reported. PIcks up 8th
graf pvs, `Since December...</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY4</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KARIN LAUB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A military source said today that an Israeli
girl killed in a clash with Arab villagers might have been shot by
a Jewish settler but said the army is not ruling out the
possibility she was killed by an Arab.
   Israeli media, citing an army probe, said Friday that
15-year-old Tirza Porat was likely killed by a bullet fired from
the rifle of another Jewish settler.
   The military source said the cause of Tirza's death had not been
determined but added that ``there is a possibility she died from a
bullet.''
   ``If so, there are two possibilities. Either Al Dubi pulled the
trigger after he was stoned (by villagers) or the shot was fired by
an Arab after he took away Al Dubi's M-16,'' the source said,
speaking on condition of anonymity.
   Romam Al Dubi was one of two Jewish guards accompanying Israeli
teen-agers on a hike Wednesday near the West Bank village of Beita.
   Tirza was struck in the head by a bullet and a large object
during a clash that broke out between villagers and the hiking
group. The army has previously maintained that she was stoned to
death by Arabs.
   More violence was reported today in the occupied territories.
Hospital officials said an 18-year-old Arab was wounded in the
chest during clashes with Israeli soldiers in the Jabaliya refugee
camp in the Gaza Strip.
   The hospital officials said soldiers firing rubber bullets in
the refugee camp also hit a 60-year-old Arab man below the left eye
and a 50-year-old woman in the stomach.
   The army said it could not confirm the reports.
   In Gaza City, Arabs staged a general strike and hoisted a
Palestinian flag, outlawed by Israel, on the city's main mosque.
Soldiers fired tear gas and live ammunition at youths who threw
stones and burned tires in the city's main thoroughfares.
   On Friday, a firebomb damaged the front porch of the home of
U.S. Consulate spokesman David Good, who said his 5-year-old
daughter and two maids were in the house but that no one was
injured. He said a guard assigned to him by the consulate had been
in the back of the building.
   Since December, the U.S. Consulate building in east Jerusalem
has been firebombed twice, but no one was injured.
   Throughout the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip, Arab youths
chanted anti-Israeli slogans and threw rocks at troops after noon
Moslem prayers Friday. Protesters hoisted black flags to
commemorate 141 Arabs killed in the four-month uprising. One
Israeli soldier also has died.
   In Jabaliya, soldiers wounded five Arabs after being stoned by
angry worshipers. Four Arabs were wounded by army gunfire in three
other clashes, hospital officials said.
   The army only would confirm four wounded.
   On Jerusalem's Temple Mount, dozens of Palestinians chanted
nationalist slogans after prayers at the Al Aqsa Mosque. Several
boys tossed rocks at border police who dispersed them without
incident.
   An army official, meanwhile, said the investigation of Miss
Porat's death had not been completed, partly because witnesses
provided conflicting accounts. ``There are 10 different people who
give you 10 different versions,'' he said.
   The army says Arab youths from Beita threw stones at the hikers
and attacked them.
   In the fighting, two Arabs were killed in addition to Miss
Porat, two Arabs were wounded, and 13 Israeli injured.
   Israel radio, citing the army probe, has said Al Dubi opened
fire when the group was first stoned.
   The radio quoted the army report as saying the other guard had
asked Al Dubi not to shoot, but that Al Dubi told the children to
gather around him and started shooting, then was disarmed by Arabs
who took the Israelis to Beita.
   Army officials said a villager handed Al Dubi's weapon, an M-16
rifle, to a soldier on Friday, and Israel TV said eight bullets
were left in the magazine.
   The second weapon, an Uzi submachine gun, was found in the
village Wednesday, and the army said villagers had dismantled it.
   Israeli media, citing the army report, have said the only shots
fired in the clash came from these two weapons, but that
investigators didn't know who pulled the trigger.
   Lt. Gen. Dan Shomron, the army chief of staff, indicated the
struggle centered around the two Israeli guards. He told Israel
radio the investigation showed the villagers did not intend to harm
the Israeli teen-agers.
</TEXT>
