<FILEID>AP-NR-04-09-88 1137EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a PM-GangViolence 2ndLd-Writethru a0477 04-09 0665</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gang Violence, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0477,0677</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Declare War on Street Gangs</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf, `The task ..., to UPDATE arrests to 634; SUBS
5th graf, `In addition ...,' to UPDATE number of vehicles, weapons
seized; INSERTS 1 graf after 8th, `The man ...,' with assistant
police chief also making arrest.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LA1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 1,000 police officers, ordered by
the mayor to ``take back the streets,'' raided gang strongholds
today in their biggest attack on drug dealing and street violence
in the nation's second-largest city.
   The task force, the largest to take to the streets of Los
Angeles since the 1984 Olympics, arrested 634 people for
investigation of a variety of offenses, with 334 suspected of being
gang members, said police spokesman Bill Frio. The other 300 were
arrested for a variety of felony and misdemeanor offenses.
   ``We are going to take these terrorists off the streets of Los
Angeles,'' Mayor Tom Bradley, a former police lieutenant, said as
the deployment began. ``We are determined to take back the streets
from these hoodlums.''
   Black-and-white police cruisers raced through South-Central Los
Angeles where gangs hold sway most nights. Every few blocks, a bust
was taking place, with officers swarming around handcuffed youths
as patrol cars blocked the streets.
   In addition to arrests, police early today impounded 96 vehicles
and 10 guns, Frio said.
   Prisoners sat in long lines on benches outside a temporary
booking center at the Los Angeles Memorial Coliseum, manacled and
chained together, waiting their turn for booking at folding tables.
Some were released and others went to jail.
   Police Chief Daryl Gates made a collar of his own, stopping a
man in gang dress, frisking him, and discovering a bottle of
prescription drugs in somebody else's name.
   The man, whose name wasn't immediately released, was held for
investigation of possessing a controlled substance, said Lt. Mark
Leap, noting wryly that ``the troops responded quite favorably.''
   Assistant Police Chief Robert Vernon also made an arrest. His
collar was wanted for a parole violation, Frio said.
   The mayor joined Gates in addressing hundreds of shotgun-toting
officers at a roll call at the coliseum, their comments apparently
addressed to violence-weary citizens as well as the officers.
   ``Be gentle with the citizens so they don't feel their
neighborhood is under siege,'' Gates said, promising sterner
measures for lawbreakers. ``We're going to wage a war and it will
be over when the violence is over.''
   About half the special force augmented regular patrols in the
gang-plagued South-Central Los Angeles neighborhoods while the rest
of the officers spread out across the city's four other police
divisions.
   The task force was assembled by putting officers on overtime at
a cost of $150,000 a day, and Bradley vowed to keep spending what
it takes to intimidate the gangs, blamed for 205 killings in the
city of Los Angeles in 1987.
   County-wide, the death toll from gang violence in 1987 was 387,
many of them innocent bystanders caught up in the gangs' trademark
drive-by shootings.
   Officials estimate that there are about 70,000 gang members in
the city, and drug dealing and gang violence have been a fact of
life in the poor, minority neighborhoods of South-Central Los
Angeles.
   But wider attention focused on the problem in February, when a
woman was killed by a stray bullet during a gang showdown in the
affluent, largely white Westwood entertainment district near the
University of California, Los Angeles.
   After a Good Friday attack killed one non-gang member and
injured 12 others on a South-Central Los Angeles sidewalk, Gates
announced plans for the new task force.
   Bradley has budgeted to add 400 new police officers to the
7,000-member force next year, and political opposition to
law-and-order measures aimed at gangs is virtually nonexistent.
   County Supervisor Kenneth Hahn has called for military police
units from the National Guard to patrol the worst neighborhoods,
but Gov. George Deukmejian is cool toward the proposal.
</TEXT>
