<FILEID>AP-NR-04-09-88 1156EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-India-Sikhs     04-09 0460</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-India-Sikhs,0476</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Say Militant Sikhs May Have Stinger Missiles</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RAJU GOPALAKRISHNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMRITSAR, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sikh militants may have acquired one or
two U.S.-made Stinger anti-aircraft missiles and hidden them inside
the Golden Temple, the Sikh faith's holiest shrine, Punjab police
officials said Saturday.
   Possession of the shoulder-fired, heat-seeking missiles would
raise the militants' arsenal to a new level.
   Sikh extremists, who have been waging a guerrilla war since 1982
for greater autonomy or an independent homeland in Punjab state,
generally have relied on knives, swords, pistols and automatic
rifles.
   Their attacks so far this year in Punjab have claimed at least
676 lives, including eight Friday night and Saturday in a
half-dozen attacks across the northern state.
   Last month the extremists used rocket-propelled grenades for the
first time in three attacks on police and paramilitary units.
   Stinger missiles may have been smuggled into the Golden Temple
in trucks carrying rice, milk and other supplies into the complex,
according to police who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   About 10 Sikh militant groups operate out of the temple complex.
Indian paramilitary units have 17 checkpoints around the Golden
Temple but no troops inside the complex.
   ``Initial intelligence reports suggest the militants inside the
temple may have Stinger missiles with them,'' one senior police
official said.
   Another police official said Sikh separatists inside the temple
were thought to have ``one or two'' Stingers.
   One official said the missiles were ``obviously from Pakistan,''
which borders Punjab state.
   India repeatedly has accused Pakistan of allowing Sikhs to train
and arm on its territory. Pakistan has denied the accusation.
   The United States supplies Stingers through Pakistan to Afghan
guerrillas who have been fighting Soviet troops and the
Soviet-backed government in Afghanistan since 1979. Afghan
guerrilla groups have bases in Pakistan, and huge arm bazaars have
sprung up there.
   Amritsar is about 15 miles east of the Pakistani border.
   Indian police have raided the Golden Temple a dozen times in the
last two years, but such raids are a political as well as a
military risk because Sikhs consider them a desecration of their
holy shrine.
   The late Prime Minister Indira Gandhi launched a major assault
on the temple in 1984 in an effort to dislodge the militants. About
1,200 people died in the raid, prompting Mrs. Gandhi's
assassination by her Sikh bodyguards six months later.
   Since then, the Golden Temple has been a hotbed of the Sikh
separatist movement and a haven for various militant factions.
   Sikhs, whose faith has roots in Hinduism and Islam, are a
majority in Punjab but make up only 2 percent of India's 800
million people. They claim they are discriminated against by
Hindus, who form more than 80 percent of the nationwide population.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
