<FILEID>AP-NR-04-09-88 1222EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-LatinAmerica-Drugs     04-09 0622</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Latin America-Drugs,590</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kerry, D'Amato Assail Latin Governments on Drug Issue</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senate investigators have stressed anew that
the battle against illicit drugs shipped from Latin America will be
``an uphill fight for a long, long time'' if the government
continues to tolerate foreign leaders who merely wink at the
problem.
   ``This is an enormously profitable business and it has been
aided by several nations who claim to be our friends,'' said Sen.
John F. Kerry, D-Mass., whose Foreign Relations subcommittee on
drugs and terrorism just concluded a second round of hearings on
the issue.
   ``We're going to be fighting an uphill fight for a long, long
time as long as leaders of these countries are allowed to get away
with this,'' said Kerry. Sen. Alfonse D'Amato, R-N.Y., agreed,
saying ``Drugs are winked at by many governments throughout Latin
America, by high-ranking officials of those countries.''
   The two senators also faulted a lack of coordination in the U.S.
effort, citing testimony which outlined disputes among various
government agencies, including the Customs Service, the FBI, the
Drug Enforcement Administration, and the State Department.
   ``What we have to do is put drugs on the front burner, establish
that it is a priority issue for us in our dealings with these
countries, make those countries know that we will act and act
toughly,'' said D'Amato.
   The most recent testimony focused on the flow of drugs,
particularly cocaine and marijuana, from Colombia and implicated
officials from Honduras, Haiti and Jamaica, in addition to Panama.
The first set of hearings last month focused on Panamanian
strongman Manuel Noriega and his ties to illegal drugs.
   The witnesses, most of them convicted drug dealers, told
detailed stories about night-time flights at treetop level,
backroom cash deals in which few questions were asked and no names
were offered, payoffs were made to officials ranging from county
sheriffs in the United States to top-level officials in Latin
America, and huge profits.
   ``In my line of work, it doesn't pay to ask too many questions
or know too much. I did not ask,'' said George Morales, a convicted
cocaine trafficker.
   Morales was explaining to reporters why he didn't know who owned
the several hundred pounds of cocaine he claimed to have
transported from Costa Rica to Florida two years ago. The drugs
were brought back on a flight in which guns were flown to the
Contra guerrillas, Morales said.
   Kerry said he believes the witnesses, despite their status as
criminals and even though some of them claim the others are lying.
For example, Michael P. Vogel made up so many stories he was known
as ``the liar'' by other members of a smuggling ring, according to
Michael Palmer, a member of the same group.
   ``There's an impressive amount of corroboration in their
stories. Yes, not every single detail matches up, but they are
telling the same stories and those stories are substantiated by the
overwhelming amount of information,'' said Kerry.
   D'Amato also believed the stories. ``I think the detail and the
corroboration in the stories we heard are impressive,'' he said.
   The story told by Gary Betzner was typical of the drug
smugglers. The 47-year-old father of five children testified that
in his home state of Arkansas, he was a civic activist who was
involved in local politics in addition to working as a crop duster.
   Betzner said he became a smuggler for a simple reason _ money.
In an 18-month period, he said, he flew 50 drug flights and was
paid at least $40,000 each. Two other flights, in which he ferried
weapons to Costa Rica for the Contras and returned with a planeload
of drugs, paid him $360,000 each, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880409-0072 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-09-88 1229EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-LiProfile     04-09 0602</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Li Profile,0619</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Li Peng Struggles To Develop Own Style, Power Base</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto POK4</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Li Peng, named to China's top government post on
Saturday, has tried to shake the label of conservative during five
months as acting premier.
   Now that the National People's Congress has confirmed him as
premier, he is expected to press for reforms but at a slower pace
than his predecessor, Zhao Ziyang.
   Li, 59, an electrical engineer by training, lacks Zhao's
personal charisma and tends to be stiff in public appearances.
   His only previous administrative experience came as head of the
power and education ministries. Unlike Zhao, who was governor of
Sichuan, China's most populous province, Li never was responsible
for administration of a region.
   Although he is well-connected _ Li is the adopted son of one of
China's most beloved Communist officials, the late Premier Chou
En-lai _ he is not believed to have a personal power base in the
central government.
   Li has moved slowly in his new job. The reorganization of
government ministries approved by the congress was suggested before
he became acting premier, but he undoubtedly played a large role in
working out details of the shakeup.
   He has tried without success to change his conservative image,
an idea based in part on his years of study in the Soviet Union. He
is believed to favor a slower pace of change than Zhao in China's
campaign to introduce market mechanisms into the economy and
streamline the stagnant bureaucracy.
   Although he has referred to the conservative label as a
``misunderstanding,'' his few statements on policy have reinforced
it. Li has stressed the need for stability in the economy and for
controlling inflation, which reached 7.3 percent last year, even if
the measures slow reform of China's pricing system.
   In a work report to the congress, delivered when it opened its
annual session March 25, Li endorsed the reform program but
repeatedly cautioned against overexpectations and ``rushing
headlong'' into change.
   As premier, Li is responsible for the day-to-day operations of
the government. Zhao, who gave up the premiership to become
Communist Party chief, controls the direction of government
policies.
   Li was born in Chengdu, in southwest China's Sichuan province,
in 1928. His father was killed by Nationalist soldiers during
China's civil war when Li was 3, and he was adopted by Chou En-lai.
   He spent his teen years at Communist Party headquarters in
Yenan, where Mao Tse-tung and Chou directed the Communists'
successful fight against the Nationalists. He joined the party at
age 17.
   From 1948 to 1954 he studied at the hydropower department of the
Moscow Electrodynamics Academy, where he became fluent in Russian.
   After returning home, he held a series of important engineering
posts, including chief engineer of China's largest hydroelectric
complex in Jilin province in the northwest.
   In 1978, Li was promoted to full membership in the party Central
Committee, and in the next year became minister of power industry.
He became vice premier in 1983 and education minister in 1985. The
same year, continuing his climb up the party hierarchy, he became a
member of the Politburo and secretariat.
   He was made a member of the highest decision-making body, the
five-member Politburo Standing Committee, at a party congress last
fall.
   Weeks later, he was appointed acting premier to replace Zhao,
who resigned to take up the leadership of the Communist Party.
   Li has taught himself English. His wife, Zhu Lin, formerly
worked in the Ministry of Water Resources and Electrical Power, and
their two sons and daughter are said to work in the same ministry.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
