<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Poachers     04-09 0170</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Poachers,0174</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviets Sentence Japanese for Poaching</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Soviet court sentenced a Japanese fisherman to
six months in prison and confiscated the boat of another for
poaching crab in Soviet territorial waters of the Pacific Ocean,
Tass reported Saturday.
   The official news agency said more than 1,000 pounds of crab
were aboard the two boats. It said the crew of one boat had poached
repeatedly, causing ``significant damage'' to the economy of the
Soviet far eastern region.
   Tass did not say when the two were sentenced or where they were
taken into custody, but issued the report from Nakhodka, a Soviet
coastal city nearly 600 miles across the Sea of Japan from Tokyo.
   The boat and equipment of Nagasaki Eshitaka were confiscated,
Tass said. Funakoshi Keiji was sentenced to six months in prison
because the court was guided by ``humane principles and took into
account the difficult circumstances of his family and his sincere
repentance.''
   Both men were fined, but Tass did not name an amount.
</TEXT>
