<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ShepherdCase Bjt   04-09 0797</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Shepherd Case, Bjt,0821</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Does Justice Nominee Have Mole Or Not?</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK PETERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The selection of John C. Shepherd to become
deputy attorney general of the United States has focused attention
not so much on his legal credentials as on whether he has a mole on
his upper thigh.
   The question has come up before, during and after a trial in
which Denise Sinner, who used to be the bookkeeper for Shepherd's
law firm, was convicted of stealing nearly $150,000 from the office.
   Shepherd says he doesn't have a mole on his thigh.
   Sinner says she knows he does because they had an affair, and
that during the affair he authorized her to write checks to herself
for the money that was taken.
   Now the FBI is looking into the case because Shepherd, 62, was
picked by Attorney General Edwin Meese to be the No. 2 man in the
Justice Department.
   Also to be checked out are Shepherd's memberships in the
Missouri Athletic Club, which does not accept women, and the
Bellerive Country Club, which has no black members although the
club's bylaws say it is open. Shepherd said last week that he has
not decided whether to resign from the clubs.
   Shepherd, a prominent St. Louis attorney and former president of
the American Bar Association, has insisted that Sinner is lying
about the mole, the affair and authorization to write checks.
   ``Her allegations are absolutely untrue and unfounded,'' he said
last week. ``I am very confident that the FBI's report will bring
this matter to an end.''
   So is the Justice Department.
   ``We were aware of the accusation before the selection was
made,'' said Justice Department spokesman Terry Eastland. ``We
understood that it was discredited at the time of the trial and
believe that another investigation of this will show there's
nothing there.''
   Sinner, 29, convicted of stealing $147,000 from the law firm
Shepherd, Sandberg & Phoenix between July 1986 and February 1987,
claimed she and Shepherd met at motels in St. Louis and Chicago.
   ``This woman had no corroboration for any of her testimony,''
said Michael G. Ravetta, the assistant St. Louis circuit attorney
who prosecuted her. ``There wasn't a plane ticket. There weren't
any receipts. No bellhops came forward. There was nothing. Not even
a matchbook from a cheap motel.''
   When Sinner was indicted, she first told investigators she had a
rich boyfriend who had been sending her checks that she'd deposit
into the firm's account. Then she would write checks to herself off
the account, thus avoiding a wait for the boyfriend's checks to be
cleared.
   ``Obviously, the auditors didn't find that to be true,'' Ravetta
said. ``That's when her story changed to the affair with Shepherd.''
   Sinner said Friday that she lied initially to ``buy some time.''
   ``I thought he (Shepherd) would be willing to work something
out,'' she said. ``But that didn't happen. So I decided to tell the
truth.''
   Sinner was hired by Shepherd's law firm through an employment
agency, Ravetta said, and appeared from her resume to be solid for
the job.
   But Sinner's attorney, Darrill S. Beebe, said Sinner, whose
college major was music, was hired because of Shepherd.
   ``A $6 million law firm hires her to take care of the money?''
Beebe asked rhetorically at trial. ``They didn't have a bookkeeper.
They had a Twinkie.''
   Ravetta said Shepherd had nothing to do with the hiring.
   Sinner wrote more than 50 checks to herself before she was
fired. She contended that, in the midst of the affair, Shepherd
authorized her to write the checks to pay bills and buy luxury
items such as a BMW car and a fur coat.
   The jury agreed that it was just ``way too far-fetched'' to
think Shepherd would have authorized Sinner to write the checks,
said juror Jo Anne Candela.
   Even so, Candela said, most of the jurors believed that there
was ``something fishy'' about the way Sinner got the job.
   ``A lot of us thought that maybe she was a con artist,'' Candela
said. ``But we also felt that there had been something there
between her and Shepherd.''
   Sinner is scheduled to be sentenced later this month. After
that, Beebe said, he'll file an appeal that claims, among other
things, that a pre-trial motion to have Shepherd's right leg
examined should not have been turned down.
   Ravetta said Shepherd was willing to undergo the exam. But
Ravetta himself decided to fight the motion because it was too
general.
   ``The motion said he had a mole, birthmark or other skin
imperfection above his right knee,'' he said. ``We just felt that
we could have drawn a star on his leg with a ballpoint pen and she
would have said that's what she saw.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
