<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PlayboyMove     04-09 0364</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Playboy Move,0370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Playboy Moving To Building In Midst of Address Change Away from 666</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A luxury high-rise some have called the Devil's
Building because of its 666 address will become the new home of
Playboy Enterprises Inc., but the street number will read 680 by
then.
   Playboy President Christie Hefner said Friday her publishing,
video and licensing company has signed a 15-year lease for 100,000
square feet on the 15th and 16th floors of the building, which is
to be called Lake Shore Place as of May 1.
   The new building, which Playboy will enter by the fall of 1989,
will provide the company with more efficient office space, Ms.
Hefner said.
   Six hundred sixty-six North Lake Shore Drive has been called the
Devil's Building or the Mark-of-the-Beast building in reference to
passages from the New Testament book of Revelation, which refer to
a beast with a mark of three sixes.
   But people who live in the building's 400 residential units were
told in a March 1 letter the building's address would change to 680
North Lake Shore Drive as of May 1.
   Spokesmen for the luxury building's owner, a Chemical Bank of
New York subsidiary, and the local management company, Golub & Co.,
said the change was intended to dissassociate the building from the
financial problems of its previous owner, who lost a mortgage
foreclosure battle with the bank last year.
   ``It certainly wasn't us who raised the devil thing,'' said
Michael Schramm, executive vice president of Golub & Co.
   Playboy holds a 10-year lease expiring in 1990 on 10 floors of
the Playboy Building, but the company does not need that space
following the disposal of some businesses in recent years because
of financial problems.
   Playboy's current home was known as the Palmolive Building
before Hugh Hefner, Playboy's founder and Ms. Hefner's father,
bought the leasehold on the structure in 1965. Playboy moved into
the building in 1967, but sold the leasehold in 1980.
   The company rejected moving to Los Angeles, where Hefner now
lives, or to New York, where some Playboy publishing and
advertising executives are based, in favor of staying in Chicago,
Ms. Hefner said.
</TEXT>
