<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Peru-Violence     04-09 0283</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Peru-Violence,0295</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rebels Assassinate Lima Police Officers On Eve of Meese Visit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Maoist guerrillas killed two police officers
in Lima on the eve of a visit by U.S. Attorney General Edwin Meese
III, the Interior Ministry said Saturday.
   Meese, on a weeklong tour to assess anti-drug efforts in Latin
America, planned to be in Peru from Saturday to Monday.
   The attacks late Friday by the Mao-inspired Shining Path
guerrillas shattered weeks of relative calm in the
terrorism-plagued capital.
   In the highlands, where guerrilla violence has increased
recently, Maoist rebels blew up railroad tracks with dynamite
Friday night, derailing a 27-car train hauling zinc from mines to a
refinery, police said Saturday.
   It was the second attack against trains in Peru's most important
rail network in a week and it severed Lima's rail connection with
the highlands.
   Police said there were no injuries in the blast but it would
take several days to make repairs.
   The state railroad company Enafer said in a communique Saturday
that it was seeking help from the army to guard the trains. Enafer
said guerrillas have bombed and derailed 89 trains causing more
than $35 million in damage.
   In the Lima attacks, the police officers were shot to death
Friday evening by groups of three or four rebels, the ministry said.
   The government says more than 10,000 people, including 562
policemen, have been killed in guerrilla violence since the Shining
Path launched an insurgency eight years ago.
   The rebels seek to topple Peru's elected government and install
a worker-peasant state, modeled on the ideas of China's Mao-Tse
Tung.
   Meese has visited the Dominican Republic, Colombia and Ecuador
and is scheduled to travel to Bolivia.
</TEXT>
