<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Reagan-Radio     04-09 0548</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-Radio,540</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Underscores Threat to Veto Trade Bill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERENCE HUNT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP White House Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTA BARBARA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan on Saturday
underscored his threat to veto a sweeping trade bill moving through
Congress, saying the legislation ``could go a long way toward
making America a bad investment.''
   Reagan, in his weekly radio address, said ``we still have very _
underline very _ serious reservations'' about the bill.
   He delivered the remarks from his mountaintop ranch where he has
been spending a 10-day vacation. Reagan will return to Washington
on Sunday, stopping briefly in Las Vegas to address the National
Association of Broadcasters' convention.
   Sen. Lloyd Bentsen, giving the Democratic Party response to the
president's address, urged Reagan to sign the trade measure.
   ``No one suggests that the bipartisan trade bill Congress will
send to the president will solve all of America's problems with
trade and restore our competitiveness,'' said Bentsen, D-Texas.
   ``But we can't do the job without a consistent trade policy to
shield us from protectionist pressures by opening world markets to
American manufactured and agricultural products to create new
opportunities for our service industry, to accord trade policy the
importance it so clearly deserves and to demonstrate that America
is serious about insisting on equal access to world markets,''
Bentsen said.
   The trade bill has been rewritten to delete a key provision that
had drawn administration criticism, the so-called Gephardt
amendment, named for Rep. Richard Gephardt, D-Mo. That amendment
would have forced a president under certain circumstances to
retaliate against a country using unfair trade practices.
   But the administration still objects to surviving provisions,
including one that would require businesses to give employees 60
days advance notice of plans to close a plant or work place.
   The administration also opposes a provision that would limit
U.S. sales by Japan's Toshiba Corp. and a subsidiary as punishment
for illegal sales to the Soviet Union of sensitive military
technology.
   Without citing the provisions he dislikes, Reagan said, ``The
bottom line is this: I will veto a bad trade bill before I let a
bad trade bill veto our economy.''
   He said foreign investment in the United States ``isn't
something to be scared of. It brings us a host of benefits,
including jobs and lower interest rates for all Americans. ...''
   ``We can be glad people in other countries choose to invest in
the vibrant and growing U.S. economy rather than their own
nations,'' Reagan said.
   However, he said the trade bill ``could go a long way toward
making America a bad investment for Americans and foreigners
alike.''
   Reagan said the economy is strong, and that the trade bill would
adversely affect U.S. business growth.
   Saying a higher percentage of the labor force is at work than
ever before, Reagan told his listeners, ``I'd love to take the
blame, or the credit, as the case may be, but that just wouldn't be
fair.''
   Reagan said he merely has presided over an administration that
has reduced the government's regulation of business and has brought
about tax cuts, and that the U.S. private sector has taken the
economy ``and run with it.''
   After the radio address, Reagan was presented with a tribute,
the Badge of the American Spirit Medal, from the California
Association of Highway Patrolmen.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880409-0078 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-09-88 1329EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Reagan-Text     04-09 0857</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-Text,850</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>With AM-Reagan-Radio</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTA BARBARA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a transcript of President
Reagan's weekly radio address delivered Saturday:
   My fellow Americans, you probably heard that some of our
political opponents are very concerned about the state of our
economy, and I have to tell you, I don't blame them. If I were in
their shoes I'd be worried too.
   You see, April marks the 65th straight month of the longest
peacetime expansion in U.S. history.
   In that time we've created nearly 16 million jobs. They are
better and higher paying too, which is one reason why the real
income of the average American has been rising steadily for the
last five years.
   The percentage of Americans employed is the highest in history,
and the unemployment rate continues to drop down to its lowest
level since 1974. Since 1980, U.S. manufacturing has increased its
productivity almost three times as fast as in the seven previous
years.
   Inflation remains low, while the gross national product growth
this year and last has exceeded even our own optimistic
expectations.
   Somehow our opponents have convinced themselves that this record
growth, vibrant job creation and more productive economy is bad
news, and they say its all the fault of Reaganomics. Well I'd love
to take the blame or credit as the case may be, but that just
wouldn't be fair.
   All we did was get government out of your way. We cut taxes,
inflation and regulations and we let the American people take back
their own economy and run with it.
   In their effort to prove that this economic boom we're in is
really a bust, our opponents have had to weave some pretty tall
tales.
   One of those they tell about America is that we're threatened by
foreign investment.
   Well, to paraphrase what Joe Friday used to say in ``Dragnet,''
``Let's just look at the facts, Ma'am.'' Yes, foreigners now hold
about 12 percent of U.S. public debt, but that's down from 16
percent in 1978. Foreign resources also accounted for 10 percent of
total credit market funds last year, exactly the same as in the mid
1970's.
   But even so, foreign investment isn't something to be scared of.
It brings us a host of benefits including jobs and lower interest
rates for all Americans whether they be home buyers, small
businessmen, consumers or farmers.
   Writer@economist Warren Brooks makes a very good point. ``What
difference does it make,'' he asks, ``whether a Japanese company
owns a factory in Detroit or in Marysville, Ohio? Does someone
seriously think they might dismantle it brick by brick and ship it
back to Japan in the middle of the night?''
   I wonder if the workers in those plants think foreign investment
is such a bad thing, or the nearly three million other Americans
employed by foreign firms in the United States whose payrolls add
up to more than $70 billion and they pay about $8 billion in income
taxes to the United States Treasury. The fact is we live in a
global economy.
   We can be glad people in other countries choose to invest in the
vibrant and growing U.S. economy rather than their own nations.
   I don't blame them. I think America's a pretty good investment
too.
   Right now, however, there's a trade bill working its way through
Congress that could go a long way toward making America's bad
investment for Americans and foreigners alike. At this moment,
we've not seen the final bill. But from what we already know, we
still have very -- underline ``very'' -- serious reservations.
   We'll continue to work with the full Congress and the
congressional leadership to clear up these problems.
   But the bottom line is this -- I will veto a bad trade bill
before I will let a bad trade bill veto out economic expansion.
   Another important matter facing the nation today is the INF
Treaty, which I signed with General Secretary Gorbachev at our
Washington Summit meeting last December.
   This treaty will, for the first time, eliminate an entire class
of US and Soviet missiles. We called this the ``Zero Option'' when
I first proposed it in 1981.
   The treaty also requires the Soviet Union to make far greater
reductions now in its missile systems to reach equality with
us.This is an historic precedent, and we will apply it to other
arms negotiations as well.
   Finally, the treaty has the most comprehensive verification
regime in arms control history. This, too, is an important
precedent for other negotiations, particularly those on strategic
arms where an even more elaborate verification regime will be
required.
   In sum, this treaty represents what can be accomplished when we
negotiate from a position of strength.
   Action on it is now up to the United States Senate which must
give its advice and consent to ratification. I hope it will be
given expeditious consideration by the full Senate, and I urge all
senators to provide their advice and consent without reservation.
   It is a solid treaty, that it enhances the security of our
country and our allies.
   Until next week then, thank you for listening and God bless you.
</TEXT>
