<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Hijack 11thLd-Writethru a0541 04-09 0832</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hijack, 11th Ld - Writethru, a0541,0855</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Hijackers Kill Kuwaiti Security Guard, Free One Captive</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 11 grafs with released man taken to hospital,
quotes from Fantis. Picks up 14th graf pvs, `The radioed...</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NIC1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MONA ZIADE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LARNACA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Arab hijackers of a Kuwaiti jetliner
today shot and killed a Kuwaiti security guard on the plane and
then freed another captive after officials refused to refuel the
jet, authorities said.
   The identity of the man released was not immediately known, but
government spokesman Akis Fantis said he was about 25 years old and
unwell. Fantis said he was taken by ambulance to a hospital in
Larnaca.
   He gave no other details.
   Photographers at Larnaca airport said the man was seen leaving
the plane with a senior Palestine Liberation Organization
negotiator and two Cypriot officials after their fourth meeting
with the hijackers.
   Earlier, the body of a man who had been killed, his hands tied
behind his back, was tossed onto the tarmac. An ambulance took the
body away.
   A stairway was then rolled out to the plane. The PLO's deputy
director in Cyprus, Malaz Abdo, and the Cypriot officials stood on
the top step, talking to a hijacker standing in the doorway of the
jet, just behind the cockpit.
   The hijackers and negotiators held four separate meetings
lasting a total of more than 1{ hours before the captive was freed.
   There was no immediate word on what was said at the plane.
   Fantis said the man was freed ``as a sign of good will by the
hijackers.''
   Fantis identified the dead man _ apparently the hijackers' first
victim _ as a young Kuwaiti security guard. He said an X-ray and
pathologist's examination showed the man was shot three times in
the head and had a broken neck.
   Earlier, the pilot said the gunmen were beating passengers.
About 55 people, including at least half a dozen hijackers, were
aboard the Kuwait Airways Boeing 747 on the fifth day of the ordeal.
   The radioed message that the guard had been killed came at 11:32
a.m. (4:32 a.m. EDT), two minutes after a deadline set by the
gunmen for refueling.
   The tower had previously radioed that airport workers were
afraid to approach the plane, which the hijackers had warned they
would blow up if security men tried to move in.
   At 11 a.m., Director of Civil Aviation Michael Herodotou told
the hijackers by radio that he needed more time to negotiate with
the fuel workers, ``who are afraid to approach you.''
   A hijacker accused the tower of ``misleading'' him throughout
the night with bogus excuses for refusing to provide fuel. He also
said Kuwait would be responsible for the consequences.
   The hijackers' main demand is the release of 17 pro-Iranian
terrorists convicted in Kuwait of bombing the U.S. and French
embassies there in 1983. Kuwait refuses.
   The threat to kill a passenger followed a message from the tower
appealing to the hijackers ``for the release of passengers so the
refueling people can come to refuel your aircraft.''
   The hijackers started beating some of their captives early today
after authorities failed to meet an earlier deadline to refuel the
plane, the pilot told the tower.
   Asked if he could see the beatings, the pilot replied
``affirmative.''
   The hijackers earlier said six of the passengers were ``sick''
and that the Cypriots' refusal to refuel the jetliner ``is causing
the sickness,'' airport officials said.
   Tower officials had told the hijackers by radio that ground
crews were afraid to approach the jet and urged them to free some
of their captives ``persuade them ... to refuel.''
   The hijackers' spokesman snapped back: ``No way. We've given you
enough time. Our patience is running out.''
   The plane landed at Larnaca on Friday night after seven hours in
the air. After the plane had left Mashhad, Iran, Syria and Lebanon
refused to allow it to land. The pilot said its fuel tanks were
near empty when it landed in Larnaca.
   The plane was commandeered Tuesday on a flight from Bangkok to
Kuwait and 57 passengers were freed in Mashhad.
   Cypriot officials said the hijackers had today demanded 100,000
pounds of fuel, the plane's capacity, and were told they would have
to free some of the passengers first.
   A hijacker snapped back sharply: ``No passengers will be
released.'' Then he switched off.
   Cypriot Foreign Minister George Iacovou warned early today that
negotiations with the hijackers ``could take days.''
   The hostages include about 30 Kuwaitis, three of them members of
the Persian Gulf emirate's large ruling Al-Sabah family. The three
have been identified as Fadel Khaled al-Sabah, and his sisters
Anware and Ebtesam, distant relatives of the emir, Sheik Jaber
al-Ahmed al-Sabah.
   The hijackers put one of them, identified as Anware, on the
radio when the jetliner was circling over Beirut to plead with the
tower in a choking voice: ``I beg you, allow us to land. We have no
fuel left.''
</TEXT>
