<FILEID>AP-NR-04-09-88 1337EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-US-Mideast Bjt   04-09 0685</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Mideast, Bjt,650</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Arab-Israeli Distrust Doomed Shultz Peace Mission</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Private pleas from Arabs and Israelis and his
own instincts keep Secretary of State George P. Shultz engaged in a
Middle East peace effort that has produced little progress so far.
   Shultz left the troubled region Friday, vowing to return,
convinced that all the key parties _ Israel, Jordan and Palestinian
Arabs _ want to work out a settlement.
   He refused to be sidetracked by Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak
Shamir's resistance to a symbolic peace conference that would
launch the negotiations. Nor was he unnerved by a government
statement in Amman only hours after he left that Jordan would not
stand in for the Palestinians.
   Shultz said ``Israelis are as interested in peace and stability
as Jordan and the Palestinians, perhaps even more so.'' He
suggested the Jordanian statement was designed for public
consumption and did not reflect a more amenable stand taken
privately by King Hussein.
   Two of the basic elements in Shultz's plan are a peace
conference and exclusion of the Palestine Liberation Organization.
He said in an interview in Amman that the PLO sought to exterminate
Israel. Officials kept it off the air.
   Shultz would have Palestinians at the table, but as part of a
delegation with Jordan. He publicly opposed establishment of a
Palestinian state in the blacked-out interview.
   In Jerusalem, Shultz tried to convince Shamir that the peace
conference he opposed was not the one Shultz had in mind. The
Israeli leader does not want to give the Soviet Union an
opportunity to tilt a settlement in the Arabs' favor. Shultz told
him the United States would not let that happen.
   But Shamir held fast to his position, even though Shimon Peres,
the Israeli foreign minister, called negotiations within the
framework of a peace conference ``the only hope in town.''
Otherwise, Peres warned, the outlook in the region was bleak.
   Shamir's apprehension and Hussein's approval of a public policy
statement that implied criticism of Shultz's position reflect the
mistrust that hung over the five-day mission like a dark cloud.
   Shamir and other skeptical Israelis doubt there is an Arab
partner ready to follow the course taken a decade ago by the late
Egyptian President Anwar Sadat and make peace with the Jewish state.
   These Israelis are convinced Sadat and the late Lebanese
President Bashir Gemayal, who also sought peace with his neighbor,
were assassinated for extending an olive branch to Israel.
   Many times in the past Hussein has stepped to the brink of
negotiations and then faltered. Peres and Israelis who share his
trust in the king, are convinced this time the king means it.
Shultz urged the Israelis to consider Hussein their ``possible
partner'' in peace.
   On the Arab side, meanwhile, there are many obstacles in
Shultz's way.
   After the 1967 Six-Day war, in which the Arabs took an
embarrassing drubbing from the vastly outnumbered Israelis and lost
the West Bank, Gaza, the Golan Heights and East Jerusalem, the
Arabs vowed not to negotiate or recognize Israel.
   In 1974, they declared the PLO to be the Palestinians' sole,
legitimate representative. The PLO undertook a terrorism campaign
against Israel, the United States and moderate Palestinians.
   The Arab positions, and a basic resistance to a Jewish state in
the Middle east, are formidable roadblocks to Shultz.
   Moreover, Shamir and Peres would retain at least part of the
West Bank. Shultz told the Arabs candidly that recovering all of
the lost territory simply was not ``in the cards.''
   And yet, Shultz said he would not give up.
   Frequently describing himself as stubborn, Shultz said he could
feel it in his bones that the Arabs and Israelis eventually will
come around.
   ``Who's afraid to struggle against odds?'' he said Friday in
Amman. ``You have to be willing to do it. What am I saving myself
for anyway?
   ``I've got a few more months to go here and I want to try to
leave something constructive for the region and for my successors.
So I am going to put my back into it, why not?''
</TEXT>
