<DOCNO> AP880409-0084 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-09-88 1425EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Posner-Homeless     04-09 0815</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Posner-Homeless,0839</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>One of Nation's Wealthiest Men Turns Eyes To Homeless</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto MH4</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Victor Posner, one of the nation's highest paid
executives who runs a multibillion-dollar business empire, has
traded the executive suite for the mean streets as he embarks on a
court-ordered campaign to aid the homeless.
   Posner pleaded no contest in February to a charge of income tax
fraud for inflating the value of a land donation. He was sentenced
to fund a $3 million program to study the extent of homelessness in
south Florida and come up with some solutions.
   In addition, since his sentencing the 69-year-old Posner has
spent one day a week as a volunteer at Camillus House, a Miami
shelter for the down-and-out.
   ``Since February I have been studying and learning about the
problems of the homeless both nationally and in Florida,'' Posner
told U.S. District Judge Eugene Spellman last week.
   But the practical businessman noted, ``All the studies in the
world will not help one homeless person. ... You must give the
homeless a home so they will feel like people, not animals.''
   The self-made industrialist, who dropped out of high school at
13, runs a 40-company empire that has been valued at about $4
billion. Business Week named him the nation's top-paid chief
executive for 1985 with an estimated salary of $12.7 million. In
1986 he slipped to third, at $8.4 million.
   His legal troubles, however, took him from the rarefied
atmosphere of high finance to helping on the bread line at Camillus
House.
   Brother Paul Johnson, the Roman Catholic clergyman who runs
Camillus House, said Posner's eyes have been opened by the
experience, which the judge ordered as part of his probation.
   ``I was surprise and pleased,'' said Johnson. ``He was quite a
bit concerned with the people.''
   Posner serves food, hands out clothing and signs people into the
shelter at night, Johnson said. But the Alcoholics Anonymous and
substance abuse meetings seem to have affected the high-powered
businessman the most.
   ``He commented that the guys were intelligent,'' he said. ``I
think he was very surprised about that _ it made him realize they
really are victims of substance abuse.''
   Johnson said Posner's instincts are generous, almost to a fault.
At one point the clergyman kidded the multimillionaire about giving
out too much bread on the food line.
   ``He was giving them all they wanted,'' said Johnson. ``He told
me I could always get more.''
   Posner has shown his generosity before. He donated $100,000 to a
fund for Ronnie DeSillers, a Miami boy who died last year in
Pittsburgh after three unsuccessful liver transplants. DeSillers'
mother, Maria, is accused of misusing some of the funds raised for
her son.
   But Posner has also shown an insensitivity that angers his
detractors.
   After his first conviction on fraud charges _ which was later
thrown out because jurors had received outside information about
the case _ Posner said: ``These people on the jury are making $150
a week. They're poor people. They just don't understand.''
   The U.S. attorney's office denounced Posner's sentence to
charity as a slap-on-the-hand for wrongdoing that could have sent
Posner to prison for 40 years.
   ``Laudable as the project envisioned by this court may be, we
submit it would disserve and cause disrespect for our system of
justice, and only emphasize that the rich can trade money for
liberty while the poor cannot,'' U.S. Attorney Leon Kellner said
last Monday in a motion challenging the sentence.
   Posner and his attorney, well-known Washington lawyer Edward
Bennett Williams, told Spellman they would go ahead with the $3
million homeless project, whether or not that part of the sentence
was upheld. Williams must reply formally within 30 days to
Kellner's motion.
   The project will be monitored by Spellman and a 10-member
blue-ribbon committee of prominent area residents. The first part,
due to be finished by May 16, is a census of the homeless in Dade,
Broward and Palm Beach counties, who they are, and what resources
are available to them.
   Next, Posner said, should come some kind of pilot program that
shows what can be done.
   ``I will come to you with what will solve the problem,'' Posner
told the judge.
   Although he's paying for the study, Posner emphasizes it was
mandated by the judge, and the industrialist clearly is more
interested in the project itself. He is already talking up
federally subsidized housing plans as a realistic approach to help
the homeless.
   Sister Jeanne O'Loughlin, president of Barry Univeristy, which
is administering the study, said she hopes the money and attention
Posner is giving to the homeless will be the catalyst for what
could become a $300 million program. And she said she expects
Posner to stay involved.
   ``He has a very fast mind,'' she said. ``He's creating solutions
even before we give him all the data.''
</TEXT>
