<1ST_LINE>r p AM-MississippiDemocrats     04-09 0420</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mississippi Democrats,0433</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mississippi Democrats Re-elect Party Chairman Over Governor's
Candidate</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT NAYLOR JR.</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mississippi Democrats dealt a major blow
Saturday to the influence of newly inaugurated Gov. Ray Mabus,
retaining the nation's only black party chairman over the candidate
backed by the governor.
   The heated campaign between Ed Cole, an assistant to Sen. John
Stennis, D-Miss., and Billie Thompson, a white Tupelo
businesswoman, had been seen by some as the sign of a split in the
party. However, Cole, Thompson, and a spokesman for Mabus, who did
not attend, all said the party would remain unified.
   Cole, 43, who became chairman in November when his predecessor
resigned, received 56 of the 97 votes cast to win a full four-year
term. Thompson was the choice of 41 members of the 100-member
committee. Two members were absent and one who attended did not
vote.
   Thompson was a strong supporter of Mabus during his successful
campaign last year. Cole supported former Gov. Bill Waller in the
first primary, but switched to Mabus in the runoff.
   Thompson said she had offered Cole her congratulations and
``pledged him my total and complete support.
   ``I really think the party is going to get together. We don't
have any choice,'' she said.
   Democrats face major elections this year with 4th District Rep.
Wayne Dowdy, a Democrat, facing 5th District Republican Rep. Trent
Lott in the race to succeed Stennis, who is retiring after 41 years
in the Senate.
   Democrats, who generally dominate Mississippi politics, also
face strong Republican opposition in the races for Dowdy's and
Lott's seats.
   Cliff Treyens, Mabus' director of communications, said the
governor was called at the Governor's Mansion and informed of the
outcome of Saturday's vote and his reaction was to congratulate
Cole.
   ``We knew it would be a tough effort,'' Treyens said.
   Mabus had refused to comment publicly on the fight.
   Cole said he ``did not ask for a fight with the governor,'' but
wanted Mabus to ``accept that he belongs to our party and our party
does not belong to him.''
   Cole took over as party head when Steve Patterson of Jackson
resigned before announcing his unsusccessful bid for the party's
nomination in the 4th Congressional District.
   Patterson, who supported Cole's effort to win a full term and
said he was ``tickled to death'' with the outcome.
   While the fight over the chairmanship had been described as
split along racial lines, all the nominating and seconding speeches
were made by blacks.
</TEXT>
