<FILEID>AP-NR-04-09-88 1612EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CigaretteSuit     04-09 0547</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cigarette Suit,0564</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Plaintiffs End Case in Tobacco Trial, Cigarette Makers Take Over</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL J. WAKIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The case against three cigarette companies
accused of liability in the lung-cancer death of Rose Cipollone
began with a review of 60 years of research into the health effects
of smoking.
   It ended this week with some observers in the federal courtroom
weeping as Mrs. Cipollone's husband, Antonio, gave a tearful
account of his wife's death.
   In between, the jury heard expert witnesses discuss cancer, Mrs.
Cipollone's 40-year smoking addiction, her medical condition, and
how cigarettes are advertised and marketed. Perhaps most damaging
to the industry was the blitz of secret internal documents obtained
over years of court-ordered pre-trial discovery by Cipollone's
lawyers.
   The documents and testimony by researchers provided the most
sensational grist for tobacco opponents, who seized on the
information as a major aid in future lawsuits.
   The evidence included memorandums that spoke of the ``hurdle''
of the smoking and health issue, of the risk that selling a safer
cigarette would bring more liability lawsuits, and of the public
relations ``war'' against health charges.
   The trial began Feb. 1. Except for testimony in early March by
an addiction expert who described Mrs. Cipollone's smoking habits,
it was only toward the end of the plaintiffs' case that Mrs.
Cipollone came to life for the jury.
   In the past few weeks her daughter took the stand and
depositions from Mrs. Cipollone's sisters were read to the jury.
Jurors also heard Mrs. Cipollone's own words in a deposition made
before her death at age 58 in 1984.
   On Wednesday, Cipollone testified.
   He is seeking damages from the defendants _ Lorillard Inc.,
Philip Morris Co. and Liggett Group Inc. _ charging that they
failed to do enough research on cigarettes and health, to tell the
public what they did know, and to put a safer product on the market.
   The industry, which has never lost such a case, is focusing on
the individual as the key to its defense, which began Thursday.
   The companies argue that it was Mrs. Cipollone's choice to smoke
as an intelligent, independent and strong-willed woman who knew the
risks of smoking, at least as articulated by critics. The industry
does not acknowledge that cigarettes are a proven cause of cancer.
   The companies began presenting their case with an economic
historian who testified about the information Mrs. Cipollone would
have had available to her _ namely hundreds of articles on the
risks of smoking that appeared in newspapers she read.
   Morris attorney Peter Bleakley said Friday the defendants' case
should last three to four weeks.
   This week, they expect to call Mrs. Cipollone's brother to the
stand to testify about what she knew and heard about smoking and
health.
   Then come more excerpts of Mrs. Cipollone's testimony and
experts on consumer behavior, marketing, cancer and addiction to
counter evidence by the plaintiff's experts.
   Both sides agree on a fundamental decision the jury has to make.
   Did Mrs. Cipollone believe smoking was legitimately dangerous,
and if she didn't, was it the industry's fault?
   ``It's going to come down to how much personal responsibility
you put on her, and how much you put on the defendants,'' said
Cipollone attorney Cynthia A. Walters.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
