<DOCNO> AP880409-0097 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-09-88 1615EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Dukakis     04-09 0585</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis,610</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Calls For National Law On Factory Closings</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CALIFORNIA, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis, on a brief foray into an
economically depressed coal and steel area, called Saturday for
enactment of a national law on plant closings and said, ``I know
what it's like to work with communities like this one.''
   Campaigning for the Democratic presidential nomination, the
Massachusetts governor appeared at a mine workers union parade in
southwestern Pennsylvania before flying to upstate New York.
   The current delegate leader in the three-candidate race, Dukakis
hopes victories in upcoming primaries in New York, Pennsylvania and
Ohio will effectively clinch his claim to the nomination.
   Dukakis and rivals Jesse Jackson and Sen. Albert Gore Jr. are
concentrating on New York, which holds its primary on April 19.
Pennsylvania votes a week later, and Ohio the the week after that.
   Asked to differentiate himself from Jackson, Dukakis replied,
``I'm not just a talker, I'm a doer. I know what it's like to work
with communities like this one. I know what it takes to bring them
back.''
   Dukakis was asked whether that meant as criticism of Jackson,
whose ability as a speaker far outshines that of his rivals.
   ``No, it's a statement of fact about the strengths I bring to
this campaign,'' he replied.
   From Pennsylvania, Dukakis flew to Rochester, N.Y., and toured a
high-tech plant.
   His final stop of the day was a community forum at a steel
workers union hall in Dunkirk, N.Y., outside of Buffalo.
   People who lined the main street of California to watch the
parade and hear Dukakis told of a community that has lost thousands
of jobs in the past 10 years.
   A nearby steel plant once employed 10,000 and now has a skeletal
force of 400. Coal mines that employed thousands more have shut
down or installed machinery that drastically cut the need for
miners.
   ``This is the most depressed area in the country,'' said one
retired miner. ``It's going down, down, down.''
   ``Twenty-six-year-old boys, as healthy as can be and they can't
get jobs,'' interjected another.
   A woman said Franklin D. Roosevelt was the last great president.
   ``There was a complete turnaround,'' she said. ``We had
confidence.''
   As for the current candidates, ``I don't see an outstanding
leader in none of them.''
   People who voiced support for Dukakis said it was because they
felt he would be pro-union.
   ``He's strictly for labor, that's what they're after, labor,''
said Edward Mathews, a retired member of the United Mine Workers of
America.
   ``I know what you've been going through here in the Mon
(Monongahela) Valley,'' said Dukakis. ``Years and years of lost
jobs.''
   He said the election was ``about people, about jobs'' and the
next president ``must be someone who knows how to build a strong
economy and has done it.''
   He said Massachusetts has ``one of the most comprehensive plant
closing laws in the nation'' that not only required companies to
give long advance notice of plans to shut down a plant but also to
require them to provide extended health care benefits to displaced
workers.
   He said he would press for enactment of similar legislation on a
national basis if elected president.
   At a news conference after his speech, Dukakis said that Japan
requires companies to give three years' notice before closing a
plant.
   ``I don't think the American people ought to tolerate what's
been permitted to happen to people and families and communities
like this one,'' he said.
</TEXT>
