<1ST_LINE>u i AM-SouthAfrica 1stLd-Writethru   04-09 0919</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-South Africa, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0508,0943</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Hammers Opponents In Bid To Hold Right-Wing Support</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: INSERTS graf after 5th pvs, `So far...' to ADD parties'
strength in Parliament. Pick up 6th pvs, `The setbacks...'</NOTE>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GREG MYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The governing National Party,
faced with dwindling support among right-wing whites, has launched
an aggressive political and military offensive aimed at its
numerous foreign and domestic opponents.
   In recent weeks, President P.W. Botha's government has
effectively banned 18 opposition groups, arrested prominent
clergymen, threatened and raided neighboring countries in pursuit
of alleged terrorists, and brazenly challenged the United Nations
to impose sanctions.
   The hardline actions have provided fresh ammunition to
anti-apartheid activists abroad and suggest the government has
chosen to ignore virtually all its critics except the conservative
whites who contend Botha is capitulating to the nation's 26 million
black majority.
   Under apartheid, blacks have no vote in national affairs. The 5
million whites control the economy and maintain separate districts,
schools and health services.
   So far, the Nationalists' tough-guy posture has not worked.
White voters opted for the staunchly pro-apartheid Conservative
Party in three special parliamentary elections in March, and the
Conservatives appear headed for additional gains in nationwide
municipal elections in October.
   The Nationalists now hold 133 seats in the 178-member dominant
white chamber of Parliament. Conservatives hold 23, the
anti-apartheid Progressive Federal Party holds 17 and other parties
hold five.
   The setbacks led two pro-government newspapers to question the
political prospects of the National Party and its vaguely defined
reform proposals.
   ``There can be no survival without reform,'' said The Citizen.
``But without providing the whites with the security they crave,
the National Party will have a tough time surviving.''
   ``Numerous Nationalists feel the road ahead should be more
clearly spelled out,'' said Beeld, an Afrikaans-language daily.
``We get the impression that (the ordinary man) now feels the NP
has risen so high above him that it has completely lost contact.''
   The National Party says it seeks gradual race reform, with
blacks gaining a voice in national politics but with whites
maintaining ultimate control. The Conservatives oppose all
concessions to blacks and seek to rescind reforms implemented in
recent years.
   Government opponents, including blacks, white liberals and
foreign critics, say the reforms are totally inadequate. But their
voices have been dismissed as irrelevant during the increasingly
bitter debate between the Nationalists and the Conservatives.
   Ironically, the government's crackdown began at a time when
black unrest was at its lowest level in years, the foreign
sanctions campaign was on the wane and domestic opposition groups
had been crippled by detentions and legal restrictions.
   When the government released Govan Mbeki, leader of the African
National Congress guerrilla group, last November, there was
widespread speculation of additional releases and increased
political reform.
   Mbeki's release did not spawn any upsurge in demonstrations or
violence, but it did produce a backlash among conservative whites
who felt Botha was caving in to black militants.
   Since that time, the government has sought to make clear that it
will protect the privileged position of the white minority.
   The latest crackdown began on Feb. 24, when the government
banned 18 leading anti-apartheid organizations from participating
in politics and placed individual restrictions on more than a dozen
activists.
   The army raided a house in Gaborone, Botswana, on March 28,
killing four people they said were guerrillas of the African
National Congress.
   Six other congress officials have been killed in foreign
countries this year. The most recent was Dulcie September, the
group's representative to France, killed in Paris on March 29.
South Africa has denied responsibility in the deaths, but
repeatedly has said it will enter other countries in pursuit of ANC
members.
   Anglican Archbishop Desmond Tutu, the 1984 Nobel Peace Prize
winner, and 24 other clerics were arrested March 29 during a
peaceful demonstration near Parliament in Cape Town. Botha has on
several occasions warned the clergy to avoid political
confrontation.
   The government on March 21 shut down the New Nation newspaper
for 12 weeks, saying it ``fanned revolution.'' Several more
publications appear likely to be closed.
   South Africa's ambassador to the United Nations, Les Manley,
recently told the Security Council to ``do your damndest'' and
impose sanctions. A subsequent sanctions measured died because of
vetoes from Britain and the United States.
   Political observers say the recent string of actions indicates
the National Party now perceives the Conservatives as a genuine
threat to the 40 years of unbroken rule of the Nationalists.
   The government regularly attacks the Conservatives and their
close ally, the Afrikaner Resistance Movement, a paramilitary,
white-supremacist organization that uses Nazi-style symbols.
   Botha recently made public a letter he sent to movement leader
Eugene TerreBlanche, who advocates creation of a whites-only
Afrikaner state.
   ``You are building emotions around nebulous dreams which have
little relationships to the practical circumstances and demands of
South Africa,'' Botha wrote.
   ``Throughout the world there is enough undeserved hatred toward
the Afrikaner, so we cannot afford in this country that Afrikaners,
by their own actions, are made the subject of hatred and
ridicule,'' Botha added.
   Botha and his party, having promoted gradual change for the past
several years, now face the prospect of losing their traditional
Afrikaner base if they continue to call for apartheid reforms.
   ``It would be foolish (for the Nationalists) to go back on
reforms,'' said Willem Kleynhans, a prominent political scientist.
``But if they introduce new reforms they will lose support. They
are in a tight spot.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
