<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     04-09 0464</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0475</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cold Front Spreads Snow & Rain Across Central Part Of Nation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A cold front sliding across the central part of the nation
Saturday spread snow across Wyoming and rain across the Plains into
Texas.
   Heavy snow was reported during the morning at South Pass, south
of Lander, Wyo., with more than 8 inches falling in about five
hours. An inch of snow was on the ground at Rawlins, while most of
central and southern Wyoming had occasional light snow but with no
significant accumulation.
   Light snow also was reported in the foothills of Colorado
including the Denver area, and in parts of Minnesota, with one inch
at Alexandria.
   Light rain fell across western Iowa, southeastern Nebraska, much
of eastern Kansas and northern Oklahoma. Rain was mixed with snow
in northeastern Kansas at Fort Riley.
   Showers were scattered across southern and western Texas, and
afternoon temperatures stayed around 60 degrees as far south as
south-central Texas.
   At the northern end of the cold front, Kalispell, Mont., had a
record low of 18 degrees, and Missoula, Mont., tied its record low
of 19.
   East of the cold front, highs in the 70s were reported in the
Mississippi Valley as far north as Wisconsin.
   But cold air still covered the mid-Atlantic states with readings
mostly in the 50s from eastern North Carolina to New Jersey, and it
was chillier still in the Appalachians from New York to West
Virginia. Binghamton, N.Y., had a 2 p.m. reading of just 34 degrees.
   A frost advisory was posted for the mountains, foothills and
eastern Piedmont region of South Carolina. And farther to the
south, Key West, Fla., had a record low of 59 degrees.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 27
degrees at Yellowstone National Park, Wyo., and Rawlins, Wyo., to
90 at Ontario, Calif. The early-morning low for the day was zero at
West Yellowstone, Mont., and Yellowstone National Park.
   For Sunday, rain was forecast from Texas across eastern Kansas
and Missouri to the upper Mississippi Valley, with a few
thunderstorms in southeastern Texas and the middle Mississippi
Valley. Scattered drizzle or snow flurries were forecast across New
Hampshire and Maine. Widely scattered showers and thunderstorms
were forecast for southern Florida.
   Highs only in the 30s were predicted in northern Maine and
northern Minnesota; in the 40s or 50s from the Rockies and Plains
across the northern half of the Mississippi Valley, the northern
Great Lakes, New York and northern Pennsylvania to New England; in
the 80s in southern Florida, southeastern Louisiana and the
southern tip of Texas, and in southwestern Oregon and much of
California; in the 90s in the desert Southwest; and in the 60s or
70s across most of the rest of the nation.
</TEXT>
