<HEAD>Yale Students Demand That School Drop South African Investments</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   NEW HAVEN, Conn. (AP ) _ About 100 student protesters
demonstrated outside the monthly meeting of the Yale Corporation on
Saturday to demand that the university sell off stock in
corporations doing business with South Africa.
   The demonstration was sponsored by the Black Student Alliance at
Yale and the Coalition Against Apartheid.
   As of June 1987, according to figures released by the Yale
Office of Public Information, the university had invested $213
million in corporations doing business in South Africa.
   Most board members refused to comment on the divestment issue or
the protest as they left the meeting. One, Maxine Frank-Singer,
said, ``There are always considerations of divestments because we
are constantly monitoring (the companies).'' But she said the
corporation didn't discuss changing the policy.
