<2ND_LINE>AM-Oyster Men,0315</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>All-Male Oyster Dinner Begrudgingly Opens Doors to Women</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Lasociete is cq.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WELCH, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Women with tickets got in, photographers
were kept out, and the previously male-only 40 & 8 Lasociete's
annual oyster dinner and political get-together went off without a
hitch.
   The group, an offshoot of the American Legion, had earlier said
it would continue to bar women from its 25th annual fund-raising
dinner at Mount View High School on Friday night.
   But after Republican congressional candidate Marianne Brewster
kicked up a fuss, the group backed down and said any woman with a
previously purchased ticket would be admitted. No tickets were sold
at the door.
   The group also barred news photographers from the dinner, but
allowed one television crew inside.
   Brewster was one of a handful of women who showed up at the
event, which drew about 1,200 people. State Democratic Chairwoman
Sally Richardson was the guest of state Sen. H. Truman Chafin, who
was indicted Thursday on a felony bribery charge.
   Chafin said he wouldn't let an indictment keep him from an
important political rally, while Richardson said she had made the
appointment to attend the dinner with Chafin ``some time ago.''
   Society members were unhappy about the women's presence and the
press coverage that preceded the event.
   ``It's no good,'' said Larry Johnson of Kimball. ``Men like to
be together by themselves once in a while.''
   The oyster dinner is a traditional campaign stop for state and
local politicians as well as a way of raising money for youth
sports programs.
   Society member J.R. Miller said the group planned to meet Sunday
to decide whether the event will be terminated because of this
year's controversy. When announcing its decision to let women in
this year, the group indicated this would be the final year for the
event.
</TEXT>
