<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Bush 1stLd-Writethru a0559 04-09 0657</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0559,600</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Worries That Democrats Are Getting The Attention</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: INSERTS 1 graf after 7th graf pvs bgng, `But that,' to UPDATE
with Bush comment on any foreign trip being substantive; INSERTS 3
grafs after 17th graf pvs bgng, `The general,' to UPDATE with Bush
comments on close election, Jackson and Dukakis</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ST.PETERSBURG, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush, his lock on the
Republican convention assured and his campaign coffers filled,
fretted Saturday that Democrats are capturing all the attention.
   ``I've got to look more frantic,'' he joked to reporters
travelling with him on Air Force Two.
   `You pick up the papers and it's all the three (Democratic)
campaigns there. ... And we're finished,'' the vice president said.
   Bush, running virtually unopposed for the GOP nomination, said
he hoped to retain visibility between now and the convention ``with
events. There are things we can do to give us a little more
attention.''
   Aides said that an official foreign trip in early summer was a
distinct possibility.
   ``I think we've just got to recognize ... we're not going to get
the intensive political coverage,'' Bush said.
   ``But that doesn't bother me. The spotlight is so sharp,'' he
said. ``Once the convention starts, you don't worry about it.''
   In Miami, Bush told reporters that any trip he took out of the
country ``would have to be substantive, not cosmetic.''
   Bush attended a $250-a-plate fund-raising barbecue and had a
similar event planned for later in the day in Miami.
   The vice president is campaigning at a leisurely pace, with a
series of fund raisers arranged before his campaign last week
reached the $27 million federal limit for pre-convention
contributions.
   Bush staff aides said money raised on the current two-day swing
through Texas and Florida, and from events scheduled for next week
in New York and Connecticut, will be used toward a $2.8 million
``compliance fund.''
   The fund, which is exempt from the federal limit, will be used
for expenses incurred in complying with Federal Election Commission
rules.
   Once those funds are raised, however, the well-heeled campaign
will accept no further contributions itself but will turn its
attention to helping the Republican National Committee raise some
$8 million for the general election, according to campaign
treasurer Fred Bush.
   Bush said he intends to continue campaigning, particularly in
populous states with primaries to come.``There is no way that
anybody is going to get elected in this country if you don't pay
proper attention to the big states,'' Bush told reporters.
   ``I will flesh out and extend the themes that we have talked
about all during the primary,'' he said.
   ``I don't think I have to have a six-point program on every
subject ... but I think the voters will want to know what I'm going
to do on some of these important areas.''
   The general election contest ``is going to be close and it is
going to be a tough race,'' he said.
   ``It always is after an eight-year cycle,'' he said later in an
interview with local reporters.
   Bush said Democrats Jesse Jackson and Michael Dukakis ``believe
the same things on how to solve the problems of this country and
they're both wrong.''
   ``Both of them come out of the more liberal tradition,'' he said.
   Aides said Bush would probably campaign for two or three days
each week between now and the summer conventions. Campaign
officials, who spoke on the condition of anonymity, also said that
an out-of-country official visit for the vice president was likely
in June, either to Europe or the Far East, in an effort to raise
his visibility.
   Late Friday, Bush and his wife, Barbara, made a surprise
appearance in Fort Worth at a lampoon dinner sponsored by Texas
journalists.
   ``There must be some mistake,'' Bush told the annual Texas
Gridiron dinner. ``I thought this was the wimp convention.''
   His self-mocking joke brought howls from the audience.
</TEXT>
