<FILEID>AP-NR-04-09-88 1736EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-KaiserEstate     04-09 0343</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Kaiser Estate,0353</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Japanese Billionaire Pays Record $38 Million For Rest of Kaiser
Estate</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One of Japan's wealthiest men has added to his
extensive Hawaii real estate holdings by paying a record $38
million to acquire the remaining 5.5 acres of the Kaiser Estate,
his attorney said.
   Billionaire Genshiro Kawamoto paid $4.5 million earlier this
year to purchase the estate's ``Picnic House'' property and picked
up an option to buy the rest of the estate built by industrialist
Henry Kaiser.
   When another interested buyer offered $38 million, Kawamoto
exercised his option, according to his attorney, Robert J. Lombardi.
   Real estate agent Scully Rogers, broker for the sale, and
appraiser Robert Hastings said the purchase price was the highest
ever paid for a residential property in Hawaii.
   The previous record of $21 million was set in March, also by a
Japanese buyer.
   Hawaii has drawn more Japanese property investment than any
other state, including an estimated $3 billion since 1986, and the
increasing Japanese appetite has sparked controversy recently.
   Honolulu Mayor Frank Fasi last month proposed state legislation
to prohibit the sale of residential, agricultural or preservation
property to anyone who is not a U.S. citizen, has no plans to
become a citizen or would not live on the land at least half the
year. The proposal has little chance of being considered by the
legislature because it was submitted late in the session.
   Kawamoto has spent an additional $36.9 million to buy 130 acres
of land and 142 homes and condominiums on Oahu, the island where
Honolulu is located.
   Kawamoto said Friday he planned to use the estate, sold by a
trust for the Goldman family, as a vacation home while in Hawaii on
monthly trips from Japan.
   The Picnic House purchase included nearly two acres of land and
a boat harbor. The latest purchase includes two houses and an
Olympic-size swimming pool.
   ``To go through them is like a James Bond movie,'' Rogers said.
``You lose track of the amenities because you are so in awe of
them.''
</TEXT>
