<FILEID>AP-NR-04-09-88 1737EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-People-TrumpTaxes     04-09 0301</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-People-Trump Taxes,0310</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Trump Gets Tax Break on Mar-A-Lago Estate</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Robb Maass is cq in 6th graf</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Real estate tycoon Donald Trump was
saved $86,000 when a court ruled that his taxes on a 118-room
mansion should be based on its purchase price, not on the county's
calculation of its value.
   Trump bought Mar-A-Lago in 1985 for $7 million. It was the first
time the estate built in 1926 had been sold.
   However, Palm Beach County property appraisers had valued the
property at $11.5 million and Trump's taxes were figured on that
basis.
   Circuit Judge Richard Burk ruled in Trump's favor on Friday.
   ``It is significant to note that this is the only purchase ever
of this property,'' Burk said. ``Surely in this case, one sale does
in fact make a market.''
   Trump's attorney, Robb Maass, said the decision was ``a very
proper way of looking at the market value.''
   But attorney Gaylord Wood, who represented Palm Beach County
Property Appraiser Rebecca Walker, promised to appeal.
   ``Donald Trump has demonstrated once again that there is no one
better in this country at buying things for less than what they are
worth,'' Wood said.
   Trump challenged the assessment in a 1987 lawsuit after the
county said he owed $208,000 in taxes on Mar-a-Lago. Trump
contended that the bill should be only $122,000, including a 4
percent discount for early payment.
   During two days of testimony last month, two real estate
appraisers explained the methods they used to place a value on
Mar-a-Lago. Even though both appraisers used a system that
considers the value of comparable properties, their assessments
were $3.4 million apart.
   In his ruling, however, Burk wrote that Trump's $7 million
purchase price established Mar-a-Lago's market value because the
estate has no equal.
</TEXT>
