<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Cuomo-Draft 2ndLd-Writethru a0573 04-09 0598</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cuomo-Draft, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0573,560</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cuomo: I Don't Want Draft And I Won't Endorse</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New throughout with second interview with Cuomo; no pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARC HUMBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Mario Cuomo said Saturday, ``I've ruled
out a draft'' for the Democratic presidential nomination, but he
declined to endorse a candidate until after the primaries end June
7.
   At a news conference Saturday and in two later conversations
with The Associated Press, Cuomo said he did not want the
Democratic party to draft him or anybody else as its presidential
nominee.
   But in the second conversation with the AP, he refused to say
point-blank that he would turn down the nomination if he were
drafted at the Democratic National Convention in Atlanta July 18-21.
   Cuomo was attempting to douse a draft movement begun during the
week by a former Democratic congressman, but the confusion arose
when he declined to close the door on circumstances that might
arise at the convention.
   ``I've ruled out a draft,'' Cuomo said.
   Cuomo's statements about a draft and endorsements came as he
released a letter to former New York Rep. Richard Ottinger, a
leader of a draft-Cuomo move in New York, asking him ``not to go
forward with your intention to encourage a draft.''
   In his letter, Cuomo also said he would not endorse any of the
Democratic candidates before the end of the primaries June 7. The
governor explained that he wanted to be uncommitted at that point
so he could help the front-runner collect enough uncommitted votes
to put him over the top for the nomination.
   Asked to clarify his statements on a draft, Cuomo told the AP,
``We can go around forever. ... I could have ended it a long time
ago by saying `General Sherman said and so I will say,' but I'm not
going to do that because that means that you accept the principle
that you have to use whatever language the press says you must use
to meet their requirements and they'll keep inventing new
language.''
   It was Civil War Gen. William Tecumseh Sherman who rejected an
appeal to draft him as the Republican nominee in 1884 with the
political disclaimer: ``I will not accept if nominated and will not
serve if elected.''
   ``I'm not going to use your language,'' said Cuomo. ``I said,
`How could I rule it out as counterproductive and unwise and still
accept it?' I have ruled it out.''
   Cuomo announced more than a year ago that he would not seek his
party's presidential nomination and has taken steps to keep his
name off state primary ballots.
   And despite his repeated insistence that he did not want to be a
candidate questions have persisted over whether he would accept the
nomination if it were offered to him anyway.
   Cuomo started out Saturday with a news conference in which he
indicated that he would reject a draft but when pressed to clarify
his position, he complained to reporters about ``your insistence
for magic language.''
   After the news conference, he telephoned the AP to say he was
making his statement because ``obviously this is in the midst of
the New York primary (campaign) and I don't want any confusing
signals to be sent to anyone.''
   But the confusion continued.
   After a story was transmitted saying that Cuomo ruled out
accepting a draft, his press secretary, Gary Fryer, called to draw
the line at the word ``accept.''
   ``I asked him that specifically and he said `I never told him
that; I'm not going to tell him that,''' Fryer said.
</TEXT>
