<1ST_LINE>d a AM-BRF--MissileTest     04-09 0127</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Missile Test,0130</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ship-Launched Cruise Missile Tested</HEAD>
<DATELINE>POINT MUGU, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Tomahawk cruise missile launched
from a Navy ship off the California coast flew 500 miles and
successfully hit land targets in the desert Saturday, a spokesman
for the Pacific Missile Test Center said.
   The missile was launched from a launch pad aboard the ship in
the center's sea test range, said spokesman Ray Lucasey.
   The Tomahawk accurately hit three targets on the China Lake test
range 125 miles north of Los Angeles with unarmed ``bomblets,'' or
multiple warheads, and then successfully dived into a fourth
simulated target on the range.
   Officials expect the weapon system will be available to the
fleet by this fall.
   The ship involved in the test was not identified.
</TEXT>
