<1ST_LINE>r a AM-LiverBoy     04-09 0310</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Liver Boy,0319</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Paves Way For Mexican Boy To Receive Life-Saving Liver
Operation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PASADENA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge has cleared the way for a state
agency to pay for a liver transplant for a 5-year-old Mexican boy
with chronic liver disease, who previously was denied aid because
he was not a U.S. resident.
   Superior Court Judge Robert Olsen rejected a California
Children's Services request Friday that would have made Armando
Vargas ineligible for state funds for the operation, which costs
approximately $150,000. The judge found that the boy is eligible
because his guardian is a California resident.
   Sharon Yackey, the deputy Los Angeles County counsel
representing Children's Services, a branch of the state Department
of Health Services, said the agency would not appeal the ruling.
   She also said the agency had approved funding for the operation
and contacted officials at the University of California, Los
Angeles, Medical Center, requesting that the boy be placed on the
hospital's donor list for a new liver.
   Armando and his family came to California seven weeks ago from
their home in central Mexico in hopes of getting the state-funded
surgery. They had previously been turned down in Texas.
   The boy, who doctors say can live only a matter of months
without a transplant, was not eligible for aid because he is not a
legal U.S. resident.
   But after news reports of his case, a group called the Right to
Life Committee established a guardianship for him so he could
qualify.
   On Friday, Olsen denied the California Children's Services
request to vacate the guardianship.
   The judge ruled that the boy was not a legal resident, but he
also determined that, as a ward of a legal guardian who is a
resident, the youth qualifies for the funds.
   ``It's an exciting victory,'' said Susan Carpenter-McMillan, a
spokeswoman for the Right to Life Committee.
</TEXT>
