<1ST_LINE>r a AM-WalkingHorses     04-09 0270</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Walking Horses,0278</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tennessee Walking Horse Industry to Fight Ruling Limiting Gait
Devices</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tennessee Walking Horse breeders are
seeking a stay of a recent court ruling restricting the use of
devices that give the horses their distinctive high-stepping
stride, their attorney said.
   The U.S. Department of Agriculture recently banned the stacked
shoes and limited the weight of leg chains used in showing the
horses.
   The department's ban followed a ruling last month by U.S.
District Judge Oliver Gasch, who ordered the new regulations after
reviewing a suit filed by the American Horse Protection Association
against the department. The association charged that the devices
caused soreness and swelling in the animals' legs.
   Proponents argued they are being penalized for abuses corrected
long ago, when chemical irritants were used on horses' hooves. They
say the new rules threaten the entire industry.
   The Tennessee Walking Horse Breeders' and Exhibitors'
Association will present arguments seeking a stay from Gasch on
Tuesday in Washington, said Walter Bussart, an attorney for the
group.
   The rules forbid the use of bracelet-like chains weighing more
than 6 ounces and padded shoes for walking horses. Chains of up to
10 ounces and stacked shoes 4 inches high had previously been
allowed.
   Several walking horse shows have been canceled or postponed
since Gasch's ruling in March, including one set for next weekend
in Jackson, Miss. That show is tentatively rescheduled for October,
officials said.
   The walking horse season usually ends with the National
Celebration in Shelbyville, Tenn., in September. Breeders have said
that show is also threatened unless the judge's ruling is stayed or
altered.
</TEXT>
