<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Gore 1stLd-Writethru   04-09 1042</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gore, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0586,1020,</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gore's Campaign Wants Strong NY Finish To Shake Up Race</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 3 grafs after 6th graf to UPDATE with comment from
Gore campaign manager; picks up 7th graf pvs, bgng: At least...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID ESPO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Albert Gore Jr.'s campaign has all but
given up on winning the New York primary on April 19 but wants a
strong enough showing to rekindle doubts about Michael Dukakis,
thus allowing for a late charge at the Democratic presidential
nomination.
   ``We've got to prove we can get a lot of Northern votes,'' said
one aide, speaking anonymnously. ``And if we do that I think the
race gets shaken up once again.''
   But Gore has been trying to find a Northern state where he could
run strongly since he vaulted near the front of the pack with
several border state victories on Super Tuesday a month ago.
   Since then, his campaign has encountered a string of defeats in
Illinois, Michigan, Connecticut, Wisconsin and elsewhere while
piling up a debt of $1.5 million. Even though he spent as much or
more on television advertising in some states as Dukakis, his best
showing of the past four weeks was 17 percent of the vote in
Wisconsin a week ago.
   He has gained only 49 delegates since Super Tuesday in The
Associated Press delegate count and now trails rivals Dukakis and
Jesse Jackson by more than 300 delegates.
   Thus, one aide conceded, and if he fails in New York, it will be
``very very difficult to go on in a meaningful way.''
   Nevertheless, Gore campaign manager Fred Martin insisted on
Saturday that strategy in New York is to win, not just do well.
   ``It's certainly true that we're underdogs,'' Martin said.
``It's certainly true that we're behind in the polls, but we are
trying to win this state.''
   ``Anyone who says differently doesn't know what he's talking
about,'' Martin said by telephone from New York.
   At least one Democrat says failure in New York could do more
than spell the end of Gore's 1988 Democratic candidacy,
particularly given the senator's decision to criticize black rival
Jackson.
   ``He'd better be careful that he's not burning bridges. New York
may pose a much more serious long-term risk to Gore than he may
imagine,'' said Robert G. Beckel, who is not advising any of this
year's Democratic presidential contenders after managing Walter F.
Mondale's bid in 1984.
   Beckel said that by attacking Jackson, Gore risks the animosity
of black voters not only in a national campaign, but in his home
state of Tennessee. ``It's a very risky strategy, and I frankly see
a lot more downside than I see upside for him.''
   An occasional adviser said that the impact on a future campaign
is on Gore's mind as he makes the rounds in 1988. ``Al believes
he's old enough to be president but too young to be vice president.
He hopes to leave a good impression and maybe he'll try again some
day,'' said this source, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   At the Dukakis campaign, aides believe that Gore cannot win the
nomination, but they fear that he could seriously damage their own
man's chances if he split the white vote and enabled Jackson to eke
out a victory.
   Thus, they seek to belittle Gore whenever they can, with Dukakis
pointing out that the senator has failed to carry a dingle
congressional district since Super Tuesday.
   ``We see it as a two-man race'' with Jackson, says Susan
Estrich, Dukakis' campaign manager. ``He's had one good day in this
campaign as far as I can tell,'' she said referring to Gore's
six-state victorties on Super Tuesday.
   Gore himself has not publicly discussed the long-term
implications of next week's primary, with 255 delegates at stake.
``New York has always been friendly to underdogs, and I am the
underdog,'' he said last week.
   To achieve his New York goal, Gore is making a strong appeal to
win New York's sizeable Jewish vote, supporting Israeli Prime
Minister Yitzhak Shamir's opposition to the Reagan administration's
peace proposal. And despite a $1.5 million campaign debt, has
embarked on a costly advertising campaign that also stresses his
record on environmental, civil rights and consumer issues in a bid
to woo voters who want a moderate alternative to Dukakis and
Jackson.
   In personal campaigning, Gore has attacked both Jackson and
Dukakis for lacking sufficient foreign policy experience. He
accused aides to the Massachusetts governor last week of saying
that a vote for Gore was a vote for Jackson _ a charge that Dukakis
denied. He also has accused Dukakis of being ``absurdly timid'' in
his treatment of Jackson.
   Coming at a time when many party officials are anxious to avoid
a prolonged battle for the nomination, Gore's criticisms have
earned him rebukes from New York Gov. Mario Cuomo and Democratic
Party Chairman Paul Kirk. ``It does not work and it's terribly
dangerous,'' Cuomo told one interviewer.
   Gore shook off the criticism and made it clear he intends to
continue portraying his rivals as short on foreign policy
experience. Spokesman Arlie Schardt said the senator ``is going to
continue campaigning just as vigorously pointing out the difference
with Dukakis and Jackson.''
   Schardt said the Gore campaign didn't view his comments as
negative campaigning, and aides said they knew of no current plans
for television commercials that would attack Dukakis or Jackson.
   Gore's aides concede he is starting at the back of the pack in
New York campaign _ his support in public polls is measured in
single digits _ but they insist a strong showing can scramble the
Democratic race.
   One aide, speaking on condition of anonymity, said Gore hopes to
enlist the support of Democrats who fear that Dukakis cannot lead
the party to victory in the fall, although the senator has
generally dropped this refrain in recent weeks.
   One aide says that when Jackson became the hot candidate in the
race recently, the fear over Dukakis ``was temporarily shelved
because Jackson is even less electable.''
   ``If we get a meaningful bite out of the apple (in New York) we
can go on to meaningful victories in other Northern states,''
including Pennsylvahia, Ohio and elsewhere, said one adviser.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
