<FILEID>AP-NR-04-09-88 1902EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Nicaragua     04-09 0523</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nicaragua,0540</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Technical Talks Suspended But Negotiator Optimistic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYNA BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Government and rebel officials are not
far from agreeing on technical aspects of a cease-fire even though
they suspended discussions because of some differences, a
negotiator said Saturday.
   ``I'm optimistic,'' said Paul Reichler, a Washington attorney
who is with the Sandinista government's negotiating delegation.
``We've come this far.''
   Talks between military leaders of the government and the rebels,
known as Contras, broke off Friday after four days of discussions.
Negotiators are dealing with the technical aspects of a 60-day
cease-fire that formally went into effect on April 1.
   Both sides agreed on seven zones where the Contras are to gather
during the cease-fire, but failed to agree on how the rebels would
receive supplies and ways of verifying compliance with the truce.
   The cease-fire is part of a peace plan leaders of the warring
parties agreed to on March 23. The pact called for the rebels to
gather in the cease-fire zones by April 15, but left details for
carrying out that plan to later technical discussions.
   On Thursday the Contras released a 34-point proposal outlining
rebel activity in the zones. The Sandinistas on Friday released a
25-point plan for the zones.
   Reichler said there were only two points in the Contra proposal
that were ``absolutely unacceptable, non-negotiable.''
   He said one would allow the rebels to ``periodically replace
arms, ammunition and war material, and the other would bar the
government from receiving military aid during the truce. Most of
Nicaragua's arms come from the Soviet bloc.
   Reichler said the Sandinistas were frustrated at not reaching an
agreement after six meetings. Earlier talks were held between
military delegations March 28-29.
   He said the Contras were unwilling to continue the talks
Saturday and called for a four-day recess.
   ``We're talking about a cease-fire, people's lives, and they
want to work 10-to-5 with a two-hour lunch,'' Reichler said.
   The government said technical subjects could be discussed
Friday, when high-level talks are scheduled to be held in Managua.
Those talks, called for under the peace plan, were to have opened
last Wednesday but the Contras asked for a postponement.
   Contra leader Adolfo Calero, in an interview from Miami, said
the Sandinistas were to blame for the breakdown of the technical
talks.
   He said he was not sure the Friday meeting would be held because
the government has not responded to the Contras' demand for free
access to political opposition figures during their visit to the
capital.
   In the peace pact, the rebels agreed to accept only humanitarian
aid delivered by a neutral organization, such as the International
Red Cross.
   The Sandinistas are insisting on inspection, but would allow the
goods to be delivered by air, land or sea to the zones.
   The Sandinistas have agreed to gradually release 3,300 political
prisoners, allow the Contras to take part in political dialogue and
restore democratic freedoms.
   Some 50,000 people have been killed or wounded in six years of
fighting.
   The peace plan was signed after three days of talks at the
border post at Sapoa, 90 miles south of Managua.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
