<FILEID>AP-NR-04-09-88 1910EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Oscar-Preview     04-09 0624</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Oscar-Preview,0642</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chatty Winners Will Have to Compete With Orchestra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD DE ATLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Oscar show will keep its identity as a
``little Hollywood party'' whose course will be unaffected by the
writers' strike, one of the hosts and the show's producers said
Saturday.
   The 60th Annual Academy Awards show, set for Monday on ABC-TV,
will be broadcast live from the 6,000-seat Shrine Auditorium, the
first time the Oscars have been held there since 1948.
   This year's show will feature virtually all the nominees in
person, and a script that was unfinished when members of the
Writers Guild of America went on strike March 7 against producers
and studios.
   ``You know something, people are making too much of the writers'
strike,'' Oscar co-host Chevy Chase told reporters at a news
conference in front of the Shrine Auditorium.
   ``The writers' strike doesn't affect us as much as you think.
We're really more prepared to do something that's normally
considered ad-lib. It's the nature of the show.''
   Chase told reporters that the material for the show had been
prepared long in advance and said of the Writers Guild, of which he
is a member: ``They've been good to us and we've been good to them.
It's not a big deal.''
   The show for this year ``is probably the most difficult because
we have the change of venue,'' director Marty Passetta said.
   He told reporters that among the problems he faced was the
Shrine's stage, which is 30 feet deep. At the Dorothy Chandler
Pavilion, the location for the Oscar in previous years, the stage
is 125 feet deep.
   But the cavernous Shrine will allow 19 camera positions this
year, giving the show a greater sense of action, Passetta said.
   Samuel Goldwyn Jr., producer of the show for the second
consecutive year, said the show will try to keep the focus on
movies as well as glamour.
   ``Although this has now become a world famous event, this is
still our own little Hollywood party. It's just become a very big
party,'' he said.
   The show usually lasts more than three hours and Goldwyn has
refused this year to say he will try to keep it under that.
   However, talkative winners this year will have chatty acceptance
speeches electronically overcome. A warning light will flash at
increasing speed as the allotted time wanes, and finally, the
orchestra music will be brought up slowly while the volume of the
podium microphone is turned down.
   ``And then you hear a gunshot,'' Chase joked.
   But film critic Roger Ebert, at the Shrine on assignment for the
Chicago Sun-Times, warned that the hosts rather than award
recipients could lengthen the show.
   ``This could be the comic Olympics. ... These guys have been
brought out this year because they are experienced with live
television. The problem is they're also experienced with working in
front of audiences and getting laughs and ad-libbing and it may
turn into a competition to see who's the funniest,'' he said,
noting that among the co-hosts and presenters are Chase and Eddie
Murphy.
   During the news conference, workers continued putting final
touches on the grandstand and sprucing up the front of the
auditorium. Six 24-foot Oscar statues were in place in front of the
auditorium, which has a Moorish design, complete with filigree
cornices and facade.
   Because workers were still constructing the stands, no
early-bird fans had yet taken up position to capture the most
coveted seat in Hollywood, the grandstand view of the stars'
entrance.
   ``This building looks like the Academy Award should be held
here,'' Ebert said. ``It looks like James Mason and Judy Garland
should be walking into it in a scene from `A Star is Born.'''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
