<FILEID>AP-NR-04-09-88 1933EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BoyPilot     04-09 0369</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Boy Pilot,0382</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>9-Year-Old Pilot Home After Record Cross-Country Flight</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COSTA MESA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 9-year-old California boy landed a
small plane Saturday to claim a record as the youngest pilot to fly
across the country and back, a flight of some 6,000 miles.
   Tony Aliengena flew low over John Wayne Airport in Orange County
as family, friends, reporters and photographers awaited, finally
setting the Cessna 210 down about 12:20 p.m.
   The San Juan Capistrano boy, who got his yen for flying from his
pilot father, had set out from John Wayne Airport on March 30,
accompanied by his flight instructor, Ed Fernett, and an observer
from the National Aeronautics Association, a group that verifies
flight records.
   His trip included stops in Texas; Tennessee; North Carolina;
Virginia; Massachusetts; Washington, D.C.; Indiana; Missouri;
Oklahoma; New Mexico; and Arizona.
   Tony left Phoenix on Saturday morning. When he found himself
ahead of schedule he made a brief stop in Ramona, Calif., so he
wouldn't arrive in Orange County before greeters could gather,
Fernett said.
   Tony, who fields most questions with one-word answers, said he
felt ``good'' and that the last leg wasn't difficult.
   ``It was good weather until we got to the ocean. It got
cloudy,'' he said.
   The boy said he didn't think his celebrity status had affected
his neighborhood friends and that he hasn't had enough of flying.
   ``I want to keep on flying. I want to go around the world,'' he
said.
   Tony set out to beat the record set last August by 10-year-old
Christopher Lee Marshall of Oceano, Calif., who flew from San Luis
Obispo County to Fort Lauderdale, Fla., and back to Burbank, Calif.
   Before his cross-country effort, Tony soloed in an ultra-light
airplane _ a type not regulated by the Federal Aviation
Administration _ at Oceanside Airport to claim a record for the
youngest solo flight.
   Fernett said the return trip to California was easier than the
flight east.
   ``The weather was better so that made everyone relax. We were
having fun with the trip,'' he said.
   Tony also gained experience, particularly with bad weather, that
showed on the trip home, his instructor said.
   ``He was sharper; he was more knowledgeable, relaxed,'' said
Fernett.
</TEXT>
