<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Ireland-Kennedy 1stLd-Writethru a0540 04-09 0555</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Ireland-Kennedy, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0540,0567</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Precede WEXFORD, Ireland</HEAD>
<HEAD>Kennedy Denounces British Role in Northern Ireland As He Returns
Home</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 8 grafs to UPDATE with Kennedy's return to U.S.,
remarks, transition. Pickup 4th graf pvs, bgng, `The British.' SUBS
penultimate graf to remove redundant first reference to Thatcher.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Rep. Joseph Kennedy returned Saturday from a
four-day trip overseas that included a visit to Northern Ireland,
saying his public criticism of that country was unavoidable.
   ``If you walk into that kind of situation, with the kind of
siege mentality that exists there, you can only call it what you
see. If that happens to upset people, you let the chips fall where
they may,'' the 35-year-old Massachusetts Democrat said after
landing at Logan International Airport.
   Earlier in the day, Kennedy told a cheering crowd in Wexford,
Ireland, that the British have no right to ``occupy'' Northern
Ireland.
   In response, Britain's energy secretary said Kennedy ``should
get back to Massachusetts as quickly as possible.''
   ``We had a really eye-opening trip to Northern Ireland, into the
tremendous oppression that exists in the area, into the
intimidation of Irish Catholics,'' Kennedy said in Boston.
   He said the problems of the strife-torn British province could
be solved if the British government used fair employment practices
and justice and fought discrimination.
   ``We should be electing a president who cares about the people
of Northern Ireland and who will stand up to (Prime Minister) Mrs.
(Margaret) Thatcher,'' he said when asked what Americans can do for
the Northern Irish. He didn't say who his choice for president
would be.
   Kennedy drew loud cheers when he spoke from the steps of the
Wexford Municipal Hall, near his ancestral home in southeast
Ireland, to the several hundred locals who had gathered to see him.
   ``The British have no right to occupy the north of Ireland,''
Kennedy said.
   ``The occupying forces are telling us what to do, what to eat,
who to pray to, how to think.''
   Kennedy, son of the late Sen. Robert Kennedy and nephew of
assassinated President John F. Kennedy, drew more cheers when he
said he couldn't visit the land of his roots without exploring the
problems of Northern Ireland.
   ``You wouldn't be satisfied with me if I came here simply as a
tourist,'' he said. ``We all have brothers in the north and they
need our help and support.''
   Energy Secretary Cecil Parkinson objected to Kennedy's views and
said on a British Broadcasting Corp. radio program that withdrawing
British troops would result in further bloodshed.
   ``He should get back to Massachusetts as quickly as possible and
I hope we never set eyes on him again,'' Parkinson said.
   Saturday was the second time in two days that Kennedy had
criticized Britain's role in Northern Ireland, where sectarian
violence has claimed nearly 2,700 lives since 1969.
   The mainly Roman Catholic Irish Republican Army is fighting a
guerrilla war to oust Britain from the predominantly Protestant
province and unite it with the Irish Republic.
   In Northern Ireland on Friday, Kennedy called on Mrs. Thatcher's
administration ``to change its attitude to the Irish Catholics of
this nation.''
   Kennedy also met Friday with Prime Minister Charles Haughey of
Ireland to discuss how cooperation between the U.S. and Irish
governments could help solve troubles in Northern Ireland.
</TEXT>
