<1ST_LINE>u i AM-GulfRoundup 1stLd-Writethru a0611 04-09 0501</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gulf Roundup, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0611,0512</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`War of Cities' in Iraq-Iran conflict eases</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS number of seats in parliament from 27 to 270 in 4th
graf</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ED BLANCHE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran and Iraq reported sporadic attacks
and shellings Saturday in their 7{-year-old war, but both appeared
to be observing a tacit cease-fire in their missile attacks in the
``war of the cities.''
   The official Iraqi News Agency, monitored in Nicosia, said
Iranian artillery shells hit the battered southern port city of
Basra and four other Iraqi border towns farther north, killing an
undisclosed number of civilians.
   But neither side reported firing or being hit by any long-range
missiles since Friday. The missile duel has taken hundreds of lives
in the past seven weeks.
   A military spokesman in Baghdad said Iraq had ``refrained from
bombarding'' Tehran, the Iranian capital, and other Iranian cities
Friday while Iranians went to the polls to elect a new 270-seat
Majlis, or Parliament.
   But he did not say if the Iraqi restraint would continue until
the results of the election will be known sometime next week.
   In Manama, Bahrain, a Navy spokesman announced that U.S.
warships safely escorted two reflagged Kuwaiti oil tankers out of
the Persian Gulf in the 23d such convoy this year.
   The supertanker Middletown and liquefied gas carrier Gas
Princess were escorted on the 550-mile journey from Kuwait to the
southern Strait of Hormuz by the guided missile frigates Samuel B.
Roberts and the John A. Moore.
   The spokesman said the convoy left Kuwait April 5, sailed
through the gulf without incident and passed through the Strait of
Hormuz overnight Saturday.
   Iraq's official news agency quoted the military spokesman as
saying Iraq halted its missile and air attacks on Iranian cities
``to facilitate some people of goodwill to cast their votes in the
election.''
   He said Iraq ``made the decision out of the hope that some good
and responsible people might be elected to the Majlis ... and work
toward ending the war'' in accordance with a United Nations
Security Council cease-fire resolution passed July 20.
   Some small Iranian opposition groups want a truce in the war
that began in September 1980.
   The last Iraqi missile was fired at Iran's holy city of Qom,
south of Tehran, at 6.15 a.m. Friday. Iran retaliated by firing
missiles at Baghdad and other Iraqi cities but then ceased the
attacks.
   Iranian officials have made no comment on Iraq's reports, but
they have said repeatedly Iran was only retaliating for Iraqi
attacks.
   Since the latest spasm in the ``war of the cities'' began Feb.29
when Iraqi warplanes bombed Tehran, the two sides have fired more
than 300 missiles into each other's population centers.
   Iraq reported its helicopter gunships flew 79 combat missions
Saturday against Iranian military positions along the 730-mile
front, but reported no major ground actions.
   Tehran's official Islamic Republic News Agency, also monitored
in Nicosia, reported Iranian artillery shelled Iraqi troops in
several sectors, ``inflicting heavy casualties.''
</TEXT>
