<2ND_LINE>AM-Meese, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0602,0366</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Meese Lauds Ecuador's Anti-Drug Efforts</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Meese arrives in Lima. New info-changes grafs 1-4. Pick up 3d
graf pvs: ``No country can... Edits 7th graf pvs bgng: He is
scheduled... to update.
^Precede Guayaquil</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru, (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Attorney General Edwin Meese III on
Saturday praised Ecuador's efforts to curb the flow of illegal
drugs and then flew to Lima where he met with Peruvian officials
involved in the anti-drug fight.
   After meeting privately with Interior Minister Jose Barsallo,
Meese attended a reception at the Lima residence of U.S. Ambassador
Alexander Watson.
   Meeze met earlier Saturday in Guayaquil, Ecuador, with
Ecuadorean President Leon Fabres Cordero.
   At an airport news conference before departing for Lima, Meese
said drug trafficking has threatened world security.
   ``No country can confront this scourge alone. It requires the
collaboration of all nations,'' said Meese, who is on a week-long
tour of Latin American nations to assess anti-drug trafficking
efforts.
   During his tour he has emphasized his call for a multinational
force to combat global narcotics trafficking, but Latin American
officials have not responded publicly to that suggestion.
   Meese met for more than an hour with Febres Cordero.
   The attorney general is accompanied by John Lawn, head of the
U.S. Drug Enforcement Administration. Their trip began Wednesday in
the Dominican Republic. Meese arrived in Ecuador Thursday after a
five-hour stop in Colombia.
   He is scheduled to visit a coca-leaf erradication site in Peru's
eastern jungle Sunday. The attorney general is to travel to Bolivia
the following day, where his tour will conclude Wednesday.
   U.S. officials say Ecuador's role in cocaine trafficking is less
significant than that of its Andean neighbors.
   Production of coca leaf, the raw ingredient of cocaine, is on a
minor scale in Ecuador. But in recent years international drug
smugglers have begun using this small nation, wedged between
Colombia and Peru, as a transfer shipping point.
   Peru is the world's largest grower of coca leaf. Most of its
production is partially refined and smuggled into Colombia, where
the drug is turned into pure cocaine for smuggling abroad. Bolivia
is the second biggest grower of coca leaf.
</TEXT>
