<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Soviet-Israel     04-09 0470</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Israel,0486</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gorbachev Says Rights Of Israel and Palestinians Equally Important</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev said Saturday
that Israel's security and statehood are as important in any Middle
East peace settlement as similar rights for Palestinians.
   Gorbachev made the comments during a meeting with Palestine
Liberation Organization chief Yasser Arafat, according to the
official Tass news agency.
   According to the Tass account, Gorbachev mentioned Israel's
rights several times during the meeting in the Kremlin.
   It quoted him as saying, ``The Palestinian people has the right
to self-determination in the same measure as it is ensured for the
people of Israel.''
   At another point, Gorbachev said: ``Just as recognition of the
state of Israel and its security interests, the solution of this
question (of Palestinian self-determination) is a necessary element
of the establishment of peace and good neighborliness in the region
on the basis of principles of international law.''
   But before a Middle East peace settlement can be worked out, the
Soviet leader told Arafat Israel must fulfill ``the key
precondition'' of withdrawing from Arab land it occupied in the
1967 Middle East war.
   The Soviet Union broke diplomatic relations with the Jewish
state in 1967.
   Gorbachev has said the lack of relations is not normal, but
insists Israel must withdraw from the occupied West Bank of the
Jordan River and Gaza Strip before ties can be restored.
   Arafat, who arrived in Moscow on Thursday, has said he will
accept U.N. Security Council resolutions recognizing Israel's right
to exist if Israel and the United States recognize the PLO and
endorse other U.N. measures calling for Israel's withdrawal from
the occupied territories.
   Gorbachev also told Arafat the best way to seek settlement of
the Arab-Israeli conflict is an international conference under the
auspices of the five permanent U.N. Security Council members: the
Soviet Union, United States, Britain, France and China.
   Arafat outlined his view of an international conference to
reporters after his talks with Gorbachev and Foreign Minister
Eduard A. Shevardnadze.
   ``We are favoring such a conference that would be really
efficient, active and would not be limited by any ceremonial
functions,'' Arafat told a news conference.
   U.S. Secretary of State George P. Shultz, during a five-day tour
of the Middle East last week, pushed the idea of a peace conference
that would prepare for Israeli-Arab negotiations but would exclude
the PLO.
   The conference Gorbachev envisions would be open to ``the most
diverse forms of interaction of its participants'' and would give
the permanent Security Council members the right to ``collectively
or individually table proposals and recommendations,'' according to
Tass.
   Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir has said he opposes an
international conference under U.N. auspices because he fears the
Soviet Union would tilt the forum in the Arabs' favor and make
demands that would jeoparize Israel's security.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
