<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Nixon     04-09 0245</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nixon,0249</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nixon Says His Biggest Mistake Was Not Bombing North Vietnam
Sooner</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former President Richard M. Nixon said in an
interview broadcast Saturday that his biggest mistake in office was
in not bombing and mining North Vietnam sooner.
   ``I would say the major mistake I made as president was one,
this will suprise you, was not doing early in 1969 what I did on
May 3 of 1972 and on Dec. 15 of 1972, and that was to bomb and mine
North Vietnam,'' Nixon said in an interview taped for Sunday's
``Meet the Press'' on NBC.
   ``I wanted to do it, I talked to Henry Kissinger about it, but
we were stuck with the bombing halt that we had inherited from the
Johnson administration, with Paris peace talks,'' he said. ``I knew
that, just like the cease fire talks down here in Nicaragua, I
didn't trust them at all. And they proved to be of course phony.
   ``But if we had done that then, I think we would have ended the
war in Vietnam in 1969 rather than in 1973,'' Nixon said in a
segment of the interview shown on NBC News on Saturday. ``That was
my biggest mistake as president.''
   In the hour-long interview, the former president, who resigned
in 1974 when threatened with impeachment for his role in the
Watergate scandal, also discussed presidential pardons, Attorney
General Edwin Meese III and the 1988 presidential candidates, NBC
said.
</TEXT>
