<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Soviet-Afghan     04-09 0551</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Afghan,0567</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gorbachev Says Soviets Will Join U.S. In Guaranteeing Afghan Pact</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviets will join America in guaranteeing a
settlement of the war in Afghanista, Mikhail S. Gorbachev was
quoted Saturday as saying, and he hinted a dispute over superpower
aid to rival factions has been resolved.
   The aid issue has been a key obstacle in the negotiations in
Geneva on a settlement of the war and the withdrawal of an
estimated 115,000 Soviet troops in Afghanistan.
   U.N. mediator Diego Cordovez announced Friday that agreements
were ready to be signed and U.S. sources said the signing would
take place Thursday.
   In a speech he gave in the republic of Uzbekistan on Friday but
not released until Saturday, Gorbachev did not directly refer to
the dispute over whether the Soviet Union would stop military aid
to Afghanistan's Marxist government and the United States would end
its support of Afghan rebels.
   But the Soviet leader said the Communist Party Politburo had
found ``a way (so) that the signings of the agreements by the
Afghan and Pakistani sides and the simultaneous signing of certain
documents by us and the Americans in the capacity of guarantors
could take place.''
   U.S. officials said Saturday in Washington they received a
written Soviet response to a Reagan administration proposal for the
two superpowers to continue military support of Afghan factions
after the Soviet withdrawal.
   No details were released, but the Soviets last week were
reported to have informally accepted the U.S. proposal. U.S.
Secretary of State George P. Shultz was studying the Soviet
response and was considering a trip to Geneva to attend the signing
of the accord aimed ending Soviet invovlement in Afghanistan, U.S.
officials said.
   In his speech, Gorbachev also repeated the statement that Soviet
troops would begin withdrawing from Afghanistan on May 15. He gave
the speech in the Communist Party Central Committee's chambers in
the Central Asian republic's capital of Tashkent.
   Gorbachev and Afghan leader Najib met in Tashkent on Thursday
and released a joint statement saying all obstacles to a war
settlement and Soviet troop withdrawal had been removed.
   The Soviets sent troops into Afghanistan in December 1979 to
help the government battle anti-communiust insurgents.
   Tass, the official news agency, released a text of Gorbachev's
remarks and the evening television news program Vremya broadcast
the 55-minute speech as its lead item on Saturday. Some excerpts of
the speech, which focused mainly on domestic economic issues, were
released Friday.
   Gorbachev said last-minute problems developed during the Geneva
talks.
   ``Difficulties threatening to torpedo the agreements arose at
the concluding stage,'' he said. ``This required additional
intensive efforts.'' He said the Politburo met and ``found
approaches which, as we think, provide now a possibility to
conclude this process.''
   He did not specify the difficulties, but appeared to be
referring to U.S. demands for ``symmetry'' in the cutoff of
superpower military aid.
   Shultz had proposed ending all U.S. and Soviet aid to the two
sides, but the Soviets rejected that saying their aid to
Afghanistan is a bilateral matter not subject to international
consideration. Shultz then offered the compromise, calling for
symmetrical levels of aid.
   It is not known what role the United States and Soviet Union
would play in guaranteeing the Geneva accords because texts the
agreements have not been released.
</TEXT>
