<1ST_LINE>r a AM-LovingSacrifice     04-09 0327</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Loving Sacrifice,0335</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Housekeeper Frightened Of Water Dies Trying To Save Drowning Boy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HILLSBORO BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A housekeeper who was afraid of
water and couldn't swim died after plunging into the ocean to try
to save a toddler whose grandparents had employed her for more than
20 years, officials and family members said.
   Kamilia M. Hassan, 46, helped raise the mother of 23-month-old
Daniel Kemper Smith Jr. She and the boy died after he bolted into
the ocean from a back yard that abuts the beach and she went in
after him.
   A passer-by spotted them in the ocean Thursday evening, and
visiting medical students tried to resuscitate them. But the child
died Thursday night at North Broward Medical Center, and Ms. Hassan
died there Friday morning.
   ``She couldn't swim, she knew that,'' said Jack Davis, the
child's great-uncle. ``She was really sacrificing herself.''
   Ms. Hassan, a Syrian native, had no relatives in the United
States, Davis said.
   The boy's mother, JoAnn Smith of Boca Raton, whom Ms. Hassan had
helped raise, was visiting her parents' beachfront home Thursday
when the incident occurred.
   The toddler apparently ran into the water, and Ms. Hassan
followed, panicking in the seas of 2 to 3 feet, said Hillsboro
Beach Police Chief Ralph Dunn. Officials don't know how long the
two were in the water before they were spotted.
   Both received first aid on the beach from three medical students
who had just arrived on a spring break holiday from the University
of Osteopathic Medicine and Health Sciences in Des Moines, Iowa.
   Joe Rowane said he and his fellow students, John Pargulski and
Gehred Wetzel, all 24, had been on the beach only a few minutes
when they were enlisted to try to save the woman and child. Neither
one had a pulse when pulled from the water, Rowane said.
   Funeral services for Daniel were held Saturday in Boca Raton.
Ms. Hassan's funeral was set for Sunday afternoon.
</TEXT>
