<HEAD>Guardian Angels Picket Actor Sean Penn's Mansion to Protest Gang
Movie</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Gang Violence, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MALIBU, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Guardian Angels picketed actor Sean
Penn's mansion Saturday to denounce his latest movie as a
``recruitment film'' for street gangs, but Penn and his wife, pop
star Madonna, were reportedly out of town.
   The anti-crime group, wearing their trademark red berets and
carrying signs and mock coffins, marched outside the gates of
Penn's mansion in this seaside celebrity enclave, demanding an end
to local screenings of the film ``Colors.''
   The demonstrators chanted, ``Profit from the movie `Colors' will
not profit the crying mothers.'' A toilet seat adorned with Penn's
photo was set up outside the gates.
   The movie ``pumps (gang members) up; it's better than what a
professional coach does,'' said Paul Barrera, the Angels' regional
coodinator. ``If I was a 14-, 15-year-old kid, I would say, `Wow, I
want to go out and join.'''
   Barrera claimed that up to 50 people took part in the
demonstration, but Malibu sheriff's Sgt. Bill Hutton put the number
at closer to a dozen.
   The picketing, which was peaceful, lasted about three hours,
Hutton said.
   ``The Penns are out of state,'' Hutton said. ``It's possibly
nothing more than a media event for the Guardian Angels.''
   The group planned to picket the home of director Dennis Hopper
on Sunday.
   The Guardian Angels are the latest group to criticize the movie,
which stars Penn and Robert Duvall as tough cops battling gangs on
the streets of Los Angeles.
   Although Los Angeles police acted as technical advisers on the
film, several law-enforcement officials who attended a pre-release
screening last month denounced the final product.
   They, like the Angels, said it glorifies gangs, which were
blamed for nearly 400 killings last year in Los Angeles County, and
were the target of massive police sweeps this weekend.
   ``It's a recruitment film,'' Barrera said. ``It never once
showed these guys for what they were, parasites on our community.''
