<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Israel 2ndLd-Writethru   04-09 0920</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel, 2nd Ld - Writethru,a0604,0943</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Villagers: Soldiers With Bulldozers Went On A Rampage</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 17 grafs to UPDATE with new details on shooting of
Israeli girl; pick up 8th graf pvs: Since Palestinians.... DELETES
grafs 22-28 at end of story, outdated.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KARIN LAUB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIT UMMAR, Occupied West Bank (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli soldiers rammed
bulldozers into shops, uprooted plum trees and smashed the windows
of a mosque during a rampage in this West Bank village, residents
said Saturday.
   Meanwhile, an army report quoted by television suggested that a
15-year-old Israeli girl killed during a clash last week with Arabs
on the West Bank was shot by a Jewish settler who panicked during
the confrontation.
   During a tour of Beit Ummar, this Associated Press reporter saw
dozens of metal store gates smashed and dented. One gate lay
twisted over the glass counters of a pharmacy where two old men
sat, surrounded by glass shards. The outside wall of a school was
torn down and uprooted trees lined the main road.
   An army official said the matter was under investigation. A
preliminary probe showed that villagers blocked roads with stones
and garbage containers after a violent protest Friday, the army
said.
   ``In the process of clearing the roads, damage was caused to
stairs, shops and cars that were parked along the road,'' the
official said, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   Violent clashes between Palestinians and soldiers were reported
throughout the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip Saturday. In the
West Bank city of Nablus, soldiers shot and wounded nine Arabs,
hospital officials said. Three Arabs were wounded in Gaza.
   The army said it could not immediately confirm the reports.
   An army report on the the death Wednesday of Tirza Porat
indicated that a Jewish settler inadvertently shot the 15-year-old
girl during a clash with Arab protesters near Beita, 10 miles south
of the West Bank town of Nablus, according to Israel television.
   Two Arabs also were killed in the fighting and 15 people were
injured. The girl was one of 16 Israeli teen-agers on a hike
accompanied by two armed Jewish settlers.
   Israeli television, quoting an army report, said that one of the
settlers, Romam Al Dubi, opened fire twice with his M-16 rifle,
killing a Beita resident. It said the group then walked toward the
village.
   Mosque loudspeakers in Beita alerted residents that a villager
had been killed and called on them to defend Beita against armed
settlers, the televison said.
   In the village, the mother and sister of the slain Arab struck
Al Dubi from behind with a large board, Israel television quoted
the army report as saying.
   The television account said Al Dubi panicked and apparently
fired his automatic rifle in all directions, killing another Arab.
   It said Miss Porat was struck by a bullet from Al Dubi's M-16,
according to the army report that is set to be submitted to the
Cabinet Sunday.
   Army officials previously said the girl was stoned to death by
Arabs during the clash, then said she had been struck both by a
bullet and a rock.
   Since Palestinians began violent protests against Israeli rule
in the territories in early December, 141 Arabs, one Israeli
soldier and one Israeli civilian have been killed. The army has
arrested hundreds of Arabs in a crackdown on the areas occupied by
Israel since the 1967 Middle East war.
   In Jerusalem, scores of left- and right-wing demonstrators
protested in front of the home of Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir.
Police intervened when members of three rival groups engaged in a
brief scuffle, Israel television said.
   Right-wing Jewish settlers have been staging a vigil at the site
since Miss Porat, the child of settlers, was killed Wednesday. The
settlers demand more settlements in the occupied territories and
harsher army measures against Arab protesters.
   They were joined Saturday by dozens of followers of U.S.-born
Rabbi Meir Kahane, who heads the anti-Arab Kach movement, and by
left-wing protesters chanting ``Occupation no, peace yes''
   After Friday's clash in Beit Ummar, about 13 miles south of
Jerusalem, the army closed the village to reporters.
   A Beit Ummar resident said the trouble started when dozens of
youths burned tires and threw stones at soldiers after Moslem noon
prayers Friday.
   In response, soldiers brought in two bulldozers and wreaked
havoc in the village for five hours, said the resident, who would
only give his first name, Mohammed, for fear of retaliation.
   ``They just wanted to punish us,'' said Mohammed, 21.
   He said each bulldozer was surrounded by about 50 soldiers who
pointed their submachine guns and raised riot sticks to keep away
screaming villagers.
   Mohammed pointed to the village mosque and said soldiers had
smashed its windows with their boots and sticks. The army's policy
is that soldiers should not enter mosques.
   In Nablus, the West Bank's largest city, hundreds of Arabs took
to the streets Saturday, burning tires and shouting anti-Israeli
slogans. Hospital officials said soldiers shot and wounded nine
Arabs.
   Violent protests also broke out in the Gaza Strip. Hospital
officials said an 18-year-old Arab was wounded in the chest during
clashes in the Jabaliya refugee camp.
   The hospital officials said soldiers firing rubber bullets in
the camp also hit a 60-year-old Arab man below the left eye and a
50-year-old woman in the stomach.
   In Gaza City, Arabs hoisted a Palestinian flag, outlawed by
Israel, on the city's main mosque. Soldiers fired tear gas and live
ammunition at youths who burned tires in the main roads.
</TEXT>
