<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SovietsVisit     04-09 0392</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviets Visit,0402</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviets Arrive in Chicago Suburb Looking For `Middle America'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELIZABETH SHOGREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Young ballerinas performed a Russian welcome
dance Saturday as residents of a Chicago suburb greeted four Soviet
guests who are visiting Oak Park in search of ``middle America.''
   ``Because of the special responsibility of our two nations,
because of our nuclear arsenals, citizen diplomacy must work hard
and assure the peace,'' said Irina Malikova, a political science
professor at Moscow State University.
   Ms. Malikova and three compatriots arrived in the United States
as part of a program called ``Soviets, Meet Middle America,''
sponsored by the U.S.-U.S.S.R. Initiatives, a San Francisco-based
organization.
   They are among 400 Soviets touring 240 cities in the year-long
program.
   Another Soviet group wrapped up a four-day stay in Tampa, Fla.,
Saturday and headed for the Dallas-Fort Worth area. The group also
plans to visit Mill Valley, Calif., and San Francisco during its
two-week trip before returning to the Soviet Union.
   Their American hosts took them on a tour of the city, a cruise
of Tampa Bay, to schools and universities, a day care center,
hospitals and shopping. At night they invited friends over to meet
and talk with them.
   Sponsors on both sides credit the new policy of openness under
Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev for allowing the plan that they say
would have been taboo five years ago.
   In Illinois, the Soviet visitors were welcomed by the Oak Park
Civic Ballet. Four children dressed in red satin skirts gave them
flowers and performed a special dance.
   Activities planned for the Soviets' four-day stay include
touring the home and studio of the late architect Frank Lloyd
Wright and seeing the Chicago Peace Museum, said Pat Andrews, a
village board member coordinating the visit.
   She said the visit is an attempt to help Americans and Soviets
``get to know each other, not just as newspaper headlines or `us
vs. them,' but one-to-one, people-to-people.''
   Ms. Malikova said she plans to share her impressions of the
United States with students and community groups when she returns
to Moscow.
   ``I'm assured that the Americans and the Soviets are so alike,''
she said in a telephone interview from the home of Virginia Cassin,
her Oak Park host. ``They have the same problems and the same
wishes and the same way of thinking.''
</TEXT>
