<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Obit-Benton     04-09 0255</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Benton,0262</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Singer of `Rainy Nights in Georgia' Dies at 56</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Brook Benton, whose smooth baritone produced a
string of hits in the late 1950s and 1960s as well as the 1970 hit
``Rainy Night in Georgia,'' died Saturday, a hospital official
said. He was 56.
   Benton, who lived in Queens, died at Mary Immaculate Hospital in
Queens, according to the hospital administrator, who identified
herself only as Mrs. Munson. She said the family had asked that no
further information be released.
   Benton, who started out as a gospel singer, was known for
ballads set against lush orchestral arrangements. One of his
biggest years was 1959, when he had four top 20 hits: ``It's Just a
Matter of Time,'' `So Many Ways,'' ``Endlessly'' and ``Thank You
Pretty Baby.''
   Among his later hits were ``The Boll Weevil Song,'' ``Think
Twice,'' ``Revenge,'' ``Frankie and Johnny'' and ``For My Baby.''
   In 1960, he recorded several duets with Dinah Washington, the
most popular of which were ``Baby (You've Got What it Takes)'' and
``A Rockin' Good Way.''
   ``Rainy Night in Georgia,'' a sentimental tune that took full
advantage of his sometimes mournful croon, reached No. 4 on the
Billboard pop chart.
   ``It was Benton's own idea to combine gospel intensity with lush
pop arrangements,'' according to the ``Rolling Stone Record
Guide,'' which described his singing as ``smooth and smoky.''
   ``From rock to ballads to blues, Benton never drops his easy
elegance, yet the swirling strings don't obscure his emotional
intensity,'' said the record guide.
</TEXT>
