<2ND_LINE>AM-SKorea-Police,0188</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ex-police Officer Arrested For Alleged Involvement in Sex Abuse
Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A district court on Saturday placed
under arrest a former police sergeant for alleged complicity in a
sex-abuse case involving a female dissident.
   Moon Kwi-dong was imprisoned in response to lawyers's demands
for his retrial in the complaint of a student from the state-run
Seoul National University who claimed she was sexually abused after
being arrestd in the summer of 1986.
   Court officials said Moon's retrial is expected to open next
month in Inchon, a port city west of Seoul.
   Moon had been charged in the initial trial with abusing Kwon
In-sook, 26, while she was being interrogated about anti-government
activities.
   But prosecutors dismissed the case, saying it was ``typical
false propaganda by ideolgically motivated dissidents.''
   Although the criminal prosecution against Moon was dropped, it
was suggested he leave the police force to accept moral
responsibility and he resigned.
   But the Supreme Court, acting on an appeal by Ms. Kwon, ruled in
February there was sufficient basis to her claim and ordered a
retrial.
