<HEAD>Two Children Die, One Survives Strangulation Attack</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: UPDATES throughout with details; NO PICKUP</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two children were strangled and a third
survived a similar attack in a home in northeast Washington on
Saturday afternoon, police said.
   Kristina Caine, 8, and her brother, Eric Hill Jr., 3, were
pronounced dead on the scene by the medical examiner while their
sister, 2-year-old Jennifer Hill, was taken to Children's Hospital
where she was listed in good condition, said police Capt. William
White.
   The children were found by their father when he returned home
from work about 2:15 p.m., White said, adding that the location of
the children's mother was not known.
   Police declared the mother, Padrica Hill, 27, a missing person
and said they had made finding her a top priority.
   No charges were filed in the case as of late Saturday, police
said.
   The father, Eric Hill, ran into a market near his home and
yelled, ``My kids are dead. Please help me!'' said Earl Washington,
the owner of the market.
   Washington said that when he and Hill returned to the home, they
found the son dead on the living room couch with a clothesline
around his neck.
   ``We then went upstairs to one of the bedrooms and found the
baby, the youngest child in the bed, safe, but she appeared to have
a rope mark around her neck,'' Washington said.
   The third child was found dead in the basement by paramedics and
the elder Hill.
   Eric Hill works as a teller at Citizens Bank & Trust Co., and
neighbors said Mrs. Hill recently had been hired by a Peoples Drug
Store.
