<HEAD>Hundreds Turn Out for Auction of Liberace's Belongings</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 10 grafs to UPDATE with sale ending for the day;
mirrored piano selling for more than $46,000, more than 800 bidders
participating, and CLARIFYING that cigaratte case price quoted in
8th graf pvs did not include 10 percent premium. Picks up 9th graf
pvs, `He had...'.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto upcoming</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN CALLISON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Liberace's fans came by the hundreds and bid
generously as thousands of items from the late pianist's five
lavish homes went on the auction block Saturday.
   Bidding for one of the flamboyant entertainer's Baldwin grand
pianos, almost entirely encrusted with mirrored squares, reached
$42,500; the total price paid by a London dealer, including a 10
percent premium over the bid, was $46,750.
   ``Bidding is way, way, way over our estimates,'' said Bernard
Osher, president of Butterfield & Butterfield auction house, as the
four-day auction of 2,365 items got under way at the Los Angeles
Convention Center.
   More than 800 bidders were on hand when the action began at 11
a.m. with Liberace's jewelry. Thirty-one lots of jewelry owned by
the glittery pianist were gone in a blaze of bids.
   Total transactions for the day reached $660,045, more than the
$525,650 auctioneers believed would come in.
   Arnold and Leslie Duke of Washington, D.C., bought the first
item, a pendant depicting Liberace's profile in sculpted silver
against a blue lapis lazuli background.
   It had been estimated to sell between $10 to $100. The Dukes,
who own a gem and jewelry show that tours the country, bought it
with a $3,500 bid. Including the 10 percent auctioneer's
percentage, they paid $3,850 for the pendant.
   The pendant was one of 10 jewelry lots they purchased to display
in their show, which also features items from such celebrities as
John Lennon and Cher.
   ``He was a master showman,'' Duke said. ``Not only were we fans,
but there was nobody else like him.''
   A personalized 14-karat gold cigarette case decorated with
diamonds, estimated to sell for between $3,000 to $5,000, was
bought for $8,800, including the 10 percent premium.
   ``We had hoped for a crowd this size, but we never really
believed it would happen,'' said Hillary Holland, vice president of
Christie's, the international auction house that organized the sale
with Butterfield & Butterfield.
   ``This is the most fun, festive feeling we've ever had at an
auction,'' Ms. Holland said.
   While many bidders were purchasing items as investments, others
were fans who had come to pay their respects to Liberace, who died
Feb. 4, 1987, of complications of AIDS. He was 67.
   Phylis Carroll, 51, chose to spend her 51st birthday at the
auction. She celebrated by playing a tune on each of the pianos on
display.
   ``Now I can say I tinkled the ivories on Liberace's pianos. I
don't see how you can top this,'' she said.
   Not everyone was impressed by the items, however.
   Pat Howell, one of six friends who accompanied Ms. Carroll on
her birthday trip, found most of it ``pretty garish.''
   The 263-page auction catalog does contain some unusual items,
including several slot machines; a two-piece denim, rhinestone and
sequin suit; a pair of Portuguese glazed ceramic chickens; and a
13-inch rhinestone crown.
   Proceeds of the auction will go to the non-profit Liberace
Foundation for the Performing and Creative Arts, which provides
scholarships at 28 schools and colleges nationwide.
</TEXT>
