<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Military Drinking,0185</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Base Gives Troops Day Off for Staying Off the Sauce</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HURLBURT FIELD, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A commander gave his 3,500 troops a
day off as a reward for going a full month without any arrests for
drunken driving.
   The wing was given Monday off, said Air Force Col. Dale Stovall,
commander of the 1st Special Operations Wing. It was the third day
the wing has earned off in the last nine months for having an
arrest-free record during the preceding month.
   In March 1987, eight of the unit's airmen were arrested on
drunken driving charges.
   In addition to holding out the carrot of a day off, the Air
Force also brandishes a stick against those who are caught driving
while drunk, on or off the base.
   An airman can lose base driving privileges for a year. Enlisted
men can lose a stripe and face fines of up to a month's pay.
Officers can get a letter of reprimand and extra duty.
   And, regardless of rank, an offender must undergo treatment in
an alcohol rehabilitation program, Stovall said.
</TEXT>
