<HEAD>Body of Stillborn Girl Found in Laundry From Hospital</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The body of a stillborn baby, mistakenly taken
from a hospital with the dirty laundry, will be returned for
cremation in keeping with the parents' wishes, hospital officials
said.
   A worker at the Angelica Health Care Plant in Rome found the
body Thursday among laundry received from Atlanta's West Paces
Ferry Hospital, said Floyd County Police Capt. Tommy Shiflett.
   The infant was stillborn late Wednesday or early Thursday, said
hospital spokeswoman Karen Koch. Nurses wrapped the body in
blankets and took it to the morgue, following hospital procedure,
she said.
   The body should have been tagged for cremation, but apparently
was not, said Ms. Koch. ``Someone mistook it for laundry and tossed
it into the laundry basket.''
   The infant girl's body will be returned to the hospital after
investigation by the Fulton County Medical Examiner's Office, she
said. Then, ``it will be cremated according to the parents'
wishes.''
