<HEAD>Potential Juror Fingers Defendant</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The defendant had a familiar face, the juror said.
All too familiar.
   Truett Walton was on a jury panel lined up to hear an aggravated
robbery case against Sylvester Irving, and when State District
Judge Jack Hampton asked if anyone knew the defendant, Walton
raised his hand.
   Walton said he thought Irving was the man who came up to his car
and robbed him of $400 at knifepoint on June 5, 1984. Walton worked
for an insurance company at the time and had been collecting
premiums from clients.
