<2ND_LINE>AM-Capitol-Barricade, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0695,360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Capitol Building Boss Hurt in Crash At Barricade He Ordered
Installed</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS 5th graf, bgng: White a, with 5 grafs of White comment;
minor editing</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID GOELLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police say that George White, the architect of
the Capitol, suffered minor injuries Friday when his government car
struck one of the barricades that White recommended be installed to
protect the Capitol from terrorists.
   Officer Dan Nichols of the Capitol police force said White, who
is responsible for the Capitol's buildings and grounds, was treated
by Capitol physicians, along with a driver who also received minor
injuries.
   Nichols said White's car struck the mechancial barrier at the
south entrance to the Capitol Plaza as the device, called a
``slammer,'' was being lowered to allow entry.
   ``Preliminarily, it looks like driver error,'' said Nichols,
adding that the investigation was continuing.
   White, a passenger in the back seat, disagreed with that
assessment. He said he thought the barrier had been lowered and
then rose unexpectedly, either because of a mechanical malfunction
or a barrier-keeper pushing the wrong button.
   ``We've had a couple of incidents like that,'' White said. ``My
driver's first rate. He's never had an accident. I can't imagine
him doing that.''
   White said his eyeglass frames were broken and his nose
scratched when the impact threw his head against a front-seat
headrest. He said the driver, Oscar Womack, received a cut on his
lower lip.
   He said the incident taught him that back seat passengers should
wear safety belts and that the barriers really work.
   ``They bring you to a sudden halt,'' he said.
   The front bumper of White's large black Mercury came to rest
atop the barrier. Cooling fluid was leaking from the vehicle and
the right front tire was flat.
   The hydraulic barriers, intended to prevent unauthorized
vehicles from entering the Capitol grounds, were installed last
year as part of a $13 million plan White recommended to tighten
security, according to Elliott Carroll, White's executive assistant.
   No terrorists have been reported snared by the slammers, but
last June a lowered barrier popped up as a White House car was
passing over it, leaving the vehicle stranded three feet in the air.
</TEXT>
