<2ND_LINE>AM-Gang Violence,0403</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Make Preparations for Gang Crackdown</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police set up a command post at Memorial
Coliseum and a holding tank for arrestees Friday in preparation for
a gang crackdown officials likened to the security taken for the
1984 Summer Olympics.
   Officials were tight-lipped about details of the planned sweep
Friday night through gang-terroized neighborhoods. However, Police
Chief Daryl Gates pledged last week to put 1,000 officers on the
streets to combat the gangs whose drive-by shootings have claimed
numerous lives, particularly in poor south-central neighborhoods.
   Margie Reid, a department spokesman, said she could not reveal
the specific number of officers to be deployed but acknowledged it
was the largest such operation ever carried out by the department.
   ``It is similar to the Olympics,'' Reid said, referring to the
elaborate security measures for the 1984 Summer Games in Los
Angeles.
   A command post was established at the coliseum, along with a
temporary holding facility for arrestees.
   ``Everything you could think of has to be arranged,'' Reid said.
   Gangs were blamed for 387 killings in Los Angeles County in
1987, and as many as 85 so far this year.
   Gang violence has long been a problem in Los Angeles and some
neighboring cities in Los Angeles County, and upsurges in violence
have triggered occasional outcries.
   However, local political leaders and police officials reached a
consensus for action when a recent gang shooting in the Westwood
district killed a young woman, and a drive-by shooting on Good
Friday killed one man and left a dozen other people wounded.
   The Police Department began large-scale sweeps of gang
territories using several hundred officers, and Mayor Tom Bradley
announced his next city budget would include allocations for 400
new police officers.
   In Sacramento, the state Assembly voted 48-13 on Thursday to
amend a bill to allow police to use wiretaps against suspected drug
dealers.
   There also have been calls for Gov. George Deukmejian to send
California National Guard forces to Los Angeles to help in gang
suppression, but city and county officials have made no formal
requests, said Tom Beerman, a spokesman for the governor in
Sacramento.
   On Thursday, Deukmejian suggested that it might be better to
have California Highway Patrol officers help out instead of the
National Guard, but Beerman said the governor was not making a
proposal.
</TEXT>
