<FILEID>AP-NR-04-09-88 0046EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-RailroadVerdict     04-09 0444</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Railroad Verdict,0457</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jury Awards South Dakota $200 Million In Suit Over Failed Coal
Project</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENNIS GALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SIOUX FALLS, S.D. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal jury awarded South Dakota
$200 million Friday in the state's antitrust lawsuit against Kansas
City Southern Railway Co. over the demise of a coal slurry project.
   Lawyers said the damage award would be tripled under federal
antitrust laws.
   Glen Johnson, a lawyer for the state, said the tripled damages
exceed the $500 million that the railroad listed as its net worth.
He had said during the trial that it was the largest case ever
tried in South Dakota in terms of damages.
   The jury found that Kansas City Southern conspired with other
railroads to thwart the project, in which Energy Transportation
Systems Inc., known as ETSI, would pipe crushed coal from Wyoming
to Southern states using Missouri River water that would be
purchased from South Dakota.
   Jurors also said the conspiracy resulted in restraint of trade
in the coal transportation market, hurt interstate commerce and
damaged the state of South Dakota.
   The jury deliberated 4{ days after hearing nine weeks of
testimony in U.S. District Court in Sioux Falls.
   Kansas City Southern lawyer John Shenefield called the verdict
``incorrect'' and predicted that the decision would be reversed on
appeal.
   Gov. George Mickelson said the state should not plan to spend
the award yet. ``It's not over,'' he said.
   The jury said Kansas City Southern intentionally interfered with
ETSI's contract to buy Missouri River water from South Dakota.
   The damages amount to what the state said was its loss of net
profits in the water sale contract, which was canceled after the
coal slurry project was abandoned in 1984.
   Former South Dakota Gov. Bill Janklow, who negotiated the water
sale contract with ETSI and who initiated the antitrust lawsuit,
said the tripled amount of damages is almost twice what the state
takes in every year in sales taxes.
   The state said in its suit that Kansas City Southern was
designated as the lead railroad in a conspiracy to kill the
pipeline project because it threatened to compete with hauling of
low-sulphur coal from Wyoming by rail.
   ETSI planned a $3.8 billion, 1,400-mile-long coal slurry line
but needed to cross railroad tracks and win numerous environmental
permits. The state contended that Kansas City Southern and other
railroads, which were not named in the lawsuit, teamed up to force
delays that eventually killed the project.
   Kansas City Southern's lawyers argued that the pipeline never
would have been built and would have failed if it had. The defense
admitted railroads were opposed to the project but denied any
conspiracy.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880409-0161 </DOCNO>
