<1ST_LINE>r p AM-NewYorkEndorsements 1stLd-Writethru a0673 04-09 0718</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-New York Endorsements, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0673,680</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cuomo Aide Detects Possible Move To Dukakis</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: Inserts 4 grafs after 2nd graf to UPDATE with Cuomo comments
on not caring whether leaders endorse candidates; Picks up 3rd graf
pvs bgng: While there ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARC HUMBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Mario Cuomo's message to New York
Democratic officials to get behind one of the party's three
presidential candidates may be helping Michael Dukakis more than
the other two, a Cuomo aide said Friday.
   ``After yesterday, I got a clear sense of some movement to
Dukakis,'' said John Marino, executive director of the state
Democratic Committee. ``By next Monday or Tuesday, we'll have a
much better felling for that. Maybe there'll be a bandwagon effect
(for Dukakis), but you may have a backlash reaction.''
   But the message from the governor seemed a bit ambiguous later
Friday, when Cuomo declared at a news conference that he did not
care whether Democratic leaders endorsed candidates or not.
   ``I did not offer instruction to people that they must endorse
or should endorse. Why should I? I haven't endorsed myself. I'm not
instructing or suggesting,'' the governor said.
   Cuomo also revealed that he has already voted by absentee ballot
for one of the candidates, but refused to say which one.
   And, the governor said he was in discussions with the three
candidates about making campaign appearances with them all, time
permitting. ``I'll go anywhere with them,'' he said.
   While there appeared to be some move among New York's most
influential Democrats toward the Massachusetts governor, Jesse
Jackson and Tennessee Sen. Albert Gore Jr. were also picking up
endorsements.
   Marino's comments came a day after state Democratic Chairman
Laurence Kirwan told the state committee that they should line up
behind Dukakis, Jackson or Gore.
   While Kirwan's message, direct from Cuomo, was a repeat of a
Cuomo-Kirwan missive delivered several months ago, it had new
significance because it came so close to the April 19 primary.
   The first major leader to take Kirwan's advice was Erie County
Chairman Joseph Crangle, a former state chairman, who said he would
support Dukakis. Rochester's Thomas Fink, the state committee
secretary and a close ally of Kirwan, also lined up behind Dukakis.
   Also, The New York Times reported that several other major
Democrats _ Brooklyn Democratic leader Howard Golden, New York City
Comptroller Harrison Goldin, Queens Borough President Claire
Shulman and Rep. Stephen Solarz of Brooklyn _ were expected to line
up behind Dukakis soon.
   One super delegate who wasn't quite ready to toe the line was
Suffolk County Chairman Dominic Baranello, also a former state
chairman.
   ``What are they going to do, take away my citizenship?'' said
Baranello. ``We're going to sit tight awhile.''
   While Marino was talking about a possible move to Dukakis by New
York's Democratic leaders, Jackson scored a victory Thursday when
he picked up the backing of Bronx Borough President Fernando Ferrer.
   Also, Rockland County Chairman Vincent Monte said Friday that
he, Rockland County Executive John Grant, Orange County Chairman
Ellie Habig and Sullivan County Chairman Kay Bodgen would all
endorse Gore at a Sunday night news conference.
   At the state committee meeting Thursday, Kirwan told the
Democratic leaders that one thing Cuomo didn't want was for them to
remain on the fence or to back an ``uncommitted'' slate of
prospective delegates on the New York primary ballot who want to go
to the national convention and help orchestrate a draft-Cuomo move.
   ``We can't force them (to endorse), but we can tell them in no
uncertain terms that this is what we want them to do,'' said Marino
of Kirwan's message to state party leaders. ``There is no
uncommitted option for Cuomo because there is no Cuomo candidacy.''
   ``We're not going to pay any attention to it,'' said former New
York Rep. Richard Ottinger of Kirwan's message. Ottinger said the
uncommitted delegates hoped to convince other convention delegates
to turn to Cuomo if none of the announced candidates could lock up
the nomination.
   ``We feel it's important to have our strongest candidate,'' said
the Westchester County lawyer. ``We think that's Cuomo.''
   While Cuomo has said he doesn't want to be a candidate himself,
he has refused to rule out accepting a draft for the nomination if
there's a deadlocked convention.
</TEXT>
