<1ST_LINE>r a AM-TaintedJury     04-09 0380</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Tainted Jury,0392</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Juror Sentenced, Fined for Contacting Defendant Who Left Her
Flowers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY HELEN GILLESPIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAMDEN, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former juror in a federal drug conspiracy
trial was sentenced Friday to three months in jail for writing
thank-you notes to a defendant who left flowers on her car and
telephoned her during deliberations.
   U.S. District Judge John F. Gerry also ordered the juror,
Patricia Hand, of Millville, to pay $46,850 to the government to
cover the costs of the 1987 trial.
   Five of the seven defendants were convicted, but Gerry threw out
the verdicts after learning of Mrs. Hand's contact with one
defendant.
   ``It was a cancer that she implanted on the judicial system,''
the judge said before sentencing Mrs. Hand. ``This travesty of
justice that resulted from her conduct brought the entire system
into disrepute for a short while.''
   He also ordered Mrs. Hand to serve three years' probation term
for what he called ``the indifferent folly and self-indulgence of
this woman.''
   Mrs. Hand, who pleaded guilty last June to a charge of contempt
of court, declined comment after Friday's sentencing.
   She was a juror from Feb. 11 to April 3, 1987, in the trial of
seven men charged with running a multimillion-dollar cocaine ring
in North Caldwell Township.
   Mrs. Hand testifed at a post-trial hearing that she spoke on the
telephone with defendant George Pepe twice one night when he called
her at home during deliberations. She also said she left two notes
for Pepe at a luncheonette near the courthouse after he left two
carnations on her car.
   A waitress at the luncheonette testifed that Mrs. Hand asked her
to act as go-between.
   Mrs. Hand's attorney, Howard Johnson, told Gerry his client was
a naive, innocent victim manipulated by Pepe. ``The actions of my
client were admittedly improper and in her words, stupid,'' he said.
   In the 1987 trial, the jury convicted five of the six other
defendants but did not reach a verdict on Pepe.
   Pepe, who faced a retrial, also pleaded guilty to a reduced
charge of using a telephone to advance a narcotics conspiracy.
   Gerry sentenced Pepe Friday to a two-year suspended sentence on
that charge. Pepe faces sentencing April 18 on a conviction of jury
tampering.
</TEXT>
