<2ND_LINE>AM-Cecelia-Court File,0319</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Orders Cecelia Cichan Court File Closed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The lone survivor of the nation's second worst
air disaster should be allowed to ``grow without the glare of
publicity,'' a judge said in closing the court files of 4-year-old
Cecelia Cichan.
   Washtenaw County Probate Judge John Kirkendall said Thursday
that he took the action earlier this year to protect Cecelia from
the news media. She was called the ``miracle baby'' after emerging
as the only passenger to survive the crash of Northwest Flight 255
at Detroit Metropolitan Airport on Aug. 16.
   ``Her (Cecelia's) family has now requested that ... to assure a
return to as much normalcy as can be, that documents filed in this
court be closed to the public view,' ' Kirkendall wrote in his
order.
   Kirkendall ordered the sealing Jan. 19. The action will prevent
the use of the court file to trace Cecelia, who will turn 5 on
Sunday, or any relatives named in it or to determine how the money
she received is being used.
   Kirkendall's order also closed the record of $130,000 the child
received after surviving the crash.
   The file includes accounts of legal fees and donations from
well-wishers that were mailed to the Cecelia following the crash.
   Cecelia, whose parents and 6-year-old brother were among 156
people killed in the crash, now lives near Birmingham, Ala., with
her aunt and uncle, who were named her legal guardians.
   She was released to the relatives, Rita and Frank Lumpkin, on
Oct. 9 after being hospitalized with a skull fracture, a fractured
collarbone, a broken left leg and burns over 30 percent of her body.
   She underwent four skin graft operations at the University of
Michigan Medical Center for severe burns to her arms and legs.
   The Lumpkins have refused offers to appear on television talk
shows or to give interviews.
</TEXT>
