<2ND_LINE>AM-Paraguay-Asylum,0317</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Paraguayan Opposition Leader Granted Asylum By Argentina</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELIZABETH LOVE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ASUNCION, Paraguay (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A leading opposition politician was
granted asylum Friday by Argentina after the Paraguayan government
ordered his arrest for accusing officials of involvement in drug
trafficking.
   ``Miguel Abdon Saguier presented himself in the Argentine
Embassy in Asuncion requesting diplomatic asylum, and it was
granted,'' said an Argentine Foreign Ministry communique reprinted
by Argentina's government news agency Telam.
   Saguier, 42, of the Authentic Radical Liberal Party, is a friend
of President Raul Alfonsin of Argentina.
   Patricia Saguier said her husband decided to seek asylum Friday
morning after he was accused by the government of ``seeking the
destruction of the social structure'' for saying during a March
visit to Washington that ``the Paraguayan government protects
narcotics traffickers.''
   She told The Associated Press, ``He's doing fine and the
Argentine Embassy has granted him asylum. Now they are seeking a
safe conduct.''
   After meeting last month with Elliott Abrams, the U.S. Assistant
Secretary of State for Latin American Affairs, Saguier said that
``the relation between the (Paraguayan) government with narcotics
traffickers has been proved. ... It is those within the government
who are drug traffickers.'' He did not elaborate.
   Saguier's statements were reprinted in the Asuncion newspaper La
Tarde.
   The Paraguayan government has rejected Saguier's charges and
similar ones in February by the U.S. ambassador to Paraguay, Clyde
Taylor.
   Judge Cesar Martinez on Friday ordered Saguier's arrest on a
charge of violating ``the defense of public peace and the freedom
of persons.''
   Saguier's brother, Hermes Rafael Saguier, has been in the
Colombian ambassador's residence since March 23, when he helped a
former political prisoner escape from his heavily guarded house. He
has been granted Colombian asylum.
   President Alfredo Stroessner, 74, has ruled Paraguay since 1954.
He has crushed virtually all opposition.
</TEXT>
