9. Pisello remained free on a $50,000 bond.
   Federal prosecutor Marvin Rudnick said Pisello, an alleged
associate of New York's Gambino crime family, faces up to 10 years
in prison and a $200,000 fine.
   According to evidence at trial, Pisello, who acted as an
independent record consultant, negotiated deals worth hundreds of
thousands of dollars for MCA, where he had been put in charge of
sales of discount records.
   The charges against him stemmed from a federal investigation of
abuses in the sales of ``cutout,'' or discounted, records.
   Witnesses testified that Pisello demanded cash payments for
himself in addition to checks that would be written to MCA for the
cutout records.
