<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Turner-Wildlife     04-09 0331</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Turner-Wildlife,0341</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Florida Charges Ted Turner With Wildlife Violations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL KACZOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Broadcast executive Ted Turner has been
charged with violating importing and possessing three black bears
and two cougars without a permit, officials said Friday.
   Turner, head of Turner Broadcasting Co., ordered that the
animals be brought to Florida from his South Carolina plantation
and released into the wild at Avalon Plantation, which he owns near
Capps, authorities said.
   One of the cougars was killed March 9 when a motorist struck it
near Capps, about 15 miles east of Tallahassee, said Henry Cabbage,
public information supervisor with the Florida Game and Fresh Water
Fish Commission.
   Assistant State Attorney Jim Hintz said he filed two counts of
importing non-native wild animals _ one for the black bears and one
for the western cougars _ and one count of possessing such animals.
   Turner faces a maximum penalty of $500 and 60 days in jail on
each of the three counts, if convicted. All the charges are
second-degree misdemeanors.
   Turner's secretary at Turner Broadcasting headquarters in
Atlanta said he was traveling and unavailable for comment Friday.
She said he received a mailed notice Wednesday asking him to come
to Florida, but that it did not state why.
   Hintz said Turner would be served with a summons for a May 4
arraignment.
   Turner applied for a permit last year to move the bears from
South Carolina and release them on his Florida property, but it was
denied, Cabbage said. No permit had been sought for the cougars, he
said.
   Game Commission Maj. Kyle Hill said Turner admitted he knew the
permit had been denied when he ordered the animals released.
   Cabbage said an attempt would be made to recapture the surviving
cougar, a female. The black bears, which are also found in Florida,
would be allowed to roam free because it would be impossible to
tell if a particular animal was one of Turner's, Cabbage said.
</TEXT>
