<HEAD>Drug Trafficking Threatens National Security, Baker Says</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-US-Panama Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHLEEN MACLAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   International drug trafficking such as that
in Central America represents an insidious threat to the national
security of the United States, White House Chief of Staff Howard
Baker said Friday.
   Baker made his remarks to the World Affairs Council of Northern
California the day after protesters angry about the arrest and
expulsion of a reputed drug lord torched a U.S. Embassy annex in
Honduras.
   His comments also followed testimony by two convicted drug
smugglers before a U.S. Senate committee that federal officials
were aware that smugglers flew weapons from Miami to the Nicaraguan
Contras and brought cocaine into the United States in return
flights.
   The testimony took President Reagan by surprise, Baker said,
adding that the chief executive got word of it Thursday night at
his Santa Barbara ranch.
   ``The president was in a rage when I walked into the house,'' he
said, adding that Reagan has ordered an immediate investigation and
report.
   Baker said American intelligence agents say there is growing
evidence that the Panamanian government, as well as the Colombian,
is under the influence of powerful, pervasive international drug
trafficking organizations.
   Baker declined to comment on circumstances under which the U.S.
might consider using force to oust Panamanian Gen. Manual Antonio
Noriega, who faces U.S. drug trafficking charges.
   Washington has supported efforts to remove Noriega as chief of
the 15,000-member Panamanian military and police. Noriega
orchestrated the ouster of President Eric Delvalle in February
after Delvalle tried to fire Noriega. Delvalle, recognized by the
U.S. as Panama's official leader, is in hiding in Panama.
   Baker predicted that new measures in dealing with Noriega,
military or otherwise, might be unveiled within the next few days.
   Reagan announced sweeping economic sanctions against Panama
later Friday.
</TEXT>
