<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions April 9-10</NOTE>
<HEAD>NEW YORK: for Woolworth.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   In other business and economic news this past week:
   _The nation's largest general retailers reported a sharp
increase in March sales, largely as a result of the early Easter
holiday.
   _The Commerce Depatment said manufacturing corporations'
after-tax profits averaged 4.3 cents per dollar of sales in the
October-December quarter, down almost one-fourth from the third
quarter of 1987.
   _A survey by the Conference Board said consumer confidence
dipped slightly in March amid concern about unemployment.
   _The Agriculture Department reported that foreigners continue to
own just under 1 percent of U.S. agricultural land, slightly more
than the level of a year ago.
   _The board of the New York Stock Exchange approved a proposal to
boost the capital requirements for the specialist firms that
control the rights to market Big Board stocks.
   _Texaco emerged from federal bankruptcy protection, and ended
its bitter feud with Pennzoil Co. with a series of bank
transactions that put $3 billion in a Pennzoil account.
   _Fortune magazine came out with its annual elite ranking of the
500 biggest U.S. industrial companies and found that total sales of
the group climbed 9 percent last year to a record $1.88 trillion.
   _RJR Nabisco Inc. fired one of its longtime advertising
agencies, Saatchi & Saatchi DFS Inc., apparently because the
tobacco and foods giant was upset with a no-smoking ad the agency
recently made for Northwest Airlines.
   _The Supreme Court let stand a $3 million libel award won by
cigarette maker Brown & Williamson Tobacco Corp. against CBS Inc.
and a television anchorman in Chicago. The court also agreed to
review rulings limiting Korean Air Lines' financial liability
involving the shooting down of a KAL passenger jet over Soviet
airspace.
   _Tate and Lyle PLC, a major British sugar refiner and
distributor, made a $1.33 billion cash tender offer for Staley
Continental Inc., the second largest refiner of corn sweeteners in
the United States.
   _Investors led by Britain's Brian C. Beazer extended their
$1.7-billion hostile bid for Koppers Co. until April 15, when a
federal court ruling is due on whether the offer violates
securities laws.
   _Lucky Stores Inc. has spurned American Stores Co.'s offer for a
$1.74 billion buyout and says it may undergo a major restructuring
or sell the company elsewhere.
   _MGM-UA Communications Inc., the filmmaker that was sold and
then bought back by financier Kirk Kerkorian, said it received
several takeover proposals, and plans to create a special committee
of directors to study them.
   _G.D. Searle & Co. expanded a program of giving heart disease
drugs to the poor, a move observers say puts the company at the
helm of the pharmaceutical industry's efforts to help the indigent.
   _The Food and Drug Administration gave comestic companies 30
days to stop claiming their over-the-counter creams can reverse or
retard aging of the skin.
   _Union Carbide Corp. said it would study a decision by a court
in India before deciding whether to appeal an order to pay $192
million in interim relief for victims of the 1984 Bhopal gas
disaster.
   _The Transportation Department said 74.7 percent of the flights
reported by 14 major airlines in February arrived within 15 minutes
of schedule, an increase from the 69.2 percent the previous month.
   _Eastern Airlines and Continental Airlines, two units of Texas
Air Corp., announced price cuts on tickets purchased by April 14,
although several restrictions apply.
   _A federal judge said that Eastern would no longer be in
contempt of court once it informs employees it has dropped plans to
sell its Northeast shuttle to another subsidiary of parent Texas
Air.
   _The Big Three automakers reported strong sales in late-March
and in the first quarter due to sales incentives, but import
carmakers had less uniform sales because of the impact of a weaker
dollar.
   _Leaders of Chrysler Corp.'s 49 United Auto Workers union locals
gave bargainers approval to seek a contract mirroring
job-protecting pacts with the nation's two largest automakers when
they begin talks with Chrysler April 18.
   _The Teamsters union and the trucking industry reworked a
tentative contract to shift some wage gains to pension and other
fringe benefit increases and unfreeze wages for part-time
``casual'' workers.
</TEXT>
