<1ST_LINE>a f BC-WeeklyWallStreet Adv09-10   04-09 0614</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Weekly Wall Street, Adv 09-10,0637</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 09</NOTE>
<NOTE>$adv 10</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions April 9-10</NOTE>
<HEAD>Wall Street Pinning Hopes on Dollar, Trade</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wall Street analysts are looking for good news
on the dollar and international trade to put some fresh impetus
into the stock market's early-1988 rally.
   Such sustenance could come in the week ahead, they say, from a
meeting of the so-called Group of Seven industrialized nations in
Washington, or from the Commerce Department's monthly report on the
U.S. trade balance for February.
   Advance estimates call for the trade data to show continuing
improvement from the record levels it reached last fall.
   But even when stocks rose Friday to new highs since the October
crash, the mood of many analysts and money managers remained
subdued and unenthusiastic.
   Brokerage-firm analysts complain of a shortage of ideas or
investment themes that stir up any interest among their customers.
   Stanley Berge, analyst at the firm of Tucker, Anthony & R.L. Day
Inc., describes current sentiment in the market as ``10 percent
long-term bulls, 10 percent long-term bears, and 80 percent
somewhere in the middle.''
   Much of the caution, of course, is the legacy of the crash last
fall. But some of its also may derive from memories of what
happened in the markets at this time a year ago.
   An inflation scare shot through the bond market, sending
interest rates sharply higher.
   Stock-market investors couldn't shrug that off. The Dow Jones
average of 30 industrials, after hitting a then-record high of
2,405 on April 6, fell to 2,216 by May 20.
   As it turned out, that was nothing compared to the collapse that
was coming later in the year. Still, it remains in Wall Streeters'
memories as a period in which even some big-time professional
traders got badly burned.
   It doesn't help now that bond traders are once again talking
about the possibility of Federal Reserve credit-tightening to keep
inflation at bay. Yields on long-term government bonds climbed from
about 8\ percent to the neighborhood of 8} percent in the past few
weeks.
   The atmosphere could improve, many observers believe, if the
markets keep getting encouragement from the news on the dollar and
foreign trade.
   Hopes on that score helped the Dow Jones industrial average
climb 102.13 points to a post-crash closing high of 2,090.19 in the
past week.
   The New York Stock Exchange composite index rose 5.43 to 152.03;
the NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter market 7.19 to
381.83, and the American Stock Exchange market value index 4.06 to
300.49.
   Volume on the Big Board remained subdued, however, averaging
170.89 million shares a day against 146.80 million in the
holiday-shortened previous week.
   In the view of Michael Sherman, analyst at Shearson Lehman
Hutton Inc., the stock market has fared pretty well lately given
the circumstances.
   ``The market's ability to shake off periodic plunges and to
internalize problems in the bond market is a healthy sign,'' he
argues.
   ``Since we believe that the economy is continuing to grow at a
moderate pace with further increases in profits to be expected, and
since we believe that the problems in the bond market are not
severe, we think there is still a good chance that stocks will work
significantly higher by the middle of the year.''
   One risk to this forecast, Sherman acknowledged, would be an
unpleasant surprise on the trade deficit.
   ``We expect it to continue to improve,'' he said. ``But that
remains a key variable. Although we don't anticipate a major and
continuing deterioration in the trade deficit from this level, such
an eventuality would be negative.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Weekend Editions April 9-10</NOTE>
