<FILEID>AP-NR-04-09-88 0631EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-US-JapaneseTrucks     04-09 0317</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Japanese Trucks,0324</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US Takes Major Step Toward Antidumping Duties on Japanese
Forklifts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. government ruled Friday that
Japanese-made forklift trucks are being exported to this country at
``less than fair value,'' a major step toward ordering steep
anti-dumping duties on the vehicles.
   U.S. customs will be instructed to collect anti-dumping duties
ranging from 14 to nearly 57 percent, if the U.S. International
Trade Commission determines in the next 45 days that the Japanese
imports threaten material injury to domestic industry, a Commerce
Department announcement said.
   Friday's ruling came in response to a year-old petition by an
American forklift manufacturer, the Hyster Co. of Portland, Oregon,
four of its labor unions and other employees, aimed at halting
alleged ``dumping'' of underpriced Japanese vehicles.
   ITC hearings on the dispute have been scheduled in Washington
next Wednesday, with the final ruling expected in late May on
anti-dumping duties on forklift truck imports that in 1987 reached
245 million dollars.
   U.S. law provides for anti-dumping duties on imports with an
unfair price advantage over comparable American-made products.
Unfairness is established by the degree to which the vehicles were
sold in this country at prices less than those in their home
market, said Commerce Department spokesman John Thomas.
   The department listed percentages for major Japanese forklift
makers representing both the amount of alleged underpricing and the
level of duty to be collected. They included Toyota 17.19 percent,
Nissan 51.33, Komatsu Forklift Co. 47.73, Sumitomo-Yale 51.33,
Toyo-Umpanki 51.33, Sanki Industrial 13.65 and Kasagi Forklift
56.81. All other makers would be assessed 39.5 percent.
   William H. Kilkenny, chairman of the Hyster firm, said in a
statement, ``We are encouraged that the Department of Commerce has
confirmed our view of the unfair pricing practices of Japanese lift
truck producers. We are hopeful that the International Trade
Commission will now make a similar determination that will restore
fair market conditions.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
