<1ST_LINE>d f PM-OilPrices     04-09 0295</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Oil Prices,0306</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oil Prices Fall Ahead of OPEC Meeting</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: for Saturday PMs</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As members of a special OPEC committee prepared
to meet, oil prices fell amid a market belief that significant
developments will not emerge from the session.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, contracts for May delivery
of West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark U.S. crude oil, settled
Friday at $16.88 per 42-gallon barrel, down 18 cents from
Thursday's close. Most other contract months lost 20 cents.
   Among refined products traded on the exchange, wholesale heating
oil for May delivery fell 0.27 cent a gallon to 45.46 cents, while
wholesale unleaded gasoline for May edged down 0.05 cent a gallon
to 48.77 cents.
   Analysts said oil traders don't expect the weekend meeting of
OPEC's pricing committee in Vienna, Austria, to produce a plan to
combat a world price slump.
   That feeling was reinforced by a statement Friday by Indonesia's
oil minister, who said on his arrival in Vienna that the meeting
was unlikely to produce any changes in the current oil policy of
the 13-nation Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries.
   ``We need something very significant to take us through these
(price) levels,'' said Chris McCormack, an oil futures broker for
investment firm Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. ``This meeting is not
of any consequence.''
   In addition to the Indonesian oil minister, the five-member OPEC
pricing panel is made up of ministers representing Saudi Arabia,
Nigeria, Venezuela and Algeria. They are expected to assess oil
market conditions and recommend action for the next full meeting of
the cartel, which is set for June 8.
   Last December, OPEC agreed to retain existing oil production
quotas for the individual member countries in hope of holding crude
prices at $18 a barrel.
</TEXT>
