<DOCNO> AP880409-0184 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-09-88 0704EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>d f PM-Crash-Students     04-09 0737</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Crash-Students,0760</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Black Monday Fears Have Eased Considerably, Business School
Students Say</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: for Saturday PMs</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RICK GLADSTONE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EVANSTON, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fears about a career crash in the
aftermath of Black Monday have abated at leading graduate business
schools, but many students are shying away from Wall Street in
favor of other positions ranging from consulting to property
development, delegates to an annual conference say.
   ``For me, real estate management was the way to go and it became
even more attractive after the market crash,'' said David Marino, a
24-year-old student at the University of California graduate
business school.
   Marino was one of 120 student delegates from nearly 30 of the
nation's top business schools attending the three-day conference
that began Friday at Northwestern University's J.L. Kellogg
Graduate School of Management in Evanston, a stately community on
Lake Michigan just north of Chicago.
   The theme of the conference, sponsored by Nabisco Brands Inc.,
was the outlook for the service industry. But against a background
of economic uncertainty raised by the Oct. 19 stock collapse,
career paths was an unofficial discussion topic.
   At the opening of the conference, the Kellogg school released a
survey of delegates that showed the crash generally had not
affected their career plans. The survey also showed nearly half
intend to pursue finance or consulting jobs upon graduation. Others
said they would go into high technology, advertising and
entertainment industries. A few chose careers in non-profit
businesses.
   ``I never felt threatened by the stock crash but there were a
lot of people worried,'' said James Depina, a 27-year-old
University of Michigan delegate, who has accepted a summer position
at the Bank of Boston.
   Students said many Wall Street firms, which historically have
been heavy hirers at leading business schools, still visited
campuses this year but the number of recruits had shrunk.
   ``In October there was strict panic,'' said Kelly Kay, a
28-year-old student at the University of Southern California's
graduate business school.
   ``The shock has settled somewhat,'' said Kay, but he has
accepted a health-care consulting job upon graduation.
   Others said the allure of investment banking, renowned for its
grinding hours and high pay, had faded at many schools, replaced by
management consulting and accounting careers, which also offer
lucrative starting salaries ranging from $50,000 to $100,000.
   ``Consulting is the rage now. The growth in consulting is
explosive and it pays incredibly well,'' said Dartmouth student Red
Barrett, who has accepted a position at Boston's Fidelity
Investment Management mutual fund company upon graduation.
   But Barrett, an English major who worked at a small Wall Street
firm before going to business school, expressed mild concern about
his choice, partly because Fidelity announced post-crash layoffs
earlier this year.
   ``When I looked at the headline about Fidelity I said, `Oh boy,
is this a mistake?''' Barrett said, though he noted that most of
the layoffs affected clerical staff hired during the company's
pre-crash boom.
   Conference events ranged from panel discussions by leading
members of the service industry to worshops on marketing, one of
Kellogg's biggest strengths. Delegates from Stanford University
planned to show a 20-minute video they produced on business ethics,
another emerging curriculum item in business schools in the wake of
the Ivan Boesky insider trading scandal.
   James P. Gorter, a partner at Goldman, Sachs & Co. and one of
the conference speakers, said a large number of students had
declined offers from the firm this year, although the firm's
recruiting needs had declined.
   He speculated part of the reason was the tainted image of
investment banking in general, caused partly by Boesky and
co-conspirator Dennis Levine.
   ``Some students saw the bloom was off the rose and got into
consulting,'' Gorter said. ``But I'm not sure that's the right way
to go.''
   Mark Sheridan, a 28-year-old Cornell delegate who pursued a
double engineering-business degree, said he believed a good part of
his class had pegged hopes on Wall Street careers before the crash.
   ``You see a lot of chameleons out there,'' Sheridan said.
``Suddenly they're all into consulting.''
   Some students said the crash indirectly affected their career
plans because of personal stock holdings, which declined sharply in
value.
   ``I had some equity investments financing my business-school
education,'' said Bryce Hausmann Jr., a 30-year-old delegate from
the University of Washington. Asked how he managed after the crash,
Hausmann said ``I went into the debt market. I took out a student
loan.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
